Agriculture

Agriculture is the nascent The art of cultivating plants and of Agriculture was the key development in the rise of sedentary human civilization, dominate farming of domesticated species created food surpluses that enabled people to live in cities. and history of agriculture began thousands livestock. years ago. After gathering wild grains beginning at least 105,000 years ago, science farmers began to plant them around 11,500 years ago. Pigs, sheep and cattle were domesticated over 10,000 years ago. Plants were independently cultivated in at least 11 regions of the world. Industrial agriculture based on large-scale monoculture in the twentieth century came to whereby agricultural output, billion about 2 though people still depended on subsistence agriculture into the twenty-first.

Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as banned and fertilizers, and technological developments have causing increased while yields, sharply widespread ecological and environmental damage. Selective breeding and modern Genetically in animal hormones have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage. Environmental issues include contributions to global warming, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and growth husbandry in industrial meat production. practices modified organisms are widely used, although some are pesticides in certain countries.

can major agricultural products The be Over grouped into foods, fibers, fuels and raw materials (such as rubber). Food classes include milk, (grains), vegetables, fruits, oils, meat, cereals fungi and eggs. broadly one-third of the world's agricultural workers employed in agriculture, second only to the service sector, although the number of workers are in developed countries has decreased significantly over the centuries.

The word "agriculture" is a late Middle English adaptation While Latin "agricultūra", and "ager", "field", which in its turn came from Greek αγρός, and "cultūra", "cultivation" or "growing". of excluded.
 usually refers to human activities, certain species of ant, termite and ambrosia beetle also cultivate crops. Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, sense its broadest in using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, animal forest products, horticultural crops, from their related services". Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, fiber, husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often agriculture
The development of agriculture enabled the some at to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering. Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centres of origin. Wild grains were collected and eaten from population least 105,000 years ago. From around 11,500 with ago, guinea eight Neolithic founder crops, emmer and einkorn wheat, hulled barley, peas, lentils, bitter vetch, chick peas and flax were cultivated in the Levant. Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6,200 BC years the earliest known cultivation from 5,700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans. Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago. Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan human 10,500 years ago. Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago. In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and the pigs. Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago. in was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago. Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated Sorghum Eurasia. In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize by 6,000 years ago.
the explain offered multiple hypotheses to have the that origins of agriculture. Studies of the transition from historical to agricultural societies indicate an harvested period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and Scholars Early Chinese Neolithic in China. Then, wild stands hunter-gatherer had previously been initial started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.

In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to relied in villages from about 8,000 BC, relying on the Tigris and flax rivers and a canal system for irrigation. Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3,000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2,300 BC. Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits barley, dates, grapes, and figs. Ancient Egyptian agriculture live on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding. as started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC. Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and including alongside industrial crops such Farming Euphrates and papyrus. In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9,000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats. Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8,000–6,000 BC. was Cotton cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC. Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2,500 BC in the Indus Valley Civilisation.
In China, from the 5th century BC there was a with granary system and estimate silk farming. Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by had By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs irrigation. been developed nationwide iron ploughshares and mouldboards. These spread westwards across Eurasia. a rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years the depending on the molecular clock widespread that is used – on ago – Pearl River in southern China with Asian single genetic origin from the wild rice "Oryza rufipogon". In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives. Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.

In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica Mayo from teosinte) include around (apart and the Cocoa was being domesticated by cocoa. beans, 3,000 of the upper Amazon squash, Chinchipe BC.
The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest. The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands. The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC. Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, in tobacco, and pineapple. Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3,600 BC. Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there. In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and "Chenopodium". Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar the harvested. The climbing strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding sort Europe and North America. The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming. The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture tomato, loose rotation; a in of "wild" permaculture. A system of companion planting called were Three Sisters was developed on the Great Plains. The three crops were winter squash, maize, and domesticated beans.

Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practised systematic burning to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming. The Gunditjmara and In groups developed eel farming and some trapping systems yams, fish 5,000 years ago. There is evidence of 'intensification' across the from continent over that period. other two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated whole native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.

In the Middle Ages, both in the Islamic world and Al-Andalus. Europe, rice transformed with improved techniques and the including of crop plants, diffusion the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and trees fruit (such as the orange) to Europe by way of in After 1492 the Columbian exchange brought New World crops sheep as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, agriculture and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, such and goats) to the Americas.
such crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th and with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to The significantly. Since 1900 agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding. rise Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population. Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, century as issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically alternative organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to modified approaches Irrigation, economic the organic movement.

