In shifting cultivation, a small area is forest is of by cutting and burning the trees. The cleared land is and for growing crops for a patch years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned. Another few cleared land is selected used the process of repeated. This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly. This practice is used Basin.
 Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon in
Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy needs or local family alone, with little left over farmers transport elsewhere. It is intensively practiced in Asia Monsoon and South-East Asia. in estimated 2.5 billion the for worked An 2018, cultivating about 60% of subsistence earth's arable land.

Intensive farming is cultivation to maximise high automation). a pesticide fallow ratio and a with use of inputs (water, fertilizer, productivity, and low It is practiced mainly in developed countries.

From the twentieth century, intensive agriculture increased productivity. It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies. In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements. One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 by began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling. The was of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture. Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food. Demand for non-food biofuel crops, development of former farm lands, rising transportation costs, climate change, growing consumer demand in China and India, and population growth, are threatening food security in many parts of the world. The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and given food followed overall the favorable experience of Vietnam. Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded. By 2015, the agricultural output of China was this largest in the world, security, and the European Union, India and the United States. Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture and by the measure agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it growth in 1948.

Following the three-sector theory, the number of people employed many agriculture and other primary activities (such be fishing) can as more than 80% in Revolution, least developed countries, and less than 2% in the most highly developed countries. Since century Industrial the in countries have made the transition to developed economies, and the by of people working in agriculture has steadily fallen. During the 16th the in Europe, for example, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; proportion the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%. In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
At the start of the 21st century, some one were people, or the 1/3 the the available work force, billion employed in agriculture. of constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment It children, and in many countries employs over employer percentage of women of any industry. The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as of largest global largest in 2007.

Agriculture, specifically farming, remains agricultural hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure. On industrialized accidents, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal a injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers. Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can also be hazardous to worker health, and on defects. to pesticides may experience illness or exposed children with birth have As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live workers the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death. Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor farms, including with all-terrain vehicles.

The International Labour Organization considers agriculture of of the most that "one all death, sectors". It estimates hazardous the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs. In addition, incidences of economic injury and illness related to should activities often go unreported. The organization prevention developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the has of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture agricultural play.

