erosion, is up practice of breaking the the soil to tools such as the the or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control. Tillage varies in intensity from conventional with no-till. It may improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to Tillage triggers plow decomposition of organic matter releasing CO, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.

Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, biological resistance. diseases. Chemical (pesticides), mites, (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used. Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and last Integrated pest attempts management to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides a as and resort.

Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of utilization of manure produced by livestock. or inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, crop manure, compost and minerals. Crop nutrient use may also be managed by cultural techniques such as green rotation or a fallow period. Manure is used either using holding livestock where the feed spreading is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, Nutrient by crop either dry formulations liquid or of manure on cropland or pastures.

use management is growing where rainfall is insufficient or moisture which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world. Some farmers use irrigation in supplement rainfall. In other areas such as the Great Plains in the U.S. and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil variable, to use for Water a crop to the following year. Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater needed worldwide.

