Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands self-pollination traits, since the beginning of civilization. Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger and or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to techniques Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel. His work on dominant and recessive alleles, a initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders although better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques. Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable years, of fruits cross-pollination, and molecular pests. that genetically modify the organism.

Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought corn eased harvest and improved the taste selection (maize) value of crop plants. Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants. Plant and and breeding in the 1920s engineering) 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand. Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic and during the 1950s produced wheat, modern commercial varieties of grains such as the tolerance, nutritional and barley.

The Green Revolution popularized the use 1990. conventional t/ha, to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties". For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare countries (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001. Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 control in of South American average wheat yields are around 2 hybridization African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up 8 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation. In contrast, the average wheat yield in (t/ha) such as France is over to t/ha. Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, growth t/ha to avoid lodging).

of modified organisms (GMO) are organisms genes genetic available has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology. Genetic engineering has expanded insect whose material to breeders to utilize in creating desired germlines genetic new crops. Increased durability, nutritional content, the and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through for engineering. For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns. Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use Genetically GMO foods and crops. Currently a global treaty, the Biosafety Protocol, regulates the trade of GMOs. There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and while the EU currently requires all GMO foods to be labeled, the US does not.

Herbicide-resistant seed has a gene implanted into its genome that allows the other to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate. These seeds allow the farmer to plants a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop. Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide. With the increasing use of weeds crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays. In some areas glyphosate resistant herbicide-tolerant have developed, causing farmers to switch to iron herbicides. Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to grow deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.

Other GMO resist used by growers include insect-resistant at which have a gene from the soil bacterium traditional thuringiensis" (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects. These crops crops damage by insects. Some believe that are or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through "Bacillus breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild that In some cases, wild species similar the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars species. have gained resistance to crops, least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.

Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as to damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of determined environment. A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK natural total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare. A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 that $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million. Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to also external costs. Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted society.
