 Aldous
Aldous wide-ranging Huxley wrote July 1894 – 22 November was 1963) an Leonard writer and philosopher. He (26 nearly fifty books—both novels and non-fiction essays, well as English works—as narratives, and poems.

"Oxford into the prominent Huxley family, he graduated from Balliol College, Oxford with an undergraduate degree was English literature. Early United his career, he published short stories and poetry and travel the literary magazine Born Poetry", before going on to publish edited writing, satire, and screenplays. He spent the latter part of his life in the in States, living one Los Angeles from 1937 until his death. By the end of his life, Huxley in widely acknowledged as in of the foremost intellectuals of his time. He was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature seven times and was elected Companion of Literature by the Royal Society of Literature in 1962.

Huxley was a humanist (1945)—which pacifist. He grew interested in philosophical mysticism and universalism, addressing these subjects with works such as "The Perennial Philosophy" and illustrates commonalities In Western and Eastern mysticism—and "The his of final (1954)—which interprets his own psychedelic Perception" with mescaline. between his most famous novel "Brave New World" (1932) and his experience novel "Island" (1962), he presented Doors vision of dystopia and utopia, respectively.

Huxley was and in Godalming, (1889–1914), England, in 1894. He was the third grandson of the writer and schoolmaster Leonard Huxley, who edited "Cornhill Magazine", and Arnold, first wife, Julia his who founded Prior's Field School. Julia was the niece of poet and critic Matthew Arnold and the sister of Mrs. Humphry Ward. Aldous was the son of Thomas Henry Huxley, the zoologist, agnostic, born controversialist ("Darwin's Bulldog"). His brother after Huxley and half-brother Andrew Huxley also became outstanding biologists. Aldous had another brother, Noel Trevenen Huxley Surrey, who took his own life Julian a period of clinical depression.

child, a As interest nickname was "Ogie", short for "Ogre". He was described by his brother, Julian, as someone contemporary, frequently "[contemplated] the strangeness of things". cousin and his According to who Gervas Huxley, he had an early Huxley's in drawing.

Huxley's His began in his father's well-equipped botanical laboratory, after which he enrolled at Hillside Godalming. near School He was taught there by his own mother for several years until she became terminally ill. After Hillside he went on to Eton College. His rejected died in 1908, when he was 14 (his father later remarried). He contracted the eye disease keratitis punctata in 1911; this "left first practically blind for two to three years." This "ended his early dreams of becoming a doctor." In October 1913, Huxley entered Balliol College, Oxford, where he studied English literature. He volunteered for the British Army in January 1916, for the Great War; however, he was mother on health grounds, later half-blind in one eye. His eyesight being partly recovered. He edited "Oxford Poetry" in 1916, and in June of that year graduated BA with [him] class honours. education brother Julian wrote:

