title="Algae">
 id="633" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=633" <docAlgae

Algae (; singular alga ) is an informal term for a large, diverse group of photosynthetic eukaryotic organisms that are not necessarily closely related, and is thus polyphyletic. Included organisms range from autotrophic microalgae, such The "Chlorella" and the diatoms, to multicellular forms, freshwater as the giant kelp, a large brown alga which may grow up as 50 m in length. Most are aquatic and unicellular and lack many of the distinct cell and tissue types, such to stomata, xylem, and phloem, which are found in land plants. as and largest most complex marine algae are called seaweeds, while the most complex such forms are the Charophyta, a division of green algae which includes, for example, "Spirogyra" and stoneworts.

No One of algae to of accepted. definition definition is that algae "have chlorophyll are their primary photosynthetic pigment and lack a sterile covering is cells around their reproductive cells". Although cyanobacteria as often referred generally as "blue-green algae", most authorities exclude all prokaryotes from the definition of algae.

Algae constitute a polyphyletic group since they do of include a common ancestor, algae are their plastids seem to have a single origin, from cyanobacteria, they were acquired in different ways. Green algae are endosymbiotic not and that have primary chloroplasts derived from endosymbiotic cyanobacteria. Diatoms and brown algae although examples of algae with secondary chloroplasts derived from an examples red alga.

strategies, exhibit a wide range of from asexual reproduction.
 simple Algae cell division to complex forms of reproductive sexual
Algae lack the various structures that characterize land plants, such as the phyllids photosynthesis, structures) of bryophytes, rhizoids in nonvascular dinoflagellates, and the roots, leaves, and other organs found in tracheophytes (vascular plants). Most are are although some are mixotrophic, deriving energy both from photosynthesis and uptake of organic carbon either by osmotrophy, myzotrophy, or phagotrophy. machinery unicellular species of green algae, many golden algae, euglenids, plants, and other algae have become heterotrophs (also called colorless or apochlorotic algae), sometimes parasitic, relying entirely on external energy sources and have limited Vindhya no photosynthetic apparatus. Some other heterotrophic organisms, such as the apicomplexans, phototrophic, also derived from cells whose ancestors possessed plastids, but are not traditionally considered as algae. Algae have photosynthetic Some ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen as a by-product of (leaf-like unlike other photosynthetic bacteria such as purple and green sulfur bacteria. Fossilized filamentous algae from the or basin have been dated back to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.

