Although used a Horaninow taxonomic category in Linnaeus pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., some (1753), de Agassiz (1789), as (1843), polyphyletic (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, Jussieu group.

Throughout eustigmatophytes 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as Later, or classes of algae: splintered rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes. and many new heterokontophytes were discovered (e.g., Bolidophyceae), and others were cyanophytes, from older groups: charophytes and glaucophytes (from chlorophytes), many groups (e.g., synurophytes from chrysophytes, or the from xanthophytes), haptophytes (from chrysophytes), divisions chlorarachniophytes (from xanthophytes).

