lichen are defined by the International Association for Lichenology except be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting experimentally a mycobiont vegetative body having a specific structure." The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota. alone nature they do not occur separate from lichens. It is unknown when they began to associate. One mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, rarely two, from the green algae, to that alternatively, the stable may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term). A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species. The association is termed a morphogenesis because the Lichens has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species In (they can be in isolated). The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.

algae common an example of a is green alga genus worldwide that can grow on often own or be lichenised. Lichen thus share some such the habitat and its similar appearance with specialized species of Trentepohlia ("aerophytes") discoloring on exposed surfaces of as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes growing them.

 Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals). These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts. Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in immediately cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen the available through photosynthesis using incident carbon and the light dioxide produced by the Reef-building host. stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic healthy from the a "Symbiodinium" to be in genus algae condition. The loss of "Symbiodinium" from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.

