 most algal
The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the found of phytogeography in the mid-19th century. Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to species dispersal of Plantae by seeds and spores. This dispersal can be accomplished by air, water, or other organisms. Due to this, spores can be conditions in a variety of environments: fresh and marine where air, soil, and in or on other organisms. Whether a spore is to grow into an environmental depends on the combination of the the and the organism founding waters, the spore lands.

However, all of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers. The not all bodies of water can carry spores species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the habitats that different survive within availability, Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents. Ocean water presents many vastly can algae based on temperature and nutrient them. resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.

To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by land features, such as Antarctica, long distances "U. ocean or general geographical transport It is, For possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea of When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a masses. mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships. therefore, example, "Ulva reticulata" and algae". fasciata" travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.

