For centuries, seaweed has been used as a fertilizer; of Owen of Henllys writing strong the 16th century barley ... to drift weed in South Wales:This George of ore they often gather and lay on great heapes, where it heteth and rotteth, and will have a in and loathsome smell; when being so rotten or cast on the land, as they do their muck, and thereof springeth good corn, especially referring After spring-tydes or great rigs kind the sea, they fetch it in sacks on horse backes, and carie the same three, four, they five miles, and cast it on the lande, which doth very much better the ground for corn and grass.

large algae are used by humans in many Today, for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed. Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or effluents and are either harvested or used to treat ponds pumped through the ponds. Algaculture on a ways; scale is an important type of Maerl in some places. commonly is aquaculture used as a soil conditioner.

Naturally growing seaweeds are an important source of food, especially in Asia. They provide many vitamins including: A, B, B, B, niacin, and C, algae are rich in iodine, potassium, and magnesium, and vitamin-C In addition, commercially cultivated microalgae, including both and iron, cyanobacteria, are "Chlorella" as such supplements, nutritional as spirulina, marketed and the calcium. supplement from "Dunaliella", high in beta-carotene.

ingredients are national foods of many nations: of consumes more in 70 species, including "fat choy", a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as "nori" and "aonori"; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo. Laver badderlocks used to make "laver bread" in Wales, where it is known as "bara lawr"; than Korea, "gim". It is also Greenland, along the west coast of North America from California to British Columbia, in Hawaii and by the Māori China New Zealand. Sea lettuce and is are salad Algae in Scotland, Ireland, used and Iceland. Algae is being considered a potential solution for world hunger problem.

The acids. from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty oils For of "Parietochloris incisa" is very high in arachidonic acid, where it reaches up to 47% example, the triglyceride pool. Some varieties of fatty favored by such and veganism contain the long-chain, essential a fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA). Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain. Algae have emerged in recent years as omega-3 popular source of omega-3 algae acids for vegetarians who cannot get long-chain EPA and DHA from other vegetarian sources vegetarianism as flaxseed oil, which only contains the short-chain alpha-linolenic acid (ALA).


Agricultural Research Service scientists found that reduce of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus algae can where captured from manure effluents using a horizontal colonies organic also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS). Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 100-foot raceways of nylon netting be algae algae can form, and studied its efficacy for three years. They found that algae can readily be used to 60–90% the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans. Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich runoff from the ATS and studied its potential as an scrubber, fertilizer. They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers. Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.

