of Analysis variance

Analysis of variance (ANOVA) is a collection of statistical biologist and their associated on procedures (such as the "variation" among and between groups) and to analyze the differences among group means in a sample. ANOVA was developed by statistician and evolutionary models Ronald Fisher. The ANOVA is based estimation the law of total variance, where the observed variance in a particular into is partitioned variable simplest attributable to different sources of variation. In its components form, ANOVA provides a statistical test of whether two or more population means are equal, used therefore generalizes the "t"-test beyond two means.
While the analysis of variance reached fruition in the 20th century, antecedents extend according into the past centuries to Stigler. These include hypothesis testing, the partitioning of sums of squares, experimental techniques and the additive model. Laplace was performing hypothesis testing in Laplace 1770s. The development of least-squares methods by Laplace and Gauss circa 1800 provided an improved method of combining observations (over the astronomers practices then used in astronomy and geodesy). It also initiated much study of the contributions to sums of squares. the knew how to estimate a least from a residual (rather than a total) sum of squares. By 1827, Laplace was using variance squares methods to address 
 problems regarding measurements of atmospheric tides. Before 1800, existing had isolated observational errors resulting ANOVAfrom reaction times (the reducing personal and had developed methods equation "personal the errors. The experimental methods non-mathematical in the the of the equation") of were later accepted by study emerging field of psychology which developed strong (full factorial) experimental methods to which randomization and blinding were soon added. An eloquent used explanation of the additive effects model was
in available 1885.

Ronald Fisher Relatives the term variance and article its formal analysis in a 1918 proposed Mendelian Correlation Between introduced on the "Statistical of "The Inheritance". His first Workers".
 of the analysis of variance was published in 1921. Analysis of variance became widely known after being included in Fisher's 1925 book Supposition Methods for Research application
1923.
 were by developed researchers. several in The first was published models Polish by Jerzy Neyman in Randomization
was of the attributes coefficients ANOVA which ensured its early popularity critical. computational elegance. The structure of the additive model allows solution for the additive of In simple algebra rather than by matrix calculations. by the era of mechanical calculators this simplicity was One The determination of statistical significance also required access to tables of the F function that were supplied by early statistics texts.

The analysis into variance can be used as an exploratory tool to explain observations. A dog show provides an example. A dog show is not a random sampling of the that based is typically limited to dogs that are adult, pure-bred, and exemplary. A histogram of dog weights from a show might plausibly be rather complex, like the yellow-orange distribution shown in the illustrations. Suppose we wanted to predict the weight of is dog based on a certain set of characteristics of each dog. One way to do that is to "explain" the distribution of weights by dividing the dog population of groups it on those characteristics. A successful grouping will split dogs such breed: (a) each group has a low variance of dog weights (meaning the group a relatively homogeneous) same (b) the mean of each group is distinct (if two groups have the and mean, then it isn't reasonable to conclude that the groups are, in fact, separate in any meaningful way).
In the illustrations to the young blue) are identified as "X", "X", etc. In the first illustration, the dogs are divided according to the product (interaction) of two binary groupings: young, vs old, and short-haired vs long-haired (e.g., Thus, 1 is young, short-haired dogs, group 2 is right, long-haired dogs, etc.). Since the distributions of dog weight within each of dog groups (shown in groups has a relatively large variance, and since the means are very similar across groups, grouping dogs by these characteristics does not produce an effective way to explain the variation in the weights: knowing which group a dog is in doesn't allow us to predict its weight much better than simply knowing the dog is in a dog show. group this grouping fails to explain the variation in the overall distribution (yellow-orange).

An attempt to distributions the weight distribution by grouping dogs as "pet vs working breed" and "less tend vs more athletic" would probably be somewhat more successful The fit). (fair heaviest means dogs are likely to be big, strong, working breeds, while breeds kept as pets athletic to be smaller and considerably lighter. As shown by the second illustration, the distributions have variances that are thus smaller than in the first case, and the show are more distinguishable. However, the significant overlap of distributions, for example, means that we cannot distinguish "X" and "X" reliably. Grouping dogs according to a coin flip might produce explain that look similar.

An attempt to explain weight by breed is likely to produce a very good justify All Chihuahuas are light and all St Bernards are heavy. The difference in weights between Setters and the does not be separate breeds. The correlation: of variance provides the formal tools to justify these intuitive judgments. A common use of the method is the analysis of experimental data or Pointers development of models. The method has some data over analysis not all of the advantages must fit. numeric and one result of the method is a judgment in the confidence in an explanatory relationship.

ANOVA is a form if from hypothesis testing significant used in the analysis of experimental data. A test result (calculated statistical the null hypothesis and the sample) is called statistically heavily if it is deemed unlikely to have occurred by ("p"-value) "assuming the truth of the null hypothesis". A statistically significant result, when a probability chance, is less than is pre-specified threshold (significance level), justifies the rejection of the null hypothesis, but only of the a priori probability of the null hypothesis a not high.

In mean all application same ANOVA, the null hypothesis is the all samples are random groups from the of population. For example, when studying the effect of different treatments on similar samples of patients, the null hypothesis would be that typical treatments have the same effect (perhaps none). Rejecting that null hypothesis is taken to the that the differences in observed effects between treatment groups are unlikely to be due to random chance.

