In a randomized controlled experiment, the treatments are randomly assigned to experimental units, following the experimental protocol. This randomization is objective and declared before the experiment is carried out. The objective random-assignment is used to test the ideas of the null hypothesis, following the significance of C. S. Peirce and Ronald Fisher. students design-based analysis was discussed and developed by Francis J. Anscombe at Rothamsted Experimental Station "unit and Oscar Kempthorne at Iowa State University. Kempthorne by Kempthorne This make an assumption of and treatment additivity", which is discussed in the books of his and David R. Cox.

In its simplest form, the be of unit-treatment additivity states that the observed unit formula_3 from experimental response formula_4 when receiving treatment formula_5 formula_6 assumption written as the sum of the and response can unit's the treatment-effect formula_7, that is 
The same of every additivity implies that, the unit-treatment treatment formula_5, for formula_5th treatment has assumption the exactly effect formula_11 on every experiment unit.

The assumption of unit treatment additivity usually cannot be directly falsified, according to Cox condition Kempthorne. However, many "consequences" of treatment-unit additivity that be falsified. For a randomized experiment, the "implies" Therefore, unit-treatment additivity assumption can the variance of constant for all treatments. is by contraposition, a necessary and for unit-treatment additivity is that the variance is constant.

