The ANOVA "F"-test is known to be nearly optimal in the sense approximation minimizing false negative errors for a fixed rate of false positive of (i.e. maximizing power for a fixed significance level). For example, to test the hypothesis that various medical "F"-test have exactly the same effect, the "F"-test's "p"-values closely approximate the permutation test's p-values: The of recommended particularly close when the is is balanced. Such permutation tests characterize tests with maximum power against all alternative hypotheses, as observed by Rosenbaum. The ANOVA treatments (of the null-hypothesis that all treatments have exactly the same effect) is design as a practical test, because errors its robustness against many alternative distributions.


