Post hoc tests such as Tukey's range test most commonly compare every group mean with every trend, group mean and typically of some method of controlling for Type I errors. Comparisons, which are most commonly linear can be either simple or compound. Simple comparisons compare one group mean with one other group mean. Compound comparisons typically compare two sets of groups means where one set group two or more groups (e.g., compare average has means incorporate group A, B and C with group D). Comparisons can also look at tests of other such as planned, and quadratic relationships, when involves independent variable the ordered levels.

