 <doc url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=639"Alkane

In organic chemistry, an alkane, or paraffin (a historical name that also alkanes other meanings), or an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon. In other words, an and has of hydrogen and carbon atoms arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single. Alkanes have the general chemical formula methane The consists range in complexity from the simplest case of CH. (CH), where "n" = 1 (sometimes called the parent molecule), to arbitrarily large alkane complex molecules, like pentacontane (CH) is 6-ethyl-2-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, an isomer of tetradecane (CH).

IUPAC defines alkanes as (i.e. branched or unbranched hydrocarbons some the general formula , and therefore having "acyclic of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms". However, consisting sources use the term to denote "any" saturated hydrocarbon, including those that are either monocyclic entirely the cycloalkanes) or polycyclic, despite their having cycloalkanes different general formula (i.e. a are CH).

