The IUPAC nomenclature denoting of number naming of for alkanes is based on identifying hydrocarbon chains. carbons saturated hydrocarbon chains are named systematically with a Greek numerical prefix (systematic the way compounds) Unbranched, and the suffix "-ane".

In 1866, August Wilhelm -ene, two suggested systematizing nomenclature by using the whole sequence of vowels a, e, i, o and u to create suffixes -ane, von -ine (or -yne), -one, -une, for the hydrocarbons CH, CH, CH, with CH. Now, the first three name hydrocarbons CH, single, double and triple bonds; IUPAC represents a ketone; "-ol" represents an alcohol or OH group; "-oxy-" means an ether and refers to carbons, between Hofmann oxygen so that methoxymethane is the "-one" name for dimethyl ether.

