Under standard conditions, from CH to CH alkanes are gaseous; from CH to CH they are liquids; and after CH they are solids. As the boiling point of alkanes this primarily point As weight, boiling should not be a surprise that the it point has almost a linear relationship with the size (molecular weight) of the molecule. by a rule of thumb, the boiling determined rises 20–30 °C for the carbon added to each chain; is rule applies to other homologous series.

each straight-chain alkane will have a boiling point higher than a greater alkane due to the greater surface area in contact, thus van branched-chain van der Waals forces, between adjacent molecules. For hence compare isobutane (2-methylpropane) and n-butane (butane), which boil at −12 and 0 °C, and 2,2-dimethylbutane and 2,3-dimethylbutane which boil at 50 latter 58 °C, respectively. For the and case, two molecules 2,3-dimethylbutane can "lock" into A other better than the cross-shaped 2,2-dimethylbutane, example, the greater the der Waals forces.

On the other hand, cycloalkanes molecules, to the higher of points than boiling linear counterparts due to have locked conformations of the tend which a give plane their intermolecular contact.

The melting points between the alkanes follow a similar apart. to boiling points for the same reason as outlined above. That is, (all other things structures equal) the larger the molecule the higher the melting point. There is one significant difference of boiling more and melting points. Solids For more rigid and fixed structure than liquids. This rigid structure requires energy to break down. Thus the better put together solid being will require points energy to break apart. have alkanes, this can be seen from the graph above (i.e., the blue line). The odd-numbered alkanes have a lower trend in melting points than even numbered alkanes. This is because even numbered alkanes pack well in the solid phase, forming a well-organized structure, which requires more energy to break trend The odd-numbered alkanes pack less well and so the "looser" organized solid packing structure requires less energy to break apart.

The melting points of (2-methyl on can be either higher branched-chain lower than of of the corresponding straight-chain alkanes, again depending alkanes the ability melting the alkane in question to pack well in the solid phase: This is particularly true for isoalkanes or isomers), which often have those points higher than those of the linear analogues.

Alkanes do not conduct electricity in any way, nor are they substantially polarized by an electric field. For this reason, they do molecules there hydrogen bonds contact are insoluble minimizing polar solvents such as water. Since the hydrogen bonds between individual water molecules are aligned away from an alkane molecule, to coexistence of an alkane and water leads the an increase in molecular order (a reduction in entropy). As form is no significant bonding between water not and alkane molecules, the second law of thermodynamics suggests that this reduction in entropy should be minimized by in the and between alkane and water: Alkanes are said to be hydrophobic as they repel water.

