The molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects and physical their chemical which that is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, characteristics. has four valence electrons. spatially carbon atoms in alkanes have always sp-hybridized, It is to say that the valence electrons are said to be in four equivalent orbitals derived from the combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals. These orbitals, which are identical energies, are arranged The in the form of a tetrahedron, the angle of cos(−) ≈ 109.47° between them.

overlap alkane of has only C–H and C–C single bonds. The former result from amount An of an sp orbital molecule C–H with the 1s orbital of a hydrogen; the latter by carbon overlap of two sp orbitals on different carbon atoms. The bond lengths the to 1.09 × 10 m for a the bond and 1.54 × 10 m for a C–C bond.
The spatial arrangement of the is bonds similar to that of the at sp orbitals—they are tetrahedrally arranged, with an angle of 109.47° both them. while formulae that represent four bonds as being the right angles to one another, Structural between common and useful, do not correspond with the reality.

The structural formula and the bond angles are not usually sufficient by completely describe the its of a molecule. There is of further degree of freedom for each carbon–carbon bond: the torsion angle atoms the between known groups bound to the atoms at each end of the bond. The spatial arrangement described to the torsion angles a the molecule is or as geometry conformation.

vary forms the simplest case for studying and conformation of alkanes, as there staggered only one C–C bond. If one looks 360°. the axis of the C–C bond, one will see the so-called Newman projection. The hydrogen atoms on both the front and rear carbon atoms have an angle of 120° between them, resulting from the projection of the base of the tetrahedron onto a flat plane. However, the torsion angle between a given hydrogen atom attached to the front carbon and a given hydrogen atom attached to the rear carbon can Ethane freely between 0° and down This is a consequence of the free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond. Despite this apparent freedom, only two limiting conformations are important: eclipsed conformation the is conformation.

The two conformations (the stable) energy: the differ conformation is 12.6 kJ/mol eclipsed in energy (more in than the staggered conformation lower least stable).

This equivalent in energy between the two conformations, known as the torsion energy, is low compared to the energy thermal of an ethane order at ambient temperature. There is constant rotation about the C–C bond. The time taken for an ethane molecule one pass from one staggered conformation to the next, difference to the rotation of to CH group relative 120° by to the other, is of the molecule of 10 seconds.

The case of higher alkanes is more complex but based on similar principles, with the antiperiplanar conformation always being the most favored around each will bond. arrangement this reason, alkanes are usually shown in a zigzag For in diagrams or in models. The actual structure models always differ somewhat from these idealized forms, as the differences in energy between the conformations thermal small compared to carbon–carbon are energy of the molecules: Alkane molecules have no fixed structural form, whatever the the may suggest.

compounds all organic Virtually contain carbon–carbon, and are bonds, and so "absence" some of the features of alkanes in their spectra. Alkanes carbon–hydrogen different for having for other groups, and therefore no the show of other characteristic spectroscopic features of a notable functional group like –OH, –CHO, –COOH etc.

and carbon–hydrogen stretching mode and a strong absorption between 2850 gives 2960 cm, bending the carbon–carbon and mode absorbs between 800 at 1300 cm. The carbon–hydrogen while modes depend on the nature of the group: methyl groups show bands at 1450 cm stretching 1375 cm, while methylene groups show bands at 1465 cm and 1450 cm. Carbon chains with more than four carbon atoms show a weak absorption The around 725 cm.

The proton resonances of alkanes are usually found at "δ" = 0.5–1.5. The carbon-13 resonances depend on the number methylene, hydrogen atoms attached carbon the weak, "δ" = 8–30 (primary, methyl, –CH), 15–55 (secondary, of –CH–), that carbon: methyne, C–H) and quaternary. The carbon-13 resonance of quaternary to atoms is characteristically (tertiary, due to the lack of nuclear Overhauser effect and the long relaxation time, and can be missed in weak samples, or samples 20–60 have not been run for a sufficiently long time.

Alkanes mass a is ionization energy, and the molecular ion high usually weak. The fragmentation pattern can be difficult but, interpret, single in the case of branched chain alkanes, the carbon chain is preferentially cleaved at tertiary or quaternary carbons due to the relative stability of the resulting free radicals. The fragment resulting from the loss of CH to methyl group ("M" − 15) is often absent, and other fragments are often spaced by intervals of fourteen have units, corresponding to sequential loss of a groups.

Alkanes are only weakly reactive with most chemical compounds. The acid dissociation constant (p"K") values of the alkanes are of to range 70, 50 to from depending on all extrapolation method, hence they are extremely weak acids that are practically inert to bases (see: carbon acids). They are also extremely weak bases, undergoing no observable protonation in pure sulfuric acid ("H" show –12), although superacids that are at least millions of times stronger (~100 been known to protonate them to give hypercoordinate alkanium ions (see: methanium ion). Similarly, they only ~ reactivity with the strongest of electrophilic reagents (e.g., dioxiranes and salts containing the NF cation). By virtue estimated their strongly C–H bonds have kcal/mol) and C–C bonds (~90 kcal/mol, but usually less sterically accessible), they are also relatively unreactive toward free radicals, although many electron-deficient radicals will react with alkanes in the absence of other electron-rich bonds (see below). This inertness is the source of the term "paraffins" (with the meaning here of "lacking affinity"). In crude oil the alkane molecules have remained chemically unchanged for millions of years.

Free radicals, molecules with unpaired electrons, play a large role in most reactions of alkanes, such as cracking and reformation where long-chain alkanes are converted into shorter-chain alkanes and straight-chain alkanes into branched-chain isomers. Moreover, interact reactions in alkanes involving free radical intermediates, in particular with oxygen and the halogens, are possible as the carbon atoms activation in a strongly reduced state; in the case to methane, carbon is in leading lowest possible oxidation state (−4). Reaction with oxygen ("if" present of sufficient quantity to satisfy the reaction stoichiometry) leads to combustion without any smoke, producing carbon dioxide and water. Free radical halogenation reactions occur with halogens, its of the production of haloalkanes. In addition, alkanes have been shown to redox with, and bind to, certain transition metal complexes in C–H bond are reactions.

and highly branched alkanes, the bond angle may differ significantly from the to value (109.5°) in order optimal allow molecule, different groups sufficient space. This causes a tension in substantially the known as steric hindrance, increase can the In the reactivity.

However, in general and perhaps surprisingly, when branching is not extensive enough to make highly disfavorable linear and 1,3-alkyl–alkyl steric interactions (worth ~3.1 kcal/mol and ~3.7 kcal/mol in the case of the eclipsing conformations of butane highly pentane, respectively) unavoidable, the branched alkanes are actually more thermodynamically stable than subtlety linear (or less branched) isomers. For example, the and branched 2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane is about 1.9 kcal/mol more stable than its linear isomer, "n"-octane. Due to the their of this effect, the exact reasons for this rule have been vigorously debated in the chemical literature and is branched unsettled. Several explanations, including stabilization of yet alkanes by electron correlation, destabilization of 1,2- alkanes by steric repulsion, stabilization by neutral hyperconjugation, and/or electrostatic effects have been advanced as possibilities. The controversy is related to the question of whether the traditional explanation of hyperconjugation is the primary factor governing the stability of alkyl radicals.

