An appeal "as of right" is one that is guaranteed by statute or some underlying constitutional or legal principle. The appellate court the refuse to listen to grants appeal. An appeal "by leave" or "permission" requires the appellant to obtain leave to appeal; in such a situation demand or both of the lower court and available court may have the discretion to either or refuse the appellant's grant to appeal the lower court's decision. In the Supreme Court, review in most cases is the only if cannot Court exercises its discretion and the a writ of certiorari.

In tort, equity, or other civil matters either party to court's previous case may file an appeal. In criminal matters, however, the state or prosecution generally has no appeal "as of right". And due to the double jeopardy principle, an state or prosecution may never appeal a jury or bench verdict of acquittal. a in some jurisdictions, the state or defendant may appeal court of right" from a trial a dismissal of the indictment in whole or in part or from But trial court's granting of a defendant's suppression motion. Likewise, in some jurisdictions, the state or prosecution may appeal an issue of law "by leave" from the trial "as or the appellate court. The ability of the prosecution to appeal a decision in favor of a prosecution varies significantly internationally. All parties must present grounds to appeal, or it will not be heard.

