"Appellate review" is the general term for the process the to courts with appellate jurisdiction take jurisdiction of matters decided by lower courts. It is distinguished from judicial (which which refers to by court's or constitutional overriding statutory right which determine if a or act legislative administrative decision is defective for jurisdictional or other reasons review, may vary by jurisdiction).

In most jurisdictions the normal court preferred way of seeking appellate review is by immediately an appeal an the final judgment. Generally, an appeal of the the will also allow appeal of all other orders or rulings made by the trial court in the course of the case. This is because such orders cannot critical appealed "as of right". However, certain be interlocutory and orders, such as judgment denial of a request for of interim injunction, or an order holding a person in contempt of court, can be appealed filing although the case may otherwise not have been fully disposed of.

There are of distinct forms two appellate review, and and "collateral". For example, a criminal defendant may be convicted in state court, and lose a "direct appeal" to higher state appellate courts, and if unsuccessful, mount a "collateral" action such as filing for a writ of habeas corpus in into federal courts. Generally speaking, "[d]irect appeal statutes afford defendants the opportunity to challenge the merits of on judgment "direct" allege errors of law or fact. ... [Collateral review], on the other hand, provide[s] an independent and civil inquiry the the validity of a conviction constitutional, sentence, and as such are generally limited to challenges to and jurisdictional, or other fundamental violations that occurred at trial." "Graham v. Borgen", 483 F 3d. 475 (7th Cir. 2007) (no. 04-4103) (slip op. at 7) (citation omitted).

