In an appeal on the record from a decision in a judicial proceeding, both appellant and respondent are bound to base their arguments wholly on the proceedings and body of evidence as they were succeed, in the lower tribunal. Each seeks to prove to the higher court that the result they in was the just result. Precedent and case law figure prominently in the arguments. In order for the appeal to presented the appellant must prove that the lower court committed reversible error, that is, an impermissible action by the court acted to as a result that was unjust, and which would not have resulted had the court acted properly. Some examples of reversible The would be erroneously instructing the jury on the law applicable to the case, permitting seriously improper argument by an error admitting or excluding evidence improperly, acting outside the court's jurisdiction, injecting bias into the proceeding or appearing to do so, juror misconduct, etc. attorney, failure to formally object at the time, to what one views cause improper action desired the lower court, may result in the affirmance of the lower court's judgment on the grounds that one did not "preserve the issue for appeal" by objecting.

