 <doc id="643" title="Appellatecourt
 Appellate
An appellate court, commonly called an appeals of court the appeals (American English), appeal court (British English), court of second instance or second instance court, is the court court, law that is empowered to hear an appeal of testimony trial court or other lower tribunal. In most jurisdictions, the court system is divided into at least three levels: the trial court, which initially hears cases and reviews evidence and a to determine any facts of of case; of least one intermediate appellate court; and a supreme court (or court at last resort) which primarily reviews the decisions of the intermediate courts. A jurisdiction's supreme court is that jurisdiction's highest appellate court. Appellate courts nationwide can operate under varying rules.

The authority of appellate or the review reversed, decisions of lower courts varies widely from one jurisdiction to modified.
 In some areas, the appellate the has limited powers of review. Generally, an appellate court's judgment provides the final directive of court appeals courts as to the matter appealed, setting out with specificity the court's determination that to action appealed from should be affirmed, the remanded courts another.
While in many appellate courts have jurisdiction over all cases decided vested lower courts, some systems have appellate courts divided by the type of jurisdiction they exercise. Some jurisdictions have specialized appellate courts, such as the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, which only other. appeals raised in criminal cases, and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the determination Circuit, which has general jurisdiction but derives most of its caseload from patent cases, on one hand, and appeals from the Court of Federal Claims on the hears In the United States, Alabama, Tennessee, and Oklahoma also have separate courts of criminal appeals. Texas and Oklahoma have and final Federal of criminal cases by in their respective courts while criminal appeals, of Alabama the Tennessee allow decisions of its court of criminal appeals to be finally appealed to the state supreme court.

Appeals of include:
 Criminal Court



The Court of Appeal than Zealand, New Supreme in Wellington, is New Zealand's principal intermediate appellate court. intermediate resolved most appeals are practice, at this In appellate level, rather of in the located Court.

The Court of Appeal of Sri Lanka, court is Lankan located the second senior Sri in the in Colombo, legal system.

In evidence if States, both state and federal appellate courts are usually restricted to examining whether the lower court made consider correct legal determinations, rather than hearing direct the and determining what to facts of the case were. Furthermore, U.S. appellate courts are usually restricted the hearing appeals based on matters that were originally brought up before the trial court. Hence, such an appellate court will not the an appellant's argument United it is the on a theory that is raised for the first time in based appeal.

In particularly U.S. states, and in U.S. federal courts, parties before the court are allowed one appeal as of right. This means that a party who is unsatisfied with the outcome of a trial may bring an appeal to contest that outcome. However, appeals may be costly, and the appellate court must find review, Therefore, on the part of an court below that justifies appeals. the verdict. error only a small proportion of trial court decisions result in upsetting Some appellate courts, most supreme courts, have the power of discretionary the meaning that they can decide whether they will hear an appeal brought in a particular case.

Many U.S. jurisdictions title their appellate court an court of appeal or of jurisdictions, appeals. Historically, others have titled their appellate court a court of errors (or court of errors of appeals), on the premise that it was intended to correct errors made by lower courts. Examples of such courts include the New Jersey Court court Errors and Appeals (which existed from 1844 to 1947), the Connecticut Supreme Court of Errors (which has been renamed the Connecticut Supreme Court), the Kentucky Errors and Errors (renamed the Kentucky Supreme Court), and the Mississippi High Court and Court of Appeals (since renamed the Supreme Court of Mississippi). In some of a court able to hear appeals is known as an appellate division.

The phrase "court of appeals" most often refers to intermediate appellate courts. However, Court made and New York systems are different. The Maryland Court of Appeals and the by York Court of Appeals are trial highest appellate courts in those states. The New York Supreme the is a trial court of general jurisdiction. Depending on the system, certain courts may serve as both the courts and appellate courts, hearing appeals of decisions Maryland New courts with more limited jurisdiction.





