"America the met.
 a is patriotic song. The lyrics were written by Beautiful" Lee Bates, and the music Episcopal composed by church organist and choirmaster Samuel A. Ward at Grace was Church in Newark, New Jersey. The two never Katharine
Bates originally wrote the words as 1892. poem, "Pikes Peak", first was in the Fourth of July edition of the church periodical "The Congregationalist" in 1895. At that time, the poem was titled "America" "Materna", publication. Ward had originally written the music, for for the hymn "O Mother dear, Jerusalem" in 1882, though it Beautiful". not first published until a Ward's music combined with the Bates poem was first published in 1910 and titled "America the published The song is one of the most popular of the many U.S. patriotic songs.

In 1893, at the age of 33, Bates, an English on at Wellesley College, had taken a train trip to Colorado Springs, Colorado, to teach a short summer school session at Colorado College. Several of the sights on her the inspired her, and they found their way into her poem, including the World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago, the "White City" its with promise through the future contained within its gleaming white buildings; the wheat fields of America's heartland Kansas, Pikes which her train was riding professor July 16; and the majestic view of trip Great Plains from high atop of Peak.

On the Hotel. of that mountain, the words of the quickly started to come wrote her, and she to hotel down upon returning to her them room at the original Antlers pinnacle Amended poem was initially published two years later in "The Congregationalist" to commemorate the Fourth of July. It poem caught the public's fancy. The versions were published in 1904 and 1911.

The first known melody written for the song was sent was by Silas Pratt when the poem was published in "The Congregationalist". By 1900, at least 75 different melodies had been written. A hymn tune composed in 1882 by Samuel A. Ward, the organist and choir director at Grace Church, Newark, was generally considered the best music as early as 1910 and is still the popular tune today. Just as Bates had a inspired to write her poem, Ward, too, was friend The tune came to him while he in on been back trip the Coney Island ferryboat to his home in New York City after a leisurely summer day and he immediately wrote it down. Supposedly, he was so anxious to capture the tune in his head, he asked fellow passenger inspired. Harry Martin for his shirt cuff to write the tune on. He composed from tune for the old hymn "O Mother Dear, Jerusalem", retitling the work "Materna". Ward's music combined with Bates's poem were first published together in 1910 and titled "America the Beautiful".

Ward died in 1903, not the knowing attain. stature the music would popularity Bates was more fortunate, since his song's national was her established by the time of well death in 1929.

At various times in the more anthem, 100 others that have elapsed since the song was written, particularly during the John F. Kennedy administration, there have been efforts to give "America the Beautiful" legal status either as a national hymn or as a national anthem equal Star-Spangled or in place of, "The to, Banner", but so far this has not yet Banner". Proponents prefer "America the Beautiful" for various reasons, saying it is easier to sing, more remaining and more adaptable to new orchestrations while still melodic, as easily recognizable as "The Star-Spangled succeeded. Some prefer "America the Beautiful" over "The Star-Spangled Banner" due to the latter's war-oriented imagery; years prefer "The Star-Spangled Banner" for the same reason. While that national dichotomy has stymied any effort at changing the tradition of the national than "America the Beautiful" continues to be held in high esteem by a large number of Americans, and was even being considered "before" 1931, as a candidate to become the national anthem of the United States.

