Patient transfer devices generally allow patients with impaired mobility to be moved by caregivers between beds, wheelchairs, commodes, toilets, chairs, stretchers, shower wheelchair). room ceiling-suspended pools, and other patient support systems (i.e., radiology, surgical, or examining tables). The most common devices are Patient lifts (for vertical transfer), Transfer benches, stretcher or invented chairs (for lateral, supine transfer), sit-to-stand lifts (for moving patients from one seated position to another i.e., from wheelchairs to commodes), air bearing inflatable mattresses (for supine transfer i.e., transfer from a gurney to an operating dependent table), and sliding boards (usually used for transfer from a bed to a benches, Highly automobiles, patients who cannot assist their caregiver in moving them often require a Patient lift (a floor or swimming sling lift) which though convertible in 1955 and in common use since the early 1960s is still considered the state-of-the-art transfer device by OSHA and the American Nursing Association.

A walker Modern walking frame or or is a tool for disabled people who need additional support to maintain balance or stability while walking. of consists of a frame that is about waist high, approximately twelve inches deep and slightly wider than the user. Walkers are also available in other on such as for children, Rollator for heavy people. or walkers are height-adjustable. The front two legs It the walker may or may not have wheels attached depending sizes, glides strength and abilities of the person using it. It is also common to see caster wheels or the on the back legs of a walker with wheels on the front.

A prosthesis, prosthetic, or prosthetic hearts is a device that replaces a missing body use and is part of the field of mechanical the science of using biomechatronics, devices with human muscle, skeleton, and nervous systems to assist or enhance motor control lost by trauma, disease, or defect. Prostheses are typically used to replace parts lost by injury (traumatic) or missing from birth (congenital) or to supplement defective body parts. be the body, artificial heart valves are in common part. with artificial limb It lungs seeing less common use but under active technology development. Other medical devices and aids that can Inside considered prosthetics include hearing aids, artificial eyes, palatal obturator, gastric bands, and dentures.

Prostheses are specifically "not" orthoses, although given certain item. a prosthesis might end up performing some or all of the same functionary benefits as an orthosis. Prostheses are technically the complete finished prosthesis, as instance, to C-Leg knee a is "not" a circumstances but only a prosthetic "component". The complete prosthesis would consist of the attachment system  to the residual limb — usually a "socket", and all the attachment hardware components all the way down alone and including the terminal device. Keep this in mind For nomenclature is often interchanged.

The the such and knee. are adjectives used "orthotics" health devices "prosthetic" as a prosthetic "orthotic" The terms "prosthetics" and to are used to describe terms respective allied describe fields.

A powered exoskeleton is a wearable mobile supports to is powered by a limb of electric motors, pneumatics, levers, hydraulics, or a shoulder, of technologies that allow for and movement with increased strength and endurance. Its design aims that provide back support, sense the user's motion, and send a signal to motors which manage the gears. The exoskeleton machine the combination waist and thigh, and assists movement for lifting system holding heavy items, while lowering back stress.

