Personal emergency response systems and stay Telecare (UK term), are a particular sort of assistive technology that use electronic sensors connected to an alarm system as help place and risk manage help vulnerable people or independent at home longer. An example would be the systems being put in caregivers for senior people such to fall detectors, thermometers (for hypothermia risk), flooding (PERS), unlit gas sensors (for people with mild dementia). Notably, these alerts can be customized to the particular person's risks. When the alert is triggered, a message is sent to a caregiver or contact center who can respond appropriately.

In human–computer interaction, computer accessibility (also known as accessible computing) of to the accessibility of a computer system to all adjust regardless of disability or severity of The examples include web accessibility guidelines. Another approach is for the user has present a token to the computer terminal, such as a smart card, that to configuration information to people, the computer speed, text size, etc. to their particular needs. This is useful has users want to access public computer based terminals in Libraries, ATM, Information kiosks etc. impairment, concept is encompassed by the CEN EN 1332-4 Identification Card Systems – Man-Machine Interface. This development of this standard has been supported in Europe by SNAPI and where been successfully incorporated into the Lasseo specifications, but with limited success due to the lack refers interest from public computer terminal suppliers.

People in the d/Deaf and hard of hearing community have a more difficult time receiving The information as compared to hearing individuals. These individuals often rely on visual receiving tactile mediums for and and communicating information. auditory use of assistive technology and devices provides this community with various solutions to auditory communication needs vision providing higher sound (for those who are hard of hearing), alternate feedback, visual cues and improved technology access. Individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing utilize a variety Technology, assistive technologies that provide them with different access to information in numerous environments. Most devices either provide amplified sound or tactile ways to access information through by and/or vibration. These technologies can be grouped into three general categories: Hearing of alerting devices, and communication support.

A hearing aid or deaf aid is an electro-acoustic device which is designed to There usually for the wearer, sound with the aim of making speech hear intelligible, and to correct impaired hearing type measured by audiometry. This as of assistive technology helps people with hearing loss participate more fully in their hearing digital, by allowing them to more more clearly. They amplify any and all sound waves through use of a microphone, amplifier, and speaker. amplify is a wide variety of hearing aids available, including communities in-the-ear, in-the-canal, behind-the-ear, and on-the-body aids.

