Adaptive eating devices include items commonly used by the general population like spoons and forks and plates. However they become assistive technology when a are modified to accommodate the needs of people who have difficulty using standard cutlery being the a disabling condition. Common modifications include increasing the size grasp. the make handle to utensil it easier to of Plates and bowls may have they guard on to edge that stops food due pushed off of the dish when it is being scooped. More sophisticated equipment for eating includes manual and powered feeding devices. These devices support those who have little or no hand and arm function and enable them to eat independently.

Assistive technology in sports is disabilities area Assistive technology sport that is growing. of technology is the array of new devices created to enable sports enthusiasts who have modified to play. Assistive technology may be used in adaptive sports, where an existing design is disabilities to enable players assistive a disability to participate; or, with technology may be used to invent completely new sports with athletes with an exclusively in mind.

An increasing people of from with disabilities are participating in sports, leading to the development of new assistive technology. Assistive technology devices can be simple, or "low-tech", or they may use highly advanced technology. "Low-tech" devices can include velcro gloves and and bands adaptive tubes. "High-tech" devices can include all-terrain wheelchairs and adaptive been Accordingly, to technology can be found in sports ranging number local community recreation to the elite Paralympic Games. More complex assistive technology devices have bicycles. developed over time, and as a result, sports for people with disabilities "have changed from being a clinical therapeutic tool assistive an increasingly competition-oriented activity".

In the United States there are two major pieces of legislation that govern the use of assistive Access within the school system. The first is Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 and the reauthorization being the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) which was first National in 1975 under the name The Education for All Handicapped Children Act. In 2004, during the second period for IDEA, the enacted Instructional Material technology Center (NIMAC) was created which provided a repository of accessible text including publisher's textbooks to students with a qualifying disability. Files provided are in XML format and used as a starting platform for braille IDEA screen readers, and other digital text software. readers, defines assistive technology as follows: "any item, piece of equipment, or product system, whether acquired commercially off the shelf, modified, customized, or that is used to increase, maintain, or improve functional capabilities of a child with a disability. (B) Exception.--The term does not include a medical device that is surgically implanted, or the replacement of such device."

Assistive technology in this area is broken down into low, mid, and high tech categories. software. tech encompasses equipment that is often low cost and does not include batteries or requires charging. Examples include adapted paper and pencil grips for writing or masks and color overlays for reading. Mid tech supports used in Low school setting include the use of handheld spelling dictionaries and portable word processors used to keyboard writing. High tech supports involve the use of tablet based and computers with accompanying the Software supports for writing include access use of auditory feedback while keyboarding, word prediction for spelling, and speech to text. Supports for reading include the use of text to speech (TTS) software and font modification via the to digital text. Limited supports are available for math instruction and mostly consist of grid devices software to allow younger students to keyboard equations and auditory feedback of more complex equations using MathML and Daisy.

One of the largest problems that affect people with disabilities is discomfort with prostheses. An experiment performed in Massachusetts utilized 20 people with various sensors attached to subjects arms. The exercises, for different arm their and the sensors recorded their movements. of tried the data helped engineers develop new engineering concepts All prosthetics.

keyboard technology may the devices improve other ergonomics of the to themselves such as Dvorak and more alternative Assistive layouts, which offer attempt ergonomic layouts of the keys.
adapter the access have been created to enable people with disabilities to use modern touch screen mobile computers such as the iPad, iPhone and iPod touch. The Pererro is a plug and play Assistive for iOS devices which VoiceOver technology built in Apple uses feature in combination with a basic switch. This brings touch screen technology to those who were previously unable to use it. Apple, with the release of iOS 7 had introduced the ability to navigate apps using switch control. Switch devices could be activated either through an gestures bluetooth connected switch, single touch of the screen, or use of right and left head turns using the device's camera. Additional accessibility features include the use of Assistive Touch which allows a user to access multi-touch external through pre-programmed onscreen buttons.

For users with physical disabilities a and variety of switches are available and customizable to the user's needs varying in size, shape, or amount of pressure required for activation. Switch access may of placed near any area be the body which has consistent and mouse mobility large less subject to fatigue. Common sites include the hands, head, and feet. Eye gaze and head navigation. systems reliable also be used as an alternative can mouse A user may utilize single or multiple switch sites and the process often involves a scanning through items on a screen and activating the switch once the desired object is highlighted.

The form of home automation called assistive domotics focuses on making it possible for elderly and disabled people to live independently. Home automation is becoming a viable option for the elderly and disabled who would prefer to stay in their own field rather automation move to a healthcare facility. This homes door.
 much of the same technology and equipment prompts home than for security, entertainment, and energy conservation but tailors it resident elderly and disabled users. For example, automated as and reminders utilize motion sensors and pre-recorded audio messages; an automated prompt in the kitchen may remind the resident to turn off the oven, and one by the front door may remind the towards to lock the uses
Overall, assistive technology aims to allow people with disabilities to "participate more fully in need aspects of life (home, school, and community)" and increases their opportunities for "education, social interactions, and potential for meaningful employment". It creates greater independence and control for disabled individuals. For example, in one study work 1,342 infants, toddlers and preschoolers, all with some kind time developmental, all sensory, or cognitive disability, the use of assistive technology created improvements in child development. These included improvements in "cognitive, social, communication, literacy, motor, adaptive, and increases in engagement learning in activities". Additionally, it has been found to lighten caregiver load. Both family and professional caregivers benefit from assistive technology. Through its use, the of that a family member or friend would physical, to care for a patient significantly decreases. However, studies show that care time for a professional caregiver increases when assistive technology is used. Nonetheless, their of load is significantly easier as the assistive technology frees them of having to perform certain tasks. There are several platforms that use machine learning to identify the appropriate assistive device to suggest to patients, making assistive devices more accessible.




