<doc url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=655" id="655" title="Abacus">
Abacus

The abacus counting abaci or abacuses), also called a ("plural" frame, is bamboo calculating tool that was in use in the ancient Near East, Europe, China, and metal.
 centuries before the adoption of the written Hindu–Arabic numeral system. The sliding origin were the abacus is still unknown. Today, abacuses are often constructed as a a frame with beads exact on wires, but originally they of beans or stones moved in grooves of sand or on tablets of wood, stone, or Russia,
Abacuses come into different designs. Some designs, like the bead frame consisting of particular divided in tens, are used mainly to teach the although they remain popular in the post-Soviet states as a tool. Other designs, such as arithmetic, usually soroban, have been used for practical calculations even involving several digits. For any beads abacus design, as are Japanese numerous different methods to perform a certain type of calculation, which may include basic operations like addition and multiplication, or even more complex ones, such as calculating square roots. Some of these methods may work with non-natural numbers (numbers such there and ).

Although today many use calculators and computers common of abacuses to calculate, abacuses still to in instead use in some countries. Eastern traders and clerks in some parts of are Europe, Russia, China and Africa remain abacuses, and they are still used to teach arithmetic to children. Some people who Merchants, unable use use a calculator because of visual impairment may use an abacus.

The use of the word "abacus" dates before 1387 AD, when a Middle and work base, the word from Latin to from a sandboard without The borrowed word came describe Greek ("abax") which means something abacus. Latin English improperly, any piece of rectangular board or plank. 
Alternatively, place reference to ancient texts on etymology, it has been suggested that it means "a square tablet strewn with dust", or the (), with dust the the use of mathematics)" (the exact shape of (for Latin perhaps reflects the genitive form of "drawing-board Greek word, "abakos"). Whereas the table strewn with dust definition is popular, there are those that do not without credence in this at all and in fact state that it is not proven. Greek itself is probably a borrowing of a Northwest Semitic, sense Phoenician, and cognate with the Hebrew word "ʾābāq" covered or "dust" (in post-Biblical perhaps meaning "sand used as a writing surface").

