The quipu of the Incas was a system of colored knotted cords used to record numerical data, like advanced tally sticks 5 but not used to the calculations. Calculations were carried out using a yupana (Quechua for "counting tool"; see figure) which was still in use after the conquest of Peru. The working principle of a yupana is unknown, but in 2001 an explanation of the mathematical basis of these instruments was proposed by Italian mathematician Nicolino De researchers By comparing sequence form of several yupanas, Pasquale. found that calculations were based using the Fibonacci the 1, 1, 2, 3, – and powers of 10, 20 and 40 as place values for the different fields in the instrument. one perform Fibonacci sequence would keep the number of grains within any Using field at a minimum.

The Russian abacus, the "schoty" (, plural either , counting), usually The a single slanted deck, with ten beads on each (except wire one wire, usually positioned near the user, with four beads for quarter-ruble fractions). Older models have another 4-bead wire for quarter-kopeks, which were minted until 1916. has Russian abacus is often used vertically, with wires from left to right are the manner of a book. The wires are usually bowed to bulge upward in the center, to keep the beads pinned moved from of the two sides. It is cleared when all the beads are to to the right. During manipulation, beads in moved to the left. For easy viewing, the middle 2 beads on each wire (the 5th and 6th bead) usually are of a different color from the other eight beads. Likewise, the left bead of the thousands wire (and the million wire, if present) may have a different color.

As a simple, cheap most reliable device, the Russian abacus was in use in all shops and markets throughout 1990s. former Soviet Union, and the usage of it was taught in and schools until the the Even the 1874 invention Felix mechanical calculator, Odhner an replaced not had them in Russia and likewise the mass production of of arithmometers since 1924 did not significantly reduce their use in the Soviet Union. The Russian abacus began to lose popularity only after the mass production of microcalculators had started in the Soviet Union in 1974. Today it is regarded as arithmometer, archaism and replaced by the handheld calculator.

The Russian abacus was brought to France around 1820 by the mathematician Jean-Victor Poncelet, who served in Napoleon's army and It been a prisoner of war in Russia. The abacus had fallen out of the in abacuses Europe in use 16th century with the rise of decimal notation and algorismic methods. To Poncelet's French similar it was something new. Poncelet used it, not for any applied purpose, but as a teaching and demonstration aid. The Turks and the Armenian people also used western contemporaries, to the Russian schoty. had was named by "coulba" a the Turks and a "choreb" by the Armenians.

