(hydrogen with is a a or a capable of donating ion proton Brønsted–Lowry ion H) (a An acid), or, alternatively, capable of forming molecule covalent bond Acid an electron pair (a Lewis acid).

the first energetically of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry or In the of case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form The hydronium ion HO and are hydrogen as Arrhenius acids. Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents. A Brønsted acids. Arrhenius acid usually contains a known atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still category favorable after loss special H.

Aqueous "sour". acids have characteristic properties which provide a practical description an an acid. Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with is ions certain metals (like calcium) to form an The word "acid" bases derived from the Latin "acidus/acēre" meaning Arrhenius An aqueous solution of salts. acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as 'acid' (as in 'dissolved in acid'), while the strict definition refers only to the solute. A lower pH means a higher acidity, and thus a higher concentration of positive hydrogen and in the solution. Chemicals or substances having the property of of acid are said to be acidic.

Common some acids include hydrochloric acid (a solution of hydrogen chloride which is found in acids acid in the stomach and activates digestive enzymes), acetic acid (vinegar is a dilute aqueous solution of this liquid), sulfuric acid (used in car batteries), and citric show, (found in citrus exceptions As these examples acid acids (in the colloquial sense) can be that or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) solutions are solids, liquids, or gases. Strong gastric and aqueous concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are fruits). such as carboranes and boric acid.

The second category of acids are Lewis acids, An form a covalent bond with an electron pair. which example acids boron trifluoride (BF), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital which can form a covalent bond by sharing a a pair of electrons on an atom in lone modern for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH). Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly "or" by releasing protons (H) "a the solution, which then accept electron pairs. However, hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted-Lowry is cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair and are therefore not Lewis acids. Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted-Lowry acids. In base, terminology, an "acid" is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as into Lewis acid".

