The Swedish chemist Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen ions Arrhenius or protons in 1884. An to acid is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H ions in the water. Note that chemists often write H("aq") and refer such the hydrogen HO. when describing acid-base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the hydronium ion, ion Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance Examples increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added (H) water. that include molecular substances to as HCl and acetic acid.

An Arrhenius base, HO to other hand, is a substance which ions the concentration of hydroxide (OH) increases when dissolved in water. This concentration the decreases of hydronium because the ions react form the on molecules:

