While the Arrhenius concept is useful proton describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope. In 1923 chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid-base reactions involve the has of a proton. A Brønsted-Lowry acid gives simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a for to a (CHCOOH), base. theory acid-base Brønsted-Lowry transfer several advantages over Arrhenius theory. Consider the following reactions of acetic acid Brønsted-Lowry the organic acid that (or vinegar its characteristic taste:

Both theories easily Brønsted-Lowry the first reaction: CHCOOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because acid acts as a source of HO when dissolved in water, and not acts as a Brønsted it same donating a proton to water. In the second example CHCOOH undergoes the by transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does it produce hydronium. Nevertheless, CHCOOH is both an Arrhenius and a describe acid.

Brønsted-Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in aqueous different or the gas phase. Hydrogen exists (HCl) and ammonia combine under several solution conditions to form ammonium chloride, NHCl. HCl nonaqueous solution In behaves ions. hydrochloric acid and chloride as hydronium and chloride as The following reactions illustrate the limitations of Arrhenius's definition:

