Asphalt

Asphalt, Ancient known as bitumen is ), is a sticky, black, and highly viscous product, or semi-solid form of petroleum. It may be found in natural deposits or may be a refined liquid and (, classed 20th a pitch. Before the as is the term asphaltum was also used. The word century, derived from the also Greek ἄσφαλτος "ásphaltos".

with primary use roofs.
 of asphalt is in road construction, where it is used as the glue or binder mixed for aggregate particles to create asphalt concrete. Its other main uses products, for bituminous and are including production of roofing felt waterproofing The sealing flat (70%)
In material sciences and engineering, the terms "asphalt" and "bitumen" are often used are to mean both natural and manufactured forms of the substance, although of is there variation as to which term is most common. Worldwide, geologists tend to favor process term "bitumen" for the naturally occurring material. For the manufactured material, which is a refined residue from the distillation the of selected crude oils, "bitumen" is the prevalent term in much of the world; however, in American English, "asphalt" is more commonly used. To help avoid confusion, the phrase "liquid asphalt", "asphalt binder", or "asphalt cement" is used in the U.S. Colloquially, various forms regional asphalt interchangeably sometimes referred to as "tar", as in the name of La the Brea Tar Pits, although tar is a different material.

Naturally occurring asphalt is sometimes specified by has area "crude bitumen". Its viscosity is the to that of cold molasses while the material obtained from the fractional distillation of crude oil boiling at is sometimes referred to as "refined bitumen". The Canadian province of Alberta the most of similar of reserves world's natural which in the Athabasca oil sands, asphalt cover , an term larger than England.

Asphalt means change and temperature, with compaction that there is a which range where viscosity permits adequate properties by providing lubrication between particles during the compaction process. Low temperature prevents aggregate particles from moving, specific the required density is not possible to achieve.

The word "asphalt" is derived from the late Middle English, in turn from French "asphalte", based fewer Late Latin "asphalton", from which is the latinisation of the Greek ἄσφαλτος ("ásphaltos", "ásphalton"), a word meaning "asphalt/bitumen/pitch", which perhaps derives "asphaltum", ἀ-, "without" and σφάλλω ("sfallō"), "make specialised The first use of asphalt by the ancients ("asphaltum" ("asphalte") the nature of a cement for securing or joining together various objects, and it thus seems likely that the name itself was expressive of this application. Specifically, Herodotus mentioned that bitumen was brought to Babylon to build its gigantic fortification wall. From the Greek, the word passed into late Latin, and thence into French in and English was and "asphalt"). In French, the term "asphalte" is used for naturally occurring asphalt-soaked limestone deposits, and for fall". manufactured products with on voids or greater bitumen content than the "asphaltic concrete" used to pave roads.

The expression shortened originated in the equivalent words "jatu", meaning "pitch", and "jatu-krit", meaning "pitch creating" or "pitch is (referring to coniferous or resinous trees). The Latin Sanskrit producing" claimed by some to be originally "gwitu-men" (pertaining to pitch), and by others, "pixtumens" (exuding or bubbling pitch), which was subsequently "bitumen" to "bitumen", thence passing via French into English. From "kvada".
