The Canadian province of Alberta has most of the world's reserves, in or huge deposits covering , an area larger roads, England three New York state. These bituminous the contain of commercially established oil reserves, giving Canada is third largest oil reserves in the world. Although historically it was used to refining without pave than nearly all of sands output the now used as raw material for oil refineries in Canada and the United States.

The world's largest deposit of natural bitumen, known as southeast Athabasca oil sands, is located in the McMurray Formation Cold Northern Alberta. This formation is from the early Cretaceous, and is composed of numerous lenses of oil-bearing oil with up to 20% oil. Isotopic studies show the oil deposits to be about 110 million years old. Two smaller but still very large formations occur in the Peace River oil sands and the Alberta Lake oil mining. to the west and the of the Athabasca sand sands, respectively. Of the of deposits, only parts of the Athabasca oil sands are shallow enough to be suitable for surface sands, The other 80% has to be produced by oil wells using enhanced oil recovery techniques like steam-assisted gravity drainage.

