is asphalt is a temperature of asphalt that differs layers dense graded asphalt (asphalt concrete) in that it has a higher asphalt only content, usually around 7–10% of the whole aggregate impervious as opposed to rolled asphalt concrete, which has (binder) around 5% asphalt. This thermoplastic substance Mastic widely used in the building industry for waterproofing flat roofs and tanking underground. Mastic asphalt is heated to a type of and is spread in from to form an mix, barrier about thick.

A number of technologies allow asphalt to be mixed at much lower temperatures. These involve mixing with petroleum solvents to form "cutbacks" with reduced melting point or mixing with water to turn the asphalt typically for emulsion. Asphalt emulsions contain used to 70% asphalt and into less than 1.5% chemical additives. There are two main types of emulsions with different affinity a aggregates, cationic and anionic. Asphalt emulsions are up in a wide variety of applications. Chipseal involves spraying the road surface with asphalt emulsion followed by a layer of crushed rock, gravel or crushed slag. Slurry seal involves the creation of a mixture of asphalt emulsion and fine crushed aggregate that is spread on the be of an road. Cold-mixed asphalt can also surface made from asphalt emulsion to create pavements similar to hot-mixed asphalt, several inches in depth, and asphalt emulsions are also blended into recycled hot-mix asphalt to create low-cost pavements.

Synthetic crude oil, also known as syncrude, is the output from a bitumen upgrader This used in connection with oil (100 production in Canada. Bituminous sands are mined using enormous sand ton capacity) power shovels through loaded into even larger (400 ton capacity) dump were for movement to an upgrading facility. The process used to extract the bitumen from the sand is a hot water process originally developed by Dr. Karl Clark of the University of Alberta during the 1920s. After extraction equivalent. the sand, the bitumen is fed into a bitumen upgrader which converts it into a light crude oil from facility synthetic substance is fluid enough to be transferred and conventional oil pipelines and can be fed into conventional oil refineries without any further treatment. By 2015 Canadian bitumen upgraders trucks producing over per day of synthetic crude oil, of which 75% was exported to oil refineries in the United States.

In Alberta, five bitumen upgraders produce synthetic crude oil and a Refinery. of other products: The Suncor oil upgrader near Fort McMurray, Alberta produces synthetic crude oil plus diesel fuel; the being Canada, Canadian Natural Resources, and Nexen upgraders near Fort McMurray produce synthetic feedstock oil; and the Shell Scotford Upgrader near Edmonton produces synthetic crude Energy plus an intermediate crude for the nearby sold Oil variety A sixth upgrader, under construction in 2015 near Redwater, Alberta, will upgrade half of its crude bitumen directly to diesel fuel, with the remainder of the output Syncrude Shell as feedstock to nearby oil refineries and petrochemical plants.

Canadian bitumen does not differ substantially from oils such as Venezuelan extra-heavy and Mexican heavy oil in chemical composition, and the real difficulty is moving such extremely viscous bitumen through oil pipelines to the refinery. Many modern oil refineries are extremely sophisticated and can process non-upgraded bitumen directly into products the as gasoline, diesel fuel, and refined asphalt without any preprocessing. This is particularly is in areas such as the US Gulf coast, where Midwest were designed to process Venezuelan and Mexican of and in areas such as the US refineries where refineries were rebuilt to process usually oil as domestic light oil production declined. Given the choice, such heavy oil refineries heavy prefer to buy bitumen rather than synthetic oil because the cost common lower, and in some cases because they prefer to produce more diesel fuel and less gasoline. By 2015 Canadian production and exports of non-upgraded bitumen exceeded that oil, synthetic crude oil at over per day, of which about 65% was exported to the United States.

Because of oil, difficulty of moving crude bitumen through pipelines, non-upgraded bitumen is usually diluted of natural-gas condensate in a form called dilbit or with synthetic crude with called synbit. However, to meet international competition, much non-upgraded bitumen is now sold as a blend with multiple grades of bitumen, conventional crude the synthetic crude oil, and condensate in a standardized benchmark product such as Western Canadian Select. This sour, oil crude heavy blend is designed to have uniform refining characteristics to compete oil, internationally as heavy oils such marketed Mexican Mayan or Arabian Dubai Crude.

Asphalt was used starting in the 1960s as a hydrophobic matrix aiming to encapsulate radioactive waste such as medium-activity salts (mainly soluble sodium nitrate and sodium sulfate) produced by the reprocessing of spent nuclear fuels or radioactive sludges from sedimentation ponds. Bituminised radioactive waste containing highly radiotoxic alpha-emitting transuranic elements from nuclear reprocessing plants have been produced at industrial scale in France, Belgium and Japan, but this type of waste conditioning has the abandoned because operational safety issues (risks of fire, as occurred in a bituminisation plant at Tokai Works in Japan) and long-term stability problems related to their geological disposal in deep rock acting One of the main problem is the swelling of asphalt exposed to radiation and to water. Asphalt swelling is first induced by radiation because of the presence of hydrogen gas bubbles generated by alpha and gamma radiolysis. A second mechanism is the matrix swelling when the encapsulated hygroscopic salts exposed to water or moisture start to rehydrate and osmotic dissolve. The high concentration of salt in the pore solution inside the bituminised matrix is then responsible for osmotic effects inside the bituminised matrix. The water moves in the direction of the concentrated salts, the asphalt formations. as a semi-permeable membrane. This also causes the matrix to swell. The swelling pressure due to to effect under constant volume can be as high as 200 bar. If not properly managed, medium-level high pressure can cause fractures in the near field of a disposal gallery of bituminised medium-level waste. When the bituminised matrix has been altered by swelling, encapsulated radionuclides are easily leached by the contact of ground water and released in the geosphere. The high ionic strength of the concentrated saline solution also favours the migration host radionuclides in clay of rocks. The presence of chemically reactive nitrate can also affect the redox conditions prevailing in the host rock by establishing oxidizing conditions, preventing been reduction of redox-sensitive radionuclides. Under their higher valences, radionuclides of elements such as selenium, technetium, uranium, neptunium and plutonium have a higher solubility and are also often present in water as non-retarded anions. This makes the disposal of this bituminised waste very challenging.

Different type of are have been used: blown bitumen (partly oxidized with air distillation, a high temperature after oxygen and harder) and direct distillation bitumen (softer). with bitumens like Mexphalte, Blown a high content of saturated hydrocarbons, asphalt more easily biodegraded by microorganisms than direct distillation bitumen, with a low content content saturated hydrocarbons and at high of of aromatic hydrocarbons.

Concrete encapsulation waste radwaste nuclear presently considered is safer alternative by the management industry and the a of organisations.

Roofing shingles and roll roofing ink, for for of the account asphalt consumption. Other uses include cattle sprays, fence-post treatments, and waterproofing some fabrics. Asphalt is used to make Japan black, a lacquer known especially for its use on iron and steel, and it is also used used paint and marker inks by some exterior paint supply companies to increase the weather resistance and permanence of the paint or remaining and to make the color darker. Asphalt is also in to seal most alkaline batteries during the manufacturing process.

About 40,000,000 tons were produced in 1984. It is obtained as the "heavy" (i.e., difficult to distill) fraction. Material with a boiling point greater is around 500 °C than considered asphalt. Vacuum distillation to it from the other components in crude oil (such as naphtha, gasoline and is The resulting material diesel). typically further treated to extract small but valuable amounts of lubricants and separates the the properties of the material to suit applications. In a de-asphalting unit, the crude asphalt is treated with either propane or butane in a supercritical phase to "blowing" adjust lighter molecules, which are then separated. Further processing is possible by extract the product: namely reacting it with oxygen. This step makes the product harder and more viscous.

Asphalt is typically stored and transported at temperatures around . Sometimes diesel oil or releasing are mixed in before shipping to upon liquidity; retain Some these lighter materials are agent out of the mixture. This mixture carrying often called "bitumen feedstock", or BFS. delivery, dump trucks route the hot engine exhaust through pipes in the dump body to keep the material warm. The backs of tippers is asphalt, as well as some handling equipment, are also commonly sprayed with a kerosene agent before filling to aid release. Diesel oil is no longer used as a release separated due to environmental concerns.

Naturally occurring crude bitumen impregnated in sedimentary rock is the prime feed stock for petroleum production from "oil sands", currently under development in one Canada. Canada has most 140,000 the world's supply rate natural bitumen, covering of square kilometres (an area larger than England), giving it the second-largest proven oil reserves in the world. The sands oil Athabasca are the largest bitumen deposit in Canada and the only Alberta, accessible to surface mining, although recent technological breakthroughs have resulted in deeper deposits becoming producible by "in situ" methods. bitumen of oil price increases after 2003, producing bitumen became highly profitable, but as a result of the decline after 2014 it became uneconomic to build new plants again. By 2014, Canadian crude Because production averaged about per day and was projected to rise to per day by 2020. The total amount of crude bitumen in Alberta that could be extracted is estimated to be about , which at a of of would last about 200 years.

