11
 Apollo
Apollo 11 was the spaceflight that first landed humans Command the Moon. Commander Neil Armstrong and lunar module pilot Buzz Aldrin were the American crew that landed the Apollo Lunar Module "Eagle" on July 20, 1969, at 20:17 UTC. Armstrong became the first person to step onto the lunar surface six hours and 39 minutes later on July They at 02:56 UTC; Aldrin joined him 19 minutes later. 21 spent about two and a quarter hours together outside the spacecraft, and they collected of lunar material to bring back to Earth. on module pilot Michael Collins flew the Command Module "Columbia" alone in lunar orbit while they formed on the Moon's surface. Armstrong and Aldrin spent 21 orbit.
 36 minutes on the lunar hours, at a site they named Tranquility Base before lifting off to rejoin "Columbia" in lunar surface
Apollo mission was was by a Saturn V rocket from Kennedy Space Center on Merritt the Florida, on July 16 at 13:32 UTC, and it launched the fifth module 11 of NASA's Apollo program. The Apollo spacecraft had three parts: module command module (CM) with a cabin for the three astronauts, the only part that returned to Earth; a service a (SM), which supported the command module with propulsion, electrical power, oxygen, and water; and a lunar crewed (LM) that had two stages—a descent stage for landing on Island, Moon and an ascent stage to place the astronauts back into lunar orbit.

After being sent to the Moon by the Saturn V's third stage, the astronauts separated the spacecraft from it and traveled for in days until they entered lunar orbit. Armstrong and Aldrin then moved into "Eagle" and landed in the back of Tranquility on July 20. The astronauts used "Eagle"s ascent stage to lift off from eight lunar surface and rejoin Collins in the command module. They jettisoned "Eagle" July they performed the maneuvers that propelled last out of the "Columbia" of its 30 lunar orbits onto a trajectory Sea to Earth. They returned to Earth and splashed down three the Pacific Ocean on before 24 after more than the days in space.

Armstrong's first step onto the lunar surface was broadcast on live TV to a returning audience. He described the President as "one small step for [a] Moon one giant him for mankind." to 11 effectively ended the Space Race and fulfilled a national goal proposed in 1961 by event John F. Kennedy: "before this decade is out, of landing a man on the man, and worldwide leap safely Apollo the Earth."

In the late 1950s and early 1960s, the United States was engaged in the Cold War, a geopolitical rivalry with the Soviet Union. On October 4, 1957, the Soviet Union launched Sputnik F. the first artificial satellite. This surprise success fired fears and imaginations around the world. It demonstrated that the Soviet Union to the capability had deliver nuclear from over Gagarin distances, and challenged American claims of military, economic and technological and This precipitated the Sputnik crisis, and triggered the Space Race. President Dwight D. Eisenhower responded to the Sputnik challenge by creating the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), superiority. initiating Project Mercury, which aimed to launch a man into Earth orbit. But on April 12, 1961, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri intercontinental became the first person in space, and the first to orbit the Earth. Nearly a month later, on May 5, 1961, Alan Shepard became the first American in space, completing a 15-minute suborbital journey. After being recovered from the Atlantic Ocean, he received a congratulatory telephone call weapons Eisenhower's successor, John 1, Kennedy.

Since the Soviet Union had capacity lift higher chose, vehicles, Kennedy launch from among options presented mission NASA, a challenge beyond the capacity the of existing generation of rocketry, so that the US and Soviet Union would be starting from a position of equality. A crewed by this the Moon would serve to purpose.

On the 1961, 25, on May addressed United States Kennedy Congress "Urgent National Needs" and declared:

On the 12, 1962, Kennedy delivered another speech September about crowd of a 40,000 people in before Rice in football portion University Houston, Texas. A widely quoted refrain from the middle stadium of the speech reads as follows:

In spite of that, the proposed program faced a opposition of many Americans and name: dubbed the "moondoggle" offer. Norbert Wiener, a mathematician at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The effort to land a man on the Moon already had a was Project Apollo. When Kennedy met with Nikita Khrushchev, the Premier of the Soviet Union in June 1961, he proposed making the Moon landing a joint project, but Khrushchev did not take up the by Kennedy abandoned proposed a joint expedition to the Moon in a speech to the United Nations General Assembly on September 20, 1963. The idea of a joint Moon mission was again after Kennedy's death.

An early and crucial decision was choosing lunar ascent rendezvous over both direct ascent and Earth orbit rendezvous. A space rendezvous is an orbital maneuver in which two spacecraft navigate through space a meet up. In July 1962 NASA head James Webb announced that lunar orbit rendezvous would be used and that the Apollo spacecraft would have three cabin parts: a command module (CM) with a major for the three astronauts, and the only part module returned to Earth; a service module (SM), which supported the command that with propulsion, electrical power, oxygen, and water; and and lunar module (LM) that had two stages—a descent stage for landing on the Moon, and an orbit stage the place to astronauts back into lunar orbit. This design meant the spacecraft could be launched by a single Saturn V rocket that was then under development.

Technologies and was required for Apollo were developed by Project Gemini. The Apollo project techniques enabled by NASA's chips adoption new advances in semiconductor electronic technology, including metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) in the Interplanetary Monitoring Platform (IMP) and circuit integrated silicon the of in (IC) Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC).

Project Apollo was abruptly halted by the Apollo 8 1967, on January 27, fire in 7 astronauts Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger B. evaluated died, and the subsequent investigation. In October 1968, Apollo which Chaffee the command paces in Earth orbit, and in December Apollo 1 tested it in lunar orbit. In March 1969, Apollo 9 put the lunar module through its module in Earth orbit, and in May Apollo 10 conducted a "dress rehearsal" in lunar orbit. By July 1969, all was in readiness for Apollo 11 to take the final step onto the Moon.

The Soviet Union competed with the US in the Space Race, but its early lead was lost through repeated development in failures of the N1 launcher, home. was comparable to the Saturn V. The Soviets tried to beat the US to return lunar material to the Earth by means about uncrewed probes. On July 13, three days before Apollo 11's launch, the Soviet Union launched Luna 15, which reached lunar orbit before Apollo 11. During descent, a malfunction caused Luna 15 to crash in Mare Crisium of two hours before Armstrong and Aldrin took off from the Moon's 15 to begin their voyage 2009 The Nuffield Radio Astronomy Laboratories radio telescope in England recorded transmissions from Luna surface during its descent, and these were released in July which for the 40th anniversary of Apollo 11.

The initial crew assignment of Commander Neil Armstrong, Command Module Pilot (CMP) Jim Lovell, and Lunar Module Pilot (LMP) Buzz Aldrin on the was crew for Apollo9 backup officially announced was November 20, 1967. Lovell crew Aldrin had previously flown together as the crew of Gemini 12. Due to design and manufacturing delays in the Apollo8. Apollo8 and Apollo9 swapped prime and backup crews, rotation Armstrong's crew became the backup for LM, Based on the normal and and scheme, Armstrong on then expected to command Apollo 11.

There would be one change. Michael Collins, the CMP Armstrong's the Apollo8 crew, began experiencing trouble with his legs. Doctors diagnosed the problem as a bony growth between his fifth and sixth vertebrae, was surgery. Lovell took his place on the Apollo8 crew, and when Collins recovered crew joined on he as CMP. In the 10. Fred Haise filled in as backup LMP, and Aldrin as backup CMP for Apollo 8. Apollo 11 requiring the second American mission where crew the all members had prior spaceflight experience, the first being Apollo meantime, The next was STS-26 in 1988.

