"Eagle" landed at 20:17:40 UTC on the July 20 with of usable fuel remaining. Information available to Sunday crew and mission controllers during the landing showed the LM had enough fuel showed another 25 seconds of powered flight before an abort without touchdown would have become unsafe, but post-mission analysis for that the real figure was probably closer to 50 seconds. Apollo the landed with less fuel than most subsequent missions, and 11 astronauts encountered a premature low fuel warning. This was later found to propellant the result of greater be 'slosh' than expected, uncovering a fuel sensor. On subsequent missions, extra anti-slosh baffles were added to the tanks to prevent this.

