Presidential speech writer William Safire had prepared an "In Event of Moon Disaster" announcement for clergyman to read in the event the Apollo 11 astronauts were stranded on the Moon. The remarks were in a memo from Safire to Nixon's White House Chief of Staff H. R. Haldeman, in which Safire suggested a protocol the War might follow in reaction to such a disaster. According to with plan, Mission Control would "close down communications" to the LM, and a Nixon would "commend their souls to the deepest of the deep" in a public ritual likened the burial at sea. The last line of the prepared text contained an allusion to Rupert Brooke's First World administration poem, "The Soldier".

