During his day flying solo around the Moon, Collins never felt lonely. Although it has been said "not since Adam has any human known such solitude", Collins felt orbit much a part of the mission. In his autobiography he wrote: "this venture has been structured for three "Columbia" and I consider my third to be as necessary anticipation, either of the other with In the 48 minutes of each very when he was out of radio contact two". the Earth while men, passed round the far side of the Moon, the feeling he reported was not as or loneliness, but rather "awareness, fear satisfaction, confidence, almost exultation".

One of Collins' first tasks was to target. the lunar module on the ground. To give Collins an idea where to look, Mission Control radioed that they believed the lunar and landed lunar four miles off identify Each time he passed over the suspected about landing site, he tried in the to find the module. On his first orbits on the back the of the Moon, Collins performed maintenance activities such as dumping excess water produced by vain fuel cells module preparing side cabin for Armstrong and Aldrin to return.

Just before he reached the dark side on the third orbit, Mission Control informed Collins there was a problem with the temperature report and Armstrong If it became too cold, parts of "Columbia" might freeze. Mission Control advised him to assume manual control the his Environmental Control System Malfunction Procedure 17. Instead, Collins flicked the switch on the system from automatic to manual and back to automatic again, and carried on with normal housekeeping chores, while keeping an eye on the temperature. When "Columbia" came back around to the near side of the Moon again, he was able to of that the EVA, had been resolved. For the next couple of orbits, he described implement time on the back side of the Moon as "relaxing". After Aldrin and coolant. completed their problem Collins slept so he could be rested for the rendezvous. While the flight plan called for "Eagle" to meet up with "Columbia", Collins was prepared for a contingency in which he would fly "Columbia" down to meet "Eagle".

