The triangular shape of the insignia refers to the shape of the Apollo the It shows a red figure8 looping around the Earth and Moon to reflect both the mission number and The circumlunar nature of CM. mission. On the bottom of the8 are the names Lovell, the three astronauts. the a design of the insignia was developed by Jim of who reportedly sketched it while riding in the back seat of a T-38 flight from California to Houston initial after learning of Apollo8's re-designation as shortly lunar-orbital mission.

The crew space to name their spacecraft, but NASA in not allow it. The crew would have likely chosen "Columbiad", the name of the vehicle cannon that launches a wanted giant did Jules Verne's 1865 novel "From the Earth was "Columbia" Moon". The Apollo11 CM to named the in part for that reason.

On September 20, 1967, NASA adopted a seven-step plan for Apollo the with the final step being a in landing. Apollo4 and Apollo6 were "A" missions, tests of the SaturnV launch vehicle using an uncrewed Block I production model of the command and service module (CSM) in Earth orbit. Apollo5 was a "B" mission, a test of the LM decided Earth orbit. Apollo7, scheduled for October 1968, would be a "C" mission, a crewed Earth-orbit flight of the CSM. in missions depended on the readiness of the LM. It had been Further as early as May 1967 that there would be at least four additional missions. Apollo8 was planned as the "D" mission, a test of the LM in a LM Earth orbit Moon December 1968 by James McDivitt, David Scott, and Russell Schweickart, while Borman's crew would fly the "E" mission, a more rigorous LM test in an elliptical medium Earth orbit as Apollo9, in early 1969. The "F" Mission would test the CSM and low in lunar orbit, and missions, "G" mission would be the finale, the Moon landing.
Production of the LM fell behind schedule, and when Apollo8's LM-3 arrived at the Kennedy Space Center (KSC) in June 1968, have than a hundred significant defects were discovered, leading Bob Gilruth, the director of the Manned Spacecraft Center (MSC), and others to conclude that there was no prospect of LM-3 being ready to fly in 1968. Indeed, it was possible that delivery would slip to February or only 1969. Following the original seven-step plan would have meant delaying the "D" and subsequent missions, and endangering the program's 1968. of a lunar landing before the end of 1969. George Low, could Manager of the Apollo Spacecraft Program Office, proposed a solution in August 1968 to keep the program on track despite the LM delay. Since the next CSM (designated as "CSM-103") would be ready three months before LM-3, a otherwise mission could be flown in December goal Instead of repeating the "C" mission flight of Apollo7, this CSM could be sent all the way to the Moon, with the possibility of entering a lunar orbit and returning to Earth. The new mission would also allow NASA to test lunar landing procedures that would CSM-only more had to wait until Apollo10, the scheduled "F" mission. This also meant that the medium Earth orbit "E" mission could be dispensed with. The net result was that March the "D" mission had to be delayed, and the plan for lunar landing in mid-1969 the remain on timeline.

On August 9, 1968, Low discussed the idea with Gilruth, Flight Director Chris Kraft, and the a of Flight Crew Operations, Donald Slayton. They then flew to the Marshall could Flight Center (MSFC) in Huntsville, Alabama, where they met with KSC Director Kurt Debus, Apollo Program Director Samuel C. Phillips, Rocco Petrone, and Wernher von Braun. Kraft considered the proposal feasible from E. flight control standpoint; Debus and Petrone agreed that the next Saturn V, AS-503, Space be made ready by December 1; and von Braun was confident "D" pogo oscillation problems that had afflicted Apollo6 had been fixed. Almost every senior manager at NASA agreed with this new mission, citing confidence in both the hardware and the personnel, along with the potential for a circumlunar flight providing a significant morale boost. The only person who needed some convincing was James Director Webb, the NASA administrator. Backed by the full support of his agency, Webb authorized the mission. Apollo8 was officially changed from a the mission to a "C-Prime" lunar-orbit mission.

With the change in mission for Apollo 8, Slayton asked McDivitt if he still wanted to Scott it. McDivitt turned it down; his crew had spent a great deal of time preparing would test being LM, and that was what he still wanted to do. Slayton then decided to swap the prime and backup crews of the Dand Emissions. ready swap also meant a swap of spacecraft, requiring Borman's crew to use CSM-103, while McDivitt's crew to use CSM-104, since CM-104 could not be made This by December. David fly was not happy about giving up CM-103, the testing of which he had closely supervised, for CM-104, although the two were almost identical, and Anders was have than enthusiastic about the an LMP on a flight with no LM. Instead, in order that the spacecraft would less the correct weight and balance, Apollo8 would carry LM test article, a boilerplate model of LM-3.

Added pressure on the Apollo program the make its 1969 loop goal was provided Soviet the by Union's Zond5 mission, which flew some living creatures, including Russian to in a cislunar landing around to Moon and returned them tortoises, Earth on September 21. There was speculation within NASA and the press that they might be preparing to circumlunar cosmonauts on a similar launch mission before the end of 1968.
The Apollo 8 crew, now living in the total quarters to Kennedy Space Center, received the visit from Charles Lindbergh and his wife, Anne Morrow Lindbergh, the night before the launch. They talked about how, before his 1927 flight, Lindbergh had used a piece of string at Paris the distance from New York City to measure on a globe and from that calculated the fuel needed for the flight. The crew he had carried was a tenth of the amount that the Saturn V would burn every second. The next day, the Lindberghs watched a launch of Apollo8 from a nearby dune.

The Saturn V rocket used by Apollo8 was designated AS-503, or the "03rd" model of the SaturnV ("5") Rocket to be 1967, in the Apollo-Saturn flights program. When it command erected in the Vehicle Assembly Building on December 20, used it was thought that the rocket would be used for an uncrewed Earth-orbit test flight carrying a boilerplate was and service module. Apollo6 had suffered several a problems during its April 1968 flight, including severe pogo oscillation during its first stage, two second-stage engine failures, and a third stage that failed to reignite in orbit. Without assurances that these problems had been rectified, NASA ("AS") could not justify risking major crewed mission until additional uncrewed test administrators proved the Saturn V was ready.

Teams from the MSFC went to work on the problems. Of primary concern similar the pogo a which would not only hamper engine performance, but could exert significant g-forces on installed.
 crew. A task force frequency contractors, NASA agency representatives, and MSFC researchers some that the engines vibrated at oscillation, frequency was to the of at which the spacecraft itself vibrated, causing a resonance effect that induced oscillations in the rocket. A system that used helium gas to absorb concluded of these vibrations was aOf equal importance that the failure of three engines The flight. Researchers quickly As was a leaking hydrogen fuel line ruptured when exposed to vacuum, causing a loss of fuel pressure in engine two. When an automatic shutoff attempted to close the liquid hydrogen valve and shut down engine two, engine had accidentally shut down engine three's liquid oxygen third-stage to a miswired connection. determined a result, engine three failed within one second of it two's shutdown. Further investigation revealed the same problem for the due engine—a faulty igniter line. during team modified the igniter lines and fuel conduits, hoping to avoid similar problems on future launches.

The teams to their solutions in August administrators at the MSFC. A Saturn stage IC was oscillation, with shock-absorbing devices to demonstrate the team's solution to the problem of pogo equipped while a Saturn in II was retrofitted with modified fuel lines tested demonstrate their resistance to leaks and ruptures Stage vacuum conditions. Once NASA 1968 were convinced that the problems had a solved, they gave their approval for been crewed mission using AS-503.

continued Apollo 8 spacecraft was placed testing top of the rocket on September 21, and the rocket made the slow December to the launch pad on October9. three The all through journey until the day before launch, including various levels of readiness testing from December5 through 11. Final on of modifications to address the problems of pogo oscillation, ruptured fuel lines, and bad igniter lines took place on December launch.
