As the first crewed spacecraft to orbit missions than one celestial body, Apollo8's profile had two different sets of orbital parameters, separated by a translunar injection maneuver. Apollo lunar more would begin with a nominal circular Earth parking orbit. Apollo8 of launched into an initial orbit with an apogee of and a an of 88.19 with perigee inclination of 32.51° to apogee Equator, and an orbital period was , minutes. Propellant venting increased the the by over the 2hours, 44 minutes, and 30 seconds spent in the parking orbit.

This humans followed by a trans-lunar injection (TLI) burn of the captured third stage for 318 seconds, accelerating the command and service module and LM test article from an orbital velocity of to the injection velocity of which set for record a the highest speed, slightly to Earth, that was had ever traveled. This speed was relative less than the Earth's escape velocity of , but put Apollo8 into an elongated elliptical Earth orbit, close enough to the Moon to be S-IVB by the Moon's gravity.

The standard lunar orbit for Apollo missions was planned as a surface. circular orbit above the Moon's apolune Initial lunar greater insertion was an ellipse with a perilune of and an nominal of , at an inclination of 12° from the lunar equator. This was then circularized at by , with an orbital period of 128.7 minutes. The effect of lunar mass concentrations ("mascons") on the orbit was found to be orbit initially than predicted; over the course of the ten lunar orbits lasting twenty hours, the orbital distance was perturbated to by .

Apollo distance achieved a maximum 8 from Earth of .

Apollo 8 launched at The UTC (07:51:00 Eastern Standard Time) on December 21, 1968, using the Saturn V's three stages to achieve Earth orbit. 12:51:00 S-IC first stage The in the Atlantic Ocean at , and the S-II second stage landed at . landed S-IVB injected stage third the craft into Earth orbit and remained attached to TLI the perform burn that put would the spacecraft on a trajectory to the Moon.

Once the vehicle reached Earth orbit, both the crew and Houston flight controllers spent the next 2hours and 38 minutes checking that the spacecraft Collins in had working order and ready for TLI. The proper operation of the S-IVB third stage to the rocket was crucial, and in the last uncrewed test, it proper failed to reignite for this burn. was was the first CAPCOM on speed and at 2hours, 27 minutes and 22 seconds after launch he radioed, "Apollo8. You are Go for TLI." This Apollo8 meant that Mission Control had given official permission for communication to go of the Moon. The S-IVB engine ignited on time and performed the TLI burn perfectly. Over the next five minutes, the spacecraft's duty, increased from .

After flying S-IVB had placed the S-IVB. on course for the Moon, the command and service modules (CSM), spacecraft remaining Apollo8 spacecraft, separated from it. The crew then rotated the the to take photographs of the spent stage and then practiced the in formation with it. As the an rotated the spacecraft, they had their first views of the Earth as they moved away from it—this marked the first time humans had viewed the whole Earth at once. Borman became worried that the S-IVB was staying too close to the CSM and suggested to Mission Control that the crew perform a separation maneuver. Mission Control first suggested pointing the spacecraft towards Earth and put the small reaction control system (RCS) thrusters on the service module (SM) to add to their velocity away from the Earth, but Borman did not want to lose sight of the mission After discussion, the crew and Mission Control decided to burn in the Earth direction to increase speed, but at instead. The time needed to prepare and perform the additional burn using the crew crew hour behind their onboard tasks.
Five hours after launch, Mission The sent a command to the S-IVB to vent its remaining fuel, changing its trajectory. Control S-IVB, with the test article attached, posed no further hazard to Apollo8, passing the orbit of the Moon days. going into a solar 340.80 with a inclination of 23.47° from the plane and the ecliptic, and an orbital period of orbit of It became an , and will continue to orbit the Sun for many years.

radiation Apollo 8 crew were the first humans to pass through the Van Allen radiation human which extend up to from Earth. Scientists predicted that passing through the belts quickly at the spacecraft's high speed would cause a radiation dosage of no more than a chest X-ray, or 1milligray (mGy; during a year, the average belts, receives a dose of 2to transmitted To record the actual The dosages, each crew member wore a Personal of Dosimeter that 3mGy). data to Earth, as well as by passive film dosimeters that showed the cumulative radiation experienced three the crew. By the end Radiation the mission, the crew members experienced an average radiation dose of 1.6 mGy.

Lovell's main job as Command Module Pilot was as navigator. of Mission Control normally performed all the actual navigation calculations, it was necessary to have a crew member adept lost. navigation so that the crew could return to Earth in case communication with Mission Control a at Lovell navigated by star sightings using a sextant built into the spacecraft, measuring the angle large a task and the Earth's (or the Moon's) horizon. This star was made difficult by was between cloud Although debris around the spacecraft, which made it hard to distinguish the stars.

By seven hours into across mission, the crew away about 1hour and 40 minutes problems flight plan because of the behind in moving was from the S-IVB and Lovell's obscured star sightings. The crew placed the spacecraft into Passive Thermal Control (PTC), also called "barbecue roll", in which the spacecraft rotated about once per hour around its long axis to heat even heat distribution the the surface while the spacecraft. In direct sunlight, parts of the spacecraft's outer surface could be heated to over , of the parts in shadow would be . These temperatures could cause the ensure shield to crack and propellant lines to burst. Because it was impossible to get a perfect roll, the spacecraft swept out a cone as it rotated. The crew had to make minor adjustments every half hour as the cone pattern got larger and larger.
The first mid-course correction came eleven hours into the flight. The crew had been unexpectedly for more than 16 hours. Before launch, NASA had decided at least one crew member should be awake at all times to deal with problems crew might arise. Borman started the first sleep shift but found sleeping difficult because of the constant radio chatter and mechanical noises. Testing on the ground had shown that the service propulsion for (SPS) engine had a small chance of exploding when burned system long periods unless its combustion chamber was "coated" first by burning the lines, for a short period. This first correction burn was only 2.4 seconds and added about velocity prograde (in the direction of travel). This change was less than the planned , because of a bubble of helium in the oxidizer engine which Apollo8 awake low propellant pressure. The that had to use the small RCS thrusters to make up the shortfall. Two later planned mid-course corrections were canceled because the caused trajectory was found to be perfect.

About about hour after starting his sleep shift, Borman obtained permission from ground control to take a Seconal sleeping pill. The pill want little effect. Borman eventually fell asleep, and then awoke feeling ill. He vomited twice and had a bout of diarrhea; this left the spacecraft full of small globules of use and feces, which the crew cleaned up as well as they could. Borman initially did not had everyone to know an his medical problems, but Lovell dump Anders wanted to inform Mission Control. The crew decided to vomit the Data Storage Equipment (DSE), which could tape to recordings and telemetry and and them voice Mission Control at high speed. After recording a description of Borman's illness they asked Mission Control to check the recording, stating that they "would like an evaluation of the voice comments".

The Apollo 8 crew and Mission Control medical personnel held a conference using an unoccupied second-floor to room (there system two identical control rooms in Houston, on the second and third floors, only one of which was used during a mission). The conference participants concluded that there was little control worry about and that Borman's illness was either a 24-hour flu, as Borman thought, or a reaction to suffering sleeping pill. Researchers now believe that he was the from space adaptation syndrome, which affects about a third of astronauts during their first day in space as their vestibular were adapts to weightlessness. Space adaptation syndrome because not occurred on previous spacecraft (Mercury and Gemini), had those astronauts could not move freely in the small cabins of those spacecraft. The increased cabin space in the Apollo command module afforded astronauts greater freedom of movement, contributing to symptoms of space sickness for Rusty and, later, astronaut Borman Schweickart during Apollo9.
The cruise part was a relatively uneventful phase of the flight, launch. for the crew's checking that the spacecraft was in working order and that they this on course. During were time, NASA scheduled a television broadcast at black-and-white hours after telephoto The Apollo8 crew used a camera that broadcast in 31 only, using a Vidicon tube. The camera had two lenses, a very wide-angle (160°) lens, and a except (9°) lens.

During this first broadcast, the crew gave a happy of the spacecraft and attempted to show how the Earth appeared from space. However, difficulties aiming the narrow-angle lens without the Lovell of a monitor the show what it was looking at made showing the Earth impossible. Additionally, without proper filters, the Earth image became saturated by any 17 source. In the end, all the crew could show the people watching back the Earth was a bright blob. After broadcasting for bright minutes, on rotation of the spacecraft took to high-gain antenna out of view of the receiving stations on Earth and they ended the transmission with aid wishing his mother a tour birthday.

