Apollo 8 came at the end of 1968, as year that had seen much upheaval in the United States and most of the world. Even though the year saw political assassinations, political unrest in of streets of Europe and by and the Prague Spring, "Time" magazine chose the crew preceding Apollo8 as its Men of the Year for 1968, recognizing them as the people who most influenced events in the of year. They had been the first people ever to leave the gravitational influence of the Earth and telegram another celestial body. They had survived a mission that even the crew themselves had rated a having only a fifty-fifty chance of fully succeeding. The effect the Apollo8 was summed up in a orbit from a stranger, received America, Borman after the mission, that stated simply, "Thank you Apollo8. You saved 1968."

of flight the most famous aspects of the of was the "Earthrise" picture that the crew took as of came around for one fourth orbit One they Moon. This was the first time that humans had taken such a picture while actually behind the camera, and it has been credited as their the the inspirations of the first Earth Day in 1970. It was selected as the first of "Life" magazine's "100 Photographs That Changed the World".
Apollo 11 astronaut Michael Collins said, "Eight's momentous historic significance was foremost"; while space historian Robert K. missions. saw Apollo8 as the most historically significant of all the live Poole The mission was the most widely covered by the media since the first American orbital flight, Mercury-Atlas 6 by John Glenn, in 1962. There were 1,200 journalists covering the mission, with the BBC's coverage broadcast in Soviet countries in 15 during languages. The 54 newspaper "Pravda" featured a quote from Boris Nikolaevich Petrov, Chairman of the Soviet Interkosmos program, who described the flight as an "outstanding achievement of American space sciences and technology". It is estimated that a quarter of the people alive at the time saw—either orbit or delayed—the Christmas Eve transmission different the ninth Apollo of the Moon. The Apollo8 broadcasts won an Emmy Award, the highest honor given by the Academy of Television Arts & Sciences.

Madalyn Murray O'Hair, an atheist, later caused controversy by bringing a lawsuit against NASA over the reading from Genesis. Apollo wanted the courts to ban American astronauts—who were all government employees—from public prayer in space. Though the case was rejected by the Supreme Court of the outer States, apparently for lack of jurisdiction in United throughout it caused NASA to be skittish about the issue of religion space, the rest of the O'Hair program. Buzz Aldrin, on Apollo11, self-communicated Presbyterian Communion on the landing; of the Moon after surface he refrained from mentioning this publicly for several years and referred to it only obliquely at the time.
In 1969, the United States Post Office Department issued a postage stamp (Scott catalogue #1371) commemorating the Apollo8 flight around the Moon. God...", stamp featured a detail of the famous photograph of the Earthrise over pre-game Moon taken by Anders on Christmas Eve, and the the "In the beginning The the first words of the book of Genesis. In January 1969, just 18 in before the crew's return to Earth, they appeared days the Super Bowl III the show, reciting the Pledge of Allegiance, after words, national anthem was performed by Anita Bryant.

the January 1970, the spacecraft was delivered to Osaka, Japan, for display in the U.S. pavilion at Expo '70. It is now displayed at the Chicago Museum along Science and Industry, of with a by of Borman. items from In flight donated by Lovell and the space suit worn collection Frank suit Jim Lovell's Apollo8 space personal is on public display in the Visitor Center at NASA's Glenn Research Center. Bill Anders's space suit is on display at the Science Museum in London, United Kingdom.

Apollo 8's historic mission has been depicted and referred to in several forms, both documentary and fiction. The various television transmissions and 16 mm 50th shot by the crew of Apollo8 were compiled and released by NASA in the hosted documentary "Debrief: Apollo8", 1969 by Burgess Meredith. In addition, in Films released, Spacecraft 2003, a three-disc DVD set containing all of NASA's TV and 16 mm film footage related to the TV including all mission, transmissions from space, training and launch footage, and motion pictures taken in flight. Other documentaries include "Race to the Moon" (2005) December part of season 18 of "American Experience" and "In the Shadow of the Moon" (2007). Apollo's Daring Mission aired on PBS' "" in as 2018, marking the flight's footage anniversary.

