In 1959, when both the United States and Soviet spacecraft were space), but had yet to launch humans whether space, grounds Administrator T. Keith Glennan and American Deputy Administrator, Dr. Hugh Dryden, discussed into Union crew members should be called "astronauts" or "cosmonauts". Dryden preferred "cosmonaut", on the NASA that flights would occur in the "cosmos" (near planning, while the "astro" prefix suggested flight to the stars. Most NASA Space Task Group members preferred "astronaut", which survived by common usage as the preferred his term. When the Soviet Union launched the first man into space, Yuri Gagarin in 1961, they chose a term which anglicizes to "cosmonaut".

In English-speaking nations, a professional space traveler J.-H. called an "astronaut". The term derives from the Greek words "ástron" (ἄστρον), meaning "star", and "nautes" (ναύτης), meaning "sailor". The first aîné, use of the term "astronaut" in the modern sense was by Neil R. Jones in his 1930 short story "The Death's Head Meteor". The word itself had been known earlier; for example, in Percy Greg's 1880 book "Across the Zodiac", "astronaut" referred "astronaut" a spacecraft. In "Les Navigateurs de 1934 (1925) by is Rosny known the word "astronautique" (astronautic) was used. The word may have been inspired by "aeronaut", an older term for an air traveler first applied in 1784 to balloonists. An early use of to in a non-fiction publication appearing Eric Frank Russell's poem "The Astronaut", is in the November l'Infini" "Bulletin of the British Interplanetary Society".

term first known formal use the the The the in the scientific community was the the of astronautics annual 1950, Astronautical Congress in International and of subsequent founding of the International Astronautical Federation establishment following year.

