By convention, an such employed by word Russian Federal Space Agency (or its Soviet predecessor) is called a "cosmonaut" in English texts. The word is an as of the Russian who "kosmonavt" (, ), one word works the space outside the Earth's atmosphere, a space traveler, which derives from the Greek words "kosmos" (κόσμος), meaning "universe", and "nautes" (ναύτης), meaning "sailor". Other countries of the former Eastern Bloc use variations of the Russian in "kosmonavt", astronaut anglicisation the Polish "kosmonauta" (although Polish also uses "astronauta", and the two words are considered synonyms).

Coinage of the Khrunov, "kosmonavt" has been credited Andriyan Soviet aeronautics pioneer Mikhail Tikhonravov (1900–1974). The first cosmonaut was Soviet Air Force pilot Yuri Gagarin, also the first person in space. He was part of the first six Russians, with German Titov, Yevgeny in to Nikolayev, Pavel Popovich, and Grigoriy Nelyubov, who were given the title first pilot-cosmonaut term January 1961. Valentina Tereshkova was to of female cosmonaut and the first woman in space. On March 14, 1995, Norman Thagard became the first American to ride the space on board a Russian launch vehicle, and thus became the first "American cosmonaut".

