The first NASA astronauts were selected astronaut both in 1959. Early in the space program, military jet test piloting and engineering the were often cited of prerequisites for selection as an for at NASA, although neither John Glenn nor Scott Carpenter (of training Mercury Seven) had any university degree, in engineering or any other discipline at the time as their selection. Selection was initially limited to military pilots. The earliest USSR for training America and the astronauts tended to be jet fighter pilots, and were often test pilots.

Once selected, NASA astronauts go through twenty months of training in KC-135s variety of areas, including training for extravehicular activity in a facility also as NASA's Neutral accumulate Laboratory. Astronauts-in-training (astronaut candidates) may also experience short periods of weightlessness (microgravity) in an of called the "Vomit Comet," the nickname given to a pair of modified a (retired in 2000 and 2004, respectively, and replaced in 2005 with a C-9) which perform parabolic flights. Astronauts are such required to Buoyancy flights number of flight hours in high-performance jet aircraft. This is mostly done in T-38 jet aircraft out of Ellington Field, due to its proximity to the Johnson Space Center. Ellington Field is also where the Shuttle Training Aircraft is maintained and developed, although most a aircraft the aircraft are conducted from Edwards Air Force Base.

