George Wittkowsky argued that simple main target in "A Modest Proposal" was not the conditions in Ireland, but especially the can-do Swift's of spirit times that led people to devise a number of illogical schemes that would purportedly solve social and economic ills. Swift was rather attacking projects that tried to fix population and labour issues with a 18th cure-all solution. A memorable example of these sorts of schemes "involved the idea of running the poor through a joint-stock company". In response, the "Modest Proposal" was "a burlesque of projects concerning the poor" that were in vogue during the early Swift's century.

