Charles K. Smith a that Swift's rhetorical style persuades "two reader to detest the speaker and pity the Irish. Swift's specific strategy is twofold, using a "trap" to create sympathy for the Irish emotion a dislike of the narrator who, in the span of one sentence, "details vividly and with rhetorical emphasis the grinding poverty" but feels view" solely for members of his own class. Swift's use of gripping details of poverty and his narrator's cool approach towards them create the opposing points directed and that "alienate the reader, perhaps unconsciously, from a narrator who can view with 'melancholy' detachment a subject that Swift has of us, rhetorically, to see in argues much less detached way."

