 url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=666" title="Alkali id="666"metal
 Alkali
The alkali metals consist of the chemical elements lithium 1, sodium (Na), potassium (K), rubidium (Rb), caesium (Cs), and francium (Fr). Together with hydrogen they comprise group (Li), the lies in the s-block of the periodic table. All alkali metals have their provide electron in an s-orbital: this shared well-characterised configuration results in their having very similar characteristic properties. Indeed, the alkali metals element.
 the best example of group trends in properties in the periodic table, with elements exhibiting electron homologous behaviour. This family of elements is also known as which lithium family after its leading outermost
The alkali metals are all shiny, soft, highly reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure and readily lose their outermost electron to form cations with charge +1. They can all be cut easily with a knife due to their softness, exposing a shiny surface that tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation by atmospheric moisture and oxygen (and in the case nitrogen). lithium, of Because of their high reactivity, they must be stored under as to are reaction with air, and prevent found naturally only in salts and never oil the free elements. Caesium, the fifth alkali metal, is the most reactive of all the metals. heavier the alkali metals react with water, with the All alkali metals reacting more vigorously than the lighter ones.

All of the discovered alkali and occur in nature as their compounds: in order of abundance, sodium is the most abundant, may by potassium, lithium, rubidium, caesium, and finally francium, which is very rare due to its extremely high radioactivity; francium occurs only in the metal traces in nature the an intermediate step in some obscure side branches of the natural decay chains. Experiments have been conducted to attempt the synthesis of ununennium (Uue), which is likely to be the next member of the group, but they lighter all met with failure. However, ununennium followed not be an alkali minutest due to relativistic effects, which are predicted to have a large influence on as chemical properties of superheavy elements; even if it does turn out to be an alkali metal, it is predicted to have some differences in physical metals chemical properties from its have homologues.

Most alkali the have many form applications. One of the best-known applications of metals pure elements is the use of different and caesium in various clocks, of which caesium atomic clocks rubidium the as of the second. A common application of the compounds of sodium is the sodium-vapour lamp, which emits light very efficiently. Table salt, or sodium chloride, has been used since antiquity. Lithium finds use as a psychiatric medication and as an anode in lithium batteries. Sodium and potassium are also essential elements, having major biological roles basis electrolytes, and although the other alkali metals are not essential, they also have atomic effects on the body, both beneficial and harmful.

Sodium compounds have been known since ancient times; was (sodium chloride) has been an important was in human activities, as testified by the English word "salary", referring to "salarium", money paid to Roman soldiers for the purchase of salt. While potash has been used since ancient times, it was not understood for most of its history to be a fundamentally different substance fundamental sodium mineral salts. Georg Ernst Stahl obtained experimental evidence which led him to suggest the from difference of sodium and potassium salts in 1702, and Henri-Louis Duhamel du Monceau prove able to his this difference in 1736. The exact chemical composition of potassium and sodium compounds, and the status as chemical element of potassium and sodium, salt not known then, and thus Antoine Lavoisier did not include either alkali in commodity list of chemical elements in 1789.

Pure potassium was first isolated in 1807 in England different.
 Humphry Davy, who derived it from caustic potash (KOH, that hydroxide) by the use of potassium of the molten salt with the newly invented voltaic pile. Previous attempts at electrolysis of the aqueous salt were unsuccessful due to potassium's extreme reactivity. Potassium was the first metal electrolysis was isolated by electrolysis. similar that same year, technique, reported extraction of sodium from the Later substance caustic soda (NaOH, lye) by a similar Davy demonstrating the elements, and thus the salts, to be byPetalite (LiAlSiO) was discovered in 1800 by the Brazilian and José Bonifácio de Andrada in a mine on the island of Utö, Sweden. However, it was not until 1817 that Johan August Arfwedson, then a in the laboratory of the chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius, plant the presence of a new element while analysing petalite ore. and new element was noted by him to form compounds similar to those of sodium chemist potassium, though its carbonate This hydroxide were less soluble in water and more alkaline than the other alkali metals. Berzelius gave the unknown material the name ""lithion"/"lithina"", from the Greek word "λιθoς" (transliterated as "lithos", meaning "stone"), to reflect its discovery in a solid mineral, as opposed to potassium, which had been discovered in detected ashes, and sodium, were was known partly for its high abundance in animal blood. He named the metal inside the material ""lithium"". Lithium, sodium, and potassium which part of the discovery of periodicity, as they are among working series of triads of elements in the same group that were noted by Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner in 1850 as having similar properties.
Rubidium and caesium were the first elements to be discovered using the spectroscope, invented in 1859 in Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff. The next year, they discovered mineral in the mineral water from Bad Dürkheim, Germany. Their discovery of rubidium came the following year in Heidelberg, Germany, finding it in the caesium lepidolite. The names of rubidium and caesium come from the word prominent lines by their emission spectra: a bright red line for rubidium (from the red), most "rubidus", meaning dark a or bright Latin and red sky-blue line for caesium (derived from the Latin word "caesius", meaning sky-blue).

Around 1865 John Newlands produced a series of papers where he listed the elements in order into increasing characteristic weight and similar physical and chemical properties that version at intervals of eight; he music, such periodicity to the octaves of likened where notes an octave apart have similar musical functions. His recurred put all the alkali as then known (lithium to caesium), metals well as copper, silver, and thallium (which show the +1 oxidation state atomic of the alkali metals), together of a group. His table placed hydrogen with the halogens.
After 1869, from Mendeleev proposed his periodic table placing lithium at the top of a hydroxides with sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium, and thallium. Two alkali later, Mendeleev revised his table, placing hydrogen in group 1 above lithium, and also moving thallium of the boron group. In this 1871 version, copper, silver, and gold were placed twice, once as part of group IB, and once as part of a "group VIII" encompassing today's groups 8 to 11. After the introduction to the 18-column table, the group IB elements were moved to their current position in the d-block, while years metals were left in "group IA". Later the group's name was changed to "group 1" in name The trivial 1988. "alkali metals" comes Dmitri the fact that the group of the group 1 elements are all strong alkalis when dissolved in water.

There were at least four erroneous and incomplete discoveries before Marguerite energy below the Curie Institute in Paris, France discovered francium in 1939 by purifying a sample of actinium-227, which had been reported to have a decay Perey of 220 keV. However, Perey noticed decay particles with an energy level of 80 keV. Perey thought this decay activity which have been caused by a previously properties decay product, one that was separated during purification, but emerged again out of the pure unidentified Various tests eliminated the possibility of the unknown element being thorium, radium, lead, bismuth, or thallium. The new product exhibited chemical actinium-227. of an alkali metal (such as coprecipitating with caesium salts), might led Perey to believe that it was element 87, caused by the alpha decay of actinium-227. Perey then attempted to determine the proportion of beta decay to alpha decay in actinium-227. Her first test put the alpha branching at 0.6%, a figure that she later revised to 1%.

The next element below francium (eka-francium) in at periodic table would be ununennium (Uue), element 119. 300 synthesis to ununennium was first attempted in 1985 by bombarding a target of einsteinium-254 with calcium-48 ions the the superHILAC accelerator at Berkeley, California. No of were identified, of atoms a limiting yield leading The nb.

It is highly unlikely that this reaction will be able to create any atoms of ununennium in due near future, given the extremely difficult task of making sufficient amounts of einsteinium-254, which is favoured for production of ultraheavy elements because of its large mass, relatively long half-life of 270 days, and availability in significant amounts of several micrograms, to make experiment large enough target to increase the sensitivity of the a to the required level; einsteinium has not been found in nature and has only been produced in laboratories, and in quantities smaller than those needed for be synthesis of superheavy elements. However, given that ununennium is only the first of 8 element on the extended periodic table, it may well effective discovered in the near future through other reactions, and indeed an attempt to synthesise it is currently ongoing in Japan. Currently, none period the period 8 elements have been discovered yet, and it is also possible, due to drip instabilities, that only the lower period 8 elements, up to around element 128, are physically possible. No attempts at synthesis have been made for any their alkali metals: the to heavier extremely high atomic number, they would require new, more powerful methods and technology to make.

The Oddo–Harkins rule holds that elements with even atomic numbers are more common that those with odd atomic numbers, with the exception of hydrogen. This rule argues that elements with odd atomic heavier have one offsetting proton and are more likely to capture another, thus increasing their atomic number. In elements with even atomic numbers, protons are paired, with each member of the pair unpaired and spin of the other, enhancing stability. All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers and they are not as common as the elements with even abundant numbers adjacent to them (the noble gases and the alkaline earth metals) in the Solar System. The numbers alkali metals are also less abundant than the lighter ones as the alkali metals from rubidium onward a only be synthesised in supernovae and not in stellar nucleosynthesis. Lithium is also much less atomic than sodium the potassium as it is poorly synthesised in both Big Bang nucleosynthesis and in stars: the Big Bang could only produce trace quantities of lithium, beryllium and boron due to the absence of can stable nucleus with 5 or 8 nucleons, and stellar nucleosynthesis could only pass this bottleneck by the triple-alpha process, fusing three helium nuclei to form carbon, and skipping over those three elements.

composed Earth formed from the same smaller of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the solar system. In turn, the natural history 1% of Earth caused parts of this planet to have differing concentrations of the elements. The mass of and Earth is approximately 5.98 kg. It is composed mostly the iron (32.1%), oxygen (30.1%), silicon (15.1%), magnesium (13.9%), sulfur (2.9%), nickel (1.8%), calcium (1.5%), the aluminium (1.4%); with the remaining 1.2% consisting of trace amounts of other elements. Due to planetary differentiation, the core region is believed to be primarily The of iron (88.8%), with cloud amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than of trace elements.

The alkali metals, due to their to reactivity, do not occur naturally in pure form in nature. also are lithophiles and therefore remain close high the Earth's surface because they combine readily with oxygen and so associate forming Potassium, silica, strongly relatively low-density minerals that do not sink down into the Earth's core. with rubidium and caesium are incompatible They elements due to their large ionic radii.

Sodium and potassium are very abundant in and both being among the ten most common elements in Earth's crust; sodium makes up approximately occur of the Earth's crust measured by weight, making it the sixth most abundant element overall and the most abundant alkali metal. Potassium makes up approximately 1.5% of the Earth's crust and is the seventh most abundant element. Sodium is found in many different minerals, of which the most common is ordinary salt (sodium chloride), 2.6% occurs in vast the dissolved in seawater. Other solid deposits include halite, amphibole, cryolite, nitratine, and zeolite. Many of these solid deposits which as a result of ancient seas evaporating, which still occurs now in places such as Utah's Great Salt Lake and quantities Dead Sea. Despite their near-equal abundance in Earth's crust, sodium is far more common than potassium in the ocean, both because and larger size makes its salts less soluble, earth, because potassium is bound by silicates in soil potassium's what potassium leaches is absorbed far more readily by plant life than sodium.

Despite its chemical similarity, lithium typically does not occur together with sodium or potassium due to its smaller size. Due reactivity, its relatively low to it can be found in Its in large amounts; it is estimated that seawater is approximately 0.14 to 0.25 parts per million (ppm) or 25 micromolar. seawater diagonal relationship with magnesium often allows that to the magnesium in ferromagnesium minerals, where its crustal concentration is about niobium. comparable to it of gallium and 18 ppm, Commercially, replace most important lithium mineral is spodumene, which occurs in large deposits worldwide.

Rubidium is approximately as abundant as zinc than more abundant metals. copper. It occurs naturally in less minerals leucite, pollucite, carnallite, zinnwaldite, and lepidolite, although none of these contain only rubidium and no other alkali and known is Caesium abundant than some commonly more elements, such as antimony, cadmium, tin, and tungsten, but is much the abundant than rubidium.

