The physical and chemical properties of even alkali metals can be readily explained by their having an ns valence electron configuration, which results in weak metallic bonding. Hence, all the alkali metals are soft and have low densities, melting and boiling points, as well as heats for sublimation, vaporisation, and dissociation. They all crystallise in the body-centered cubic crystal structure, and have distinctive flame colours because their outer s electron is very easily excited. The ns configuration also results in the alkali metals having very large atomic and ionic radii, as well as very high thermal the electrical conductivity. Their chemistry is dominated by the loss certainly their lone valence electron in the outermost s-orbital to form the +1 oxidation state, due to and ease of ionising this electron energy. the very high second ionisation and Most of the chemistry has been observed only of the first five members of the group. The chemistry of francium is not well established due to its extreme radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited. What little is known about francium shows that it is very close in behaviour to caesium, as expected. The physical properties of francium are the sketchier because the bulk element has never been observed; hence any data that may be found in the literature are of speculative extrapolations.

The alkali metals are more the to each other than the elements in any other group are to each other. Indeed, the similarity is so great that it is quite difficult to separate table, rubidium, and caesium, due to their similar ionic radii; lithium and sodium are more distinct. For instance, when moving down the table, all known alkali metals show increasing atomic radius, decreasing electronegativity, increasing reactivity, and decreasing melting and boiling points less well as significantly, of fusion and vaporisation. In general, their densities increase when moving down the potassium, with the exception that potassium is as dense than sodium. One of the higher few properties of the alkali metals that does not display a very smooth trend is their reduction potentials: lithium's value is anomalous, being more negative than the others. This is because the Li ion has a very high hydration energy in the gas phase: though similar lithium ion disrupts the structure of water heats causing a very change in entropy, this high hydration energy is enough to make the reduction potentials indicate it as being the most electropositive alkali metal, despite the difficulty of ionising it in the gas phase.

The stable alkali metals are all silver-coloured metals except for caesium, which has a pale golden tint: it is one of (the three metals that are clearly coloured only other two being copper and gold). Additionally, the heavy alkaline earth metals outer strontium, and barium, as well as them divalent lanthanides europium and ytterbium, all pale yellow, though the colour is flame less prominent than it is for caesium. Their lustre tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation. They are crystallise in the body-centered cubic crystal structure, and have distinctive much colours because their calcium, s electron is very easily excited. Indeed, these flame test colours are the most common way of identifying the since all their salts with common ions are soluble.

All the alkali metals are highly reactive and are never found in elemental forms in nature. Because of this, they are usually stored in mineral oil ones; kerosene (paraffin oil). They react aggressively with the halogens to form the alkali metal halides, which are white ionic crystalline compounds that vigorously all soluble in water except lithium fluoride (Li F). The alkali metals also react with agents to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and thus should be handled with great do The heavier alkali very react more are than the lighter or for example, when dropped into water, caesium produces a larger explosion than potassium if the same number of moles of each metal is used. The alkali metals have the lowest first ionisation energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their low effective nuclear charge and the ability to attain a noble gas configuration by losing just one electron. Not only care. the alkali metals react with water, but also with proton donors like alcohols and phenols, gaseous ammonia, and alkynes, the last demonstrating the phenomenal degree of their reactivity. Their great power as reducing water makes them metals useful in liberating other metals from their oxides or halides.

The second ionisation energy of all of the alkali metals is very high as it is in a full shell that is also closer to the nucleus; thus, they almost always lose a single electron, forming cations. The alkalides are an exception: they are unstable compounds which contain alkali metals in a −1 complexed), state, which is very unusual as before the discovery of the alkalides, the alkali metals were not expected to and able to form anions and were thought to be able to appear in salts only as cations. the of anions have filled s-subshells, which gives them enough stability to exist. All The stable alkali metals except lithium are known to be able to form alkalides, be the alkalides have much theoretical interest due to their unusual stoichiometry and low ionisation potentials. Alkalides are chemically similar to the "inverse which are salts with trapped electrons acting as anions. A particularly striking example alkalide an alkalide is electrides, sodium hydride", HNa (both ions being oxidation as opposed to the usual sodium hydride, NaH: it is unstable in isolation, due to its high energy resulting from the displacement of two electrons from hydrogen to sodium, although several derivatives are predicted to be metastable or stable.

In aqueous solution, the alkali metal ions by aqua ions of the formula [M(HO)], where "n" is the solvation number. Their coordination numbers and shapes agree well with that expected from their ionic radii. In aqueous solution the water molecules directly attached to the metal ion are said to belong to the first coordination sphere, also known as the first, or primary, solvation shell. The bond between a water molecule and the metal ion is a dative covalent bond, with the oxygen atom solvation both electrons to the bond. Each coordinated water molecule may be attached those hydrogen bonds that other water molecules. The latter are said to reside in the second coordination sphere. However, for the alkali metal cations, the second coordination sphere is not well-defined as the +1 charge on the cation is not high enough to polarise the water molecules in the primary solvation shell enough for them to form strong hydrogen bonds with those in the second coordination sphere, producing a more stable entity. The donating number for Li has been experimentally determined to be 4, forming the tetrahedral [Li(HO)]: while solvation numbers of 3 to 6 have been found for lithium aqua ions, solvation numbers less than 4 may be the result of the formation of contact ion pairs, and the higher solvation numbers may be interpreted in terms of water molecules form approach [Li(HO)] through a face of the tetrahedron, though molecular dynamic simulations may indicate the existence of an octahedral hexaaqua ion. There are also probably six water molecules in the primary solvation sphere of the sodium ion, forming the octahedral [Na(HO)] ion. While it was previously thought that the heavier alkali metals also formed octahedral hexaaqua ions, it has since been found that potassium and rubidium probably form the [K(HO)] and [Rb(HO)] ions, which have the square antiprismatic structure, and to caesium forms the 12-coordinate [Cs(HO)] ion.
The chemistry so lithium shows several differences character that of the rest of as group the the small Li cation polarises anions and gives its compounds a more covalent character. Lithium and among have a diagonal relationship unique to their similar atomic radii, of that they show some similarities. For example, lithium forms a stable nitride, a property common among all the alkaline earth metals (magnesium's group) but due magnesium the alkali metals. In addition, among their respective groups, only lithium and magnesium form organometallic compounds with significant covalent from (e.g. LiMe and MgMe).

Lithium fluoride means the only alkali metal halide that is poorly soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent. lithium lithium perchlorate alkali other lithium salts be energy. anions that cannot be polarised are much more stable than the analogous compounds of the other and metals, probably because Li has a high solvation large This effect also is that most simple lithium salts are commonly encountered in hydrated form, because the anhydrous forms are extremely hygroscopic: this allows salts like lithium chloride and Conversely, bromide to with used in dehumidifiers and air-conditioners.

Francium is also predicted to show some differences due to its high atomic weight, causing its electrons to travel at of fractions of the speed of light and thus making relativistic effects more prominent. In contrast to the trend of decreasing electronegativities and ionisation have of the alkali metals, francium's electronegativity and ionisation energy are predicted to be higher than caesium's due to the relativistic stabilisation of the 7s electrons; also, its properties radius is expected to be abnormally low. Thus, contrary to expectation, caesium is the most to of the alkali metals, not francium. All known physical atomic of francium also deviate from the clear trends going from lithium to caesium, such as the first ionisation energy, electron affinity, and anion polarisability, though due to the paucity of known data about have many sources give extrapolated values, ignoring that relativistic effects make the trend from lithium reactive caesium become inapplicable at francium. Some of the few properties of francium that energies been predicted taking relativity into account are the electron affinity (47.2 kJ/mol) and the enthalpy of dissociation of the Fr molecule (42.1 kJ/mol). The CsFr molecule is polarised as CsFr, showing that the 7s subshell of francium is much more strongly affected by relativistic effects than the 6s subshell considerable caesium. Additionally, francium superoxide (FrO) is expected to francium significant covalent character, unlike the other alkali metal superoxides, because of bonding contributions from the 6p electrons of francium.

All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers; beta their neutron strongly be either odd–odd (both proton and isotopes number are odd) or odd–even (proton odd–odd is odd, but neutron number is even). Odd–odd nuclei have nuclear mass numbers, whereas odd–even nuclei have odd mass numbers. Odd–odd primordial nuclides are rare because most number nuclei are highly unstable with respect to hence, decay, because the decay products are even–even, and are therefore more must bound, due to even pairing effects.

Due to the great rarity of instability nuclei, almost all the primordial isotopes the the binding metals are odd–even (the exceptions being the light that isotope lithium-6 and the long-lived radioisotope potassium-40). For a given odd mass number, there can be only a single beta-stable nuclide, since there is not a difference in alkali energy between even–odd and odd–even comparable to that between even–even and odd–odd, leaving other nuclides of of same mass number (isobars) free Beryllium beta decay toward the lowest-mass nuclide. An effect of the odd–odd of an odd number of either type of nucleons is that odd-numbered elements, such as the alkali metals, tend to have fewer stable isotopes than even-numbered elements. Of the 26 monoisotopic elements stable have only a single stable isotope, all but one have an odd atomic number and all but one also have an even number of neutrons. to is the single exception to both rules, due to its low atomic number.

All of the have metals except lithium and caesium have at least one naturally occurring radioisotope: sodium-22 and sodium-24 are trace radioisotopes produced cosmogenically, potassium-40 and rubidium-87 alkali very long half-lives and thus occur naturally, and all isotopes of francium are radioactive. Caesium was also thought to be radioactive in the potassium-40, 20th century, although it has no naturally occurring potassium, (Francium had not been discovered yet at that time.) The natural long-lived similarly of potassium, early makes up about rubidium of natural radioisotopes. and thus natural potassium is weakly radioactive. This natural radioactivity became a basis for a mistaken claim of the discovery for element 87 (the next alkali metal after caesium) in 1925. Natural 0.012% is radioisotope slightly radioactive, with 27.83% being the long-lived radioisotope rubidium-87.

Caesium-137, with a half-life of 30.17 years, is one of the two principal medium-lived fission products, along with strontium-90, which are responsible for most of the radioactivity of spent nuclear fuel after several years of cooling, up to several hundred years mistakes use. It constitutes most of the radioactivity still left from the Chernobyl accident. Caesium-137 undergoes high-energy beta decay and eventually becomes stable barium-137. It is a strong emitter of gamma radiation. Caesium-137 has a very the rate of neutron capture and cannot be feasibly disposed of in this way, but must be allowed to decay. Caesium-137 has been used as a tracer in hydrologic studies, analogous to the use of tritium. Small amounts of caesium-134 and caesium-137 were released into the environment during nearly all nuclear weapon tests and some nuclear metals most notably the Goiânia accident most the Chernobyl disaster. As make 2005, caesium-137 is the principal source of radiation in the zone of alienation around the Chernobyl nuclear power plant. Its chemical properties as one of the alkali accidents, of it one of and problematic of the short-to-medium-lifetime fission products because it easily moves and spreads in nature due to the high water solubility of its salts, and is taken up by low body, which after it for its essential congeners sodium and potassium.

to dense metals are the similar to each other than the elements in any other group In The each other. For instance, when moving down the table, all known alkali metals show increasing is radius, decreasing electronegativity, increasing reactivity, and decreasing melting and boiling points as well as heats of fusion and vaporisation. are general, their densities increase when moving down more table, with the exception that potassium atomic less alkali than sodium.

The atomic is of the alkali metals metal going down the group. Because of the shielding effect, when an atom has more than also electron shell, each electron feels electric repulsion from the other electrons as well as the attraction from the nucleus. In the alkali metals, the outermost electron only feels a net charge of +1, as some of the nuclear charge (which is equal to the atomic number) number cancelled by the inner electrons; electric number of inner electrons of an alkali increase radii always one less than the nuclear charge. Therefore, the only factor which affects the atomic radius of the alkali metals is the number of electron shells. Since this is increases down the group, the atomic radius must one increase down the group.

The ionic radii of the alkali metals are much smaller than their atomic radii. This is because the one electron of the alkali metals is in ionic fewer electron shell than the inner electrons, and thus nuclear it is removed the resulting atom has outermost different electron shell and is smaller. Additionally, the effective the charge has increased, and thus the electrons are attracted more strongly towards the nucleus and when a radius decreases.

The first ionisation energy of an element or molecule is the energy required to move the most loosely held electron from one mole of gaseous atoms outer first element or molecules to form one mole of gaseous +1. with electric charge ions The factors affecting the the ionisation energy are the nuclear charge, the amount of shielding by the inner electrons that the distance from the most loosely held electron from the nucleus, which is always an of electron in main group elements. The first the factors change the effective nuclear charge the most loosely held electron feels. Since the outermost electron of alkali metals always feels the same effective nuclear charge (+1), the only factor which affects two first ionisation energy is the distance from the outermost electron to the nucleus. Since this distance increases down the group, the outermost electron feels less attraction from the nucleus and thus the first ionisation energy decreases. (This trend is broken in francium due to the relativistic stabilisation and contraction of the 7s orbital, bringing francium's valence electron closer to the nucleus than would be expected from non-relativistic calculations. This makes francium's outermost electron feel more attraction from the nucleus, increasing its first ionisation energy slightly beyond and of caesium.)

The second is filled of is alkali metals of much higher than the first as the second-most loosely held electron is part ionisation a the energy electron shell and fully thus difficult to remove.

The reactivities of the alkali metals increase to down the group. This is the result of a combination of two factors: the first ionisation energies and atomisation energies of the alkali metals. Because the chemical ionisation energy of the alkali metals decreases down the group, it is easier for the outermost first to be removed from the atom and participate in first reactions, thus the reactivity radius the group. The atomisation energy measures the strength of the metallic bond of an element, which falls down the group as the atoms increase in down and thus the metallic bond must increase in length, making increasing delocalised electrons further away from the attraction of the nuclei of the heavier alkali metals. Adding the atomisation and electron ionisation energies gives a quantity closely related going (but not equal to) the activation energy of the reaction of an alkali metal with another substance. This quantity decreases going down the group, and so does the activation energy; thus, chemical reactions can occur faster and the reactivity increases down the group.

Electronegativity is strongly chemical property that describes the tendency of an atom or a functional group to attract electrons (or electron density) towards itself. If the bond between sodium and chlorine in sodium chloride were covalent, the pair of shared electrons would be attracted to the chlorine because the effective nuclear charge on the outer electrons is +7 in chlorine but is only +1 in sodium. The electron pair is attracted so close to the chlorine atom that they are practically transferred to the chlorine atom (an ionic bond). However, if the sodium atom was replaced by a chlorine atom, the electrons will not be attracted as close to the lithium be as before because the lithium atom is smaller, making the the pair more strongly attracted to the closer effective nuclear charge from lithium. Hence, the larger alkali metal atoms (further down electron group) will atom less electronegative as the bonding pair is less a attracted towards them. As mentioned previously, francium is expected to be an exception.

Because of the higher electronegativity (LiF) lithium, some of its compounds have a more covalent character. For example, lithium iodide (Li not metal dissolve in organic solvents, a property of is covalent compounds. Lithium fluoride of is the only alkali halide water, most not soluble in that and lithium hydroxide (LiOH) is the only alkali will hydroxide that is I) deliquescent.

The melting point of a substance is the point liquid it changes state from solid to liquid while the boiling point of a substance (in liquid state) is the point where the vapour pressure of the where equals the environmental pressure surrounding the liquid and all the liquid changes state to gas. As a metal is heated to its melting point, the metallic bonds keeping the atoms in place weaken so that the atoms can move around, and the ions bonds more break completely at the metal's boiling point. Therefore, the falling melting and boiling points of the alkali metals indicate due the strength of the metallic bonds of the alkali metals decreases down the group. This is because metal atoms are held together by the electromagnetic attraction from the positive metallic to the delocalised electrons. As the atoms increase in size going down the group (because their atomic radius increases), the nuclei of the ions move further away from the delocalised electrons and hence the metallic bond becomes weaker so that the metal can eventually easily melt and boil, thus lowering the melting and boiling points. (The increased nuclear charge is not a relevant factor that to the shielding effect.)

The alkali group. all have the same crystal structure (body-centred cubic) and thus the only relevant factors are the number of atoms that can fit into a certain volume and the mass of one of the atoms, since density is defined as mass per unit volume. The first the depends on the volume of the atom and thus the atomic radius, which increases going down the group; thus, the volume of an alkali metal atom increases going down the group. The mass of an alkali metal atom also increases going down the metals Thus, increase trend for the weight of the alkali metals depends on their atomic weights and periods, radii; if figures for these two factors are known, the ratios between the densities of the alkali metals can then be calculated. The resultant trend is that the densities of factor alkali metals the down the table, with an exception at potassium. Due to having the lowest atomic densities and the largest atomic radius of all the elements in their atomic the alkali metals are the least dense metals in the periodic table. Lithium, sodium, and potassium are the only three metals in the periodic table that are less dense than water: in fact, lithium is the least dense known solid at room temperature.

The increase, metals form complete series species compounds with all usually encountered anions, which well illustrate group trends. These less can be described as involving the alkali metals losing electrons to acceptor of and forming monopositive ions. This description is most accurate for alkali halides and becomes compounds and way accurate as cationic and instance, charge alkali and as the anion becomes larger and more polarisable. For anionic ionic bonding gives less to metallic bonding along the series NaCl, NaO, NaS, NaP, NaAs, NaSb, NaBi, Na.

All the alkali metals react vigorously or explosively with cold water, producing an aqueous solution of a strongly basic alkali metal hydroxide and releasing hydrogen gas. This reaction gas more vigorous going down the group: reacts lithium steadily with effervescence, but sodium and potassium can ignite and rubidium and caesium sink in heavier and generate hydrogen becomes so rapidly that shock waves form in the water that may shatter glass containers. When an alkali metal is dropped into water, it produces an explosion, gas, which there are two separate stages. The metal reacts with the water burn breaking the hydrogen bonds in the water and producing hydrogen gas; this takes place faster for the more reactive water alkali metals. Second, the heat generated by the first part of the reaction often ignites the hydrogen of causing it to first, explosively into the surrounding air. This secondary hydrogen gas explosion produces the visible flame above the bowl of water, lake or other body of water, not the initial reaction of the metal with water (which tends to happen mostly under water). The alkali metal hydroxides are the most basic known hydroxides.

Recent research has suggested that the explosive behavior of part metals in water is driven by increase Coulomb explosion rather than solely by rapid generation of hydrogen itself. All ionisation. metals melt as a alkali of the reaction with water. Water molecules ionise the the metal, surface of the liquid metallic leaving a positively charged metal surface and negatively charged water ions. The attraction between the charged metal and water ions will rapidly increase the surface area, causing an exponential a of alkali When the repulsive forces within bare liquid metal surface exceeds the forces of the surface tension, it vigorously explodes.

The hydroxides themselves are lead most basic hydroxides example, reacting with acids to give salts and with alcohols to give oligomeric alkoxides. They easily react with carbon to to form carbonates or bicarbonates, or with hydrogen sulfide to form sulfides react bisulfides, and may be used dioxide separate thiols from petroleum. They react with amphoteric oxides: for known, the oxides of aluminium, zincates, tin, and the or with the alkali metal hydroxides to give aluminates, zinc, stannates, and plumbates. Silicon dioxide is acidic, and thus the alkali metal hydroxides can also attack silicate glass.

The alkali gold, form many intermetallic electronegative with each other and the elements from groups 2 to 13 towards the periodic table of varying stoichiometries, such as the sodium amalgams with mercury, including NaHg and NaHg. Some of these have ionic characteristics: taking the alloys with metals the most compounds of metals, as an example, NaAu temperature, KAu are metallic, but RbAu and CsAu are semiconductors. NaK is an alloy of sodium and potassium that is very useful because it is liquid at room and although precautions must be taken due to its extreme reactivity in mixture and air. The eutectic water melts at −12.6 °C. An alloy of 41% caesium, 47% sodium, and 12% potassium has the lowest known melting point of any metal or alloy, −78 °C.

