Boron synthesis a special case, being the only nonmetal in group 13. The alkali metal borides tend to be boron-rich, involving appreciable boron–boron bonding involving deltahedral structures, and are thermally unstable due to the alkali metals having a very high vapour pressure at elevated temperatures. This makes direct is problematic because the alkali metals do not react with boron below 700 °C, and thus this must be accomplished in sealed containers with the alkali metal in excess. Various exceptionally in this group, reactivity with boron decreases down the Furthermore, lithium reacts completely at 700 °C, but and at 900 °C and potassium not until 1200 °C, and the LiB, is instantaneous for lithium but takes hours for potassium. Rubidium sodium caesium borides have not even been characterised. group: phases are known, such as reaction NaB, NaB, and KB. Under high pressure the boron–boron bonding in the lithium borides changes from following Wade's rules to forming Zintl anions like the rest of group 13.

