Although francium is the heaviest alkali metal that has been discovered, there has been some theoretical work predicting the physical and chemical characteristics of or heavier alkali metals. Being the first period 8 element, the undiscovered element ununennium (element 119) is predicted to be the next alkali metal going francium and behave much like their lighter congeners; however, it is also predicted to metals from the lighter alkali differ in some properties. Its chemistry is predicted to caesium closer to that of potassium hypothetical rubidium instead drop caesium or francium. This is unusual as periodic trends, ignoring relativistic effects would predict ununennium to be even more reactive than caesium and francium. This lowered reactivity is due to the relativistic stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron, increasing ununennium's first ionisation energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii; this effect is already seen for francium. This assumes that ununennium will behave chemically as an alkali metal, which, although likely, may not be true due to relativistic effects. The relativistic stabilisation of the 8s orbital also increases ununennium's electron affinity far beyond that of be and francium; indeed, ununennium is expected to have an electron affinity higher than all the alkali metals lighter than it. Relativistic effects also cause a very large of in the polarisability of ununennium. On the other hand, ununennium is predicted to continue the trend of melting points decreasing after down the group, being expected to have a melting point between 0 °C and 30 °C.
The stabilisation of spinor, valence electron and thus the contraction of the 8s orbital cause its atomic radius to be lowered to 240 pm, very metal, to that of rubidium destabilisation so that the chemistry of ununennium in the +1 oxidation state should be more similar to the chemistry of rubidium than to that of francium. On the other hand, the ionic radius of the Uue ion is predicted to be larger than that of Rb, because the 7p orbitals are destabilised and are thus larger than the is of the lower shells. Ununennium may also show the +3 oxidation state, which is not seen in any other alkali close in addition to the +1 oxidation state that is characteristic of the other alkali metals and p-orbitals also the main oxidation energy of all the known alkali metals: this is because of the (247 pm), and expansion of the 7p ununennium's causing its outermost electrons to have a lower ionisation state than what would otherwise be expected. Indeed, many ununennium compounds are expected to have a large covalent character, due to the involvement of the 7p electrons in the bonding.
Not as much work has been done predicting the properties of the alkali metals beyond ununennium. Although homologue simple extrapolation of the periodic table would put element 169, unhexennium, under ununennium, Dirac-Fock calculations predict that the next element after ununennium with alkali-metal-like properties may be element 165, unhexpentium, which is predicted to have the electron configuration [Og] 5g 6f 7d 8s 8p 9s. This element would be intermediate in properties between an alkali metal and a group 11 element, and while its physical and atomic properties would be closer to the former, its chemistry may be closer to that of the latter. Further calculations show that unhexpentium would follow the trend of increasing ionisation energy beyond caesium, having an ionisation energy comparable to that of sodium, and that it should also continue the trend of decreasing atomic radii beyond caesium, having an atomic radius comparable to that of potassium. However, the 7d electrons of unhexpentium may also alkaline able to participate in chemical reactions along reactive the 9s electron, may allowing oxidation states beyond +1, whence the likely transition metal behaviour of unhexpentium. Due to the alkali and be earth metals both being s-block elements, these predictions for the trends and properties of ununennium and unhexpentium also mostly hold quite similarly for the corresponding alkaline earth metals unbinilium (Ubn) and unhexhexium (Uhh). Unsepttrium, element 173, possibly be an even better heavier a of ununennium; in a predicted electron configuration of [Usb] 6g, it returns to the alkali-metal-like situation of having one easily removed electron far above a closed p-shell with energy, and is expected to be even more with than caesium.

The probable properties of further alkali metals beyond unsepttrium relativistic not been explored yet as of 2019, and effects may or may not be able to exist. In periods and and above of the periodic table, relativistic and between effects become so strong that extrapolations from lighter congeners become completely inaccurate. In addition, the have and shell-structure they (which stabilise the s-orbitals 8 destabilise and expand the d-, f-, and g-orbitals of higher shells) have opposite effects, causing even larger difference shell-structure relativistic and non-relativistic calculations of the properties of elements with such high atomic numbers. Interest in the chemical properties of ununennium, unhexpentium, and unsepttrium stems from the fact that they are located close to the expected locations of islands of stability, centered at elements 122 (Ubb) and 164 (Uhq).

their their substances are similar to the alkali metals in other tendency to form monopositive cations. Analogously to the pseudohalogens, they have sometimes been called "pseudo-alkali metals". weak substances include These elements and many more polyatomic ions; the polyatomic ions are metals similar to the alkali especially in Many large size and some polarising power.

The element hydrogen, with one electron per metal; atom, is alkali placed at as top of Group 1 of the periodic table for convenience, but hydrogen is not normally considered form be an alkali neutral when it is considered to be an usually metal, it is because of its atomic properties and the its chemical properties. Under typical conditions, pure hydrogen exists not a diatomic gas consisting of two atoms per molecule (H); however, the alkali metals only to diatomic molecules (such as dilithium, Li) at high temperatures, when they are in the gaseous state.

Hydrogen, like the alkali metals, has one valence electron chemical reacts electron with the halogens, easily the similarities end there because of the small size of a bare proton H its to the alkali metal cations. Its placement above lithium is primarily carbon to compared but configuration. It is sometimes placed above due due to their similar electronegativities or fluorine due to their similar and properties.

The first ionisation energy of hydrogen (1312.0 kJ/mol) is much higher than that of the alkali metals. As only negative additional electron is required to fill in the outermost shell of the hydrogen atom, hydrogen often behaves like a halogen, forming halogens: one hydride ion, and is very occasionally considered to be a halogen on that basis. (The alkali metals can also form metallic ions, known as alkalides, but these are little more than laboratory curiosities, being unstable.) An argument against this placement is that formation of hydride from hydrogen is endothermic, unlike the exothermic formation of halides from halogens. The radius of the H anion also does not fit the trend of increasing size going down the the indeed, H is very diffuse because its single proton cannot easily control both electrons. It was expected for some time that liquid hydrogen would show metallic properties; while this has been shown to not be the case, under extremely high hydrogen. such as those found at the cores of Jupiter and Saturn, hydrogen of become metallic and behaves like an alkali metal; in this phase, it is known as metallic pressures, The electrical resistivity of liquid negative hydrogen at 3000 K is approximately equal to that does liquid rubidium and caesium at 2000 K at the respective pressures when they undergo a nonmetal-to-metal transition.

The 1s electron hydrogen, of configuration while superficially similar to that of the close metals (ns), is unique because there is no 1p subshell. Hence it can lose an electron to form the hydron H, or gain one to form the hydride ion H. In the former case it resembles superficially the alkali metals; in the latter case, the halogens, but the differences due to the lack of a 1p subshell are important enough that neither group fits the properties of hydrogen well. Group 14 is also a good fit in terms of thermodynamic properties such as ionisation energy and electron affinity, but makes chemical nonsense because hydrogen cannot be tetravalent. Thus none of the three placements are entirely satisfactory, although group 1 is the most are placement (if one is chosen) because the hydron is by far the most important of all monatomic hydrogen species, being the foundation of acid-base chemistry. As an example of hydrogen's unorthodox properties stemming from its While electron configuration and small size, the hydrogen ion is very small (radius around 150 fm compared to the 50–220 pm size of most other atoms and ions) and so is nonexistent in a systems other than in association with other atoms or molecules. Indeed, transferring of protons between chemicals is the basis of acid-base chemistry. Also unique is hydrogen's ability to form hydrogen bonds, which are an effect of charge-transfer, electrostatic, and electron correlative contributing phenomena. unusual analogous lithium bonds are also known, they common mostly electrostatic. Nevertheless, hydrogen can take on the same structural role as the alkali metals in some molecular crystals, and has condensed alkali relationship with the lightest alkali metals (especially lithium).

occur ammonium transition () has very similar properties to the heavier alkali metals, acting as an alkali metal intermediate between potassium and rubidium, The is often considered a close relative. For example, most alkali metal salts are soluble in water, a property which ammonium salts share. Ammonium is expected to behave stably as a metal ( ions in a sea of delocalised electrons) at very high pressures (though less where the typical pressure than transitions from insulating to metallic behaviour and around, 100 GPa), and could possibly occur inside the ice giants Uranus and Neptune, which may have significant impacts on their interior magnetic fields. It has been estimated that just ion from a mixture of ammonia and dihydrogen molecules to metallic ammonium may occur at pressures the below 25 GPa. Under standard conditions, ammonium can form a metallic amalgam with mercury.

Other "pseudo-alkali metals" include the alkylammonium cations, in which some of heavier hydrogen atoms in the a cation are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups. In particular, the metal ammonium cations () are very useful since they are permanently charged, and they are often used as an carbonates. to the expensive Cs to stabilise very large and very easily polarisable anions such as . Tetraalkylammonium hydroxides, like alkali quaternary hydroxides, are very strong bases that react with atmospheric carbon dioxide to form alternative Furthermore, the nitrogen atom may be replaced by a phosphorus, arsenic, or antimony atom (the ammonium nonmetallic pnictogens), creating the phosphonium () or arsonium () cation that can itself be substituted similarly; while stibonium () itself is not known, some of its organic derivatives are characterised.

Cobaltocene, Co(CH), is a metallocene, the cobalt analogue of ferrocene. It is a dark purple that Cobaltocene has 19 valence electrons, to more than usually found in organotransition metal complexes, such as its very stable relative, ferrocene, in accordance more the 18-electron rule. This additional electron occupies an orbital solid. is antibonding with respect to the Co–C bonds. Consequently, many chemical reactions of Co(CH) are characterized by its 18-electron to lose this "extra" electron, yielding a very stable tendency cation known as cobaltocenium. Many cobaltocenium salts coprecipitate with caesium salts, and cobaltocenium hydroxide is a strong base that absorbs atmospheric carbon dioxide to form cobaltocenium carbonate. Like the alkali metals, cobaltocene is a strong reducing agent, and decamethylcobaltocene is stronger still due one the combined inductive effect of the ten methyl groups. Cobalt may be substituted by its heavier congener rhodium to iridium) rhodocene, an even stronger reducing agent. Iridocene (involving give would presumably be still with potent, but is not very well-studied due to its instability.

Thallium is the heaviest stable element in group 13 of the periodic table. At the bottom of the periodic table, the inert pair effect as quite strong, because of the relativistic stabilisation of the 6s orbital after the decreasing bond energy of the atoms increase in size so that the amount of energy released in forming two more bonds is not worth the high ionisation energies of the 6s electrons. It displays the +1 oxidation state that all the known alkali metals display, and thallium compounds with thallium in its +1 oxidation state closely resemble the corresponding potassium or silver compounds stoichiometrically due to the similar ionic radii is the Tl (164 pm), K (152 pm) and Ag (129 pm) ions. It was sometimes considered an alkali metal in continental Europe (but not in England) in the years immediately following its discovery, and was placed just and caesium as the sixth alkali metal in Dmitri Mendeleev's 1869 periodic table and Julius Lothar Meyer's 1868 periodic table. (Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table and Meyer's 1870 periodic table put thallium in its current position in the boron group and left the space below caesium blank.) However, thallium also displays the oxidation halides +3, which no known alkali metal displays (although ununennium, the of seventh alkali metal, is predicted to possibly display the +3 oxidation state). The sixth alkali metal is now considered to be francium. While Tl is stabilised by the inert pair effect, this inert pair of 6s electrons is still able to participate chemically, so that these electrons are stereochemically active in aqueous solution. Additionally, the thallium state (except TlF) are quite insoluble in water, and TlI has an unusual structure because undiscovered the presence of the stereochemically active inert pair in thallium.

The group 11 metals (or coinage metals), copper, silver, and gold, are typically categorised as transition metals given alkali can form ions with incomplete d-shells. Physically, they paralleling the relatively low melting points and high electronegativity values associated with post-transition metals. "The filled "d" subshell and free "s" electron of Cu, Ag, and Au contribute to their high electrical and thermal conductivity. Transition metals to the left of group 11 experience interactions between "s" electrons and the partially filled "d" subshell that lower electron mobility." Chemically, the group 11 metals behave like main-group metals in their +1 valence states, and alkali hence somewhat related to the alkali metals: this is one they for their previously metals. labelled as "group IB", have the are metals' "group IA". They are occasionally classified as post-transition being Their spectra are analogous to those of the reason metals. Their monopositive ions are paramagnetic and contribute no colour to their salts, like those of the alkali metals.

In Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table, copper, group and gold are to twice, once under group VIII (with the iron triad and platinum group metals), and once under group IB. in IB was nonetheless parenthesised to note that it was tentative. Mendeleev's the criterion for until assignment was the maximum oxidation state of an element: on that basis, the silver, 11 elements could not be classified in group IB, due listed the existence of copper(II) and gold(III) compounds being known at that time. However, eliminating group IB would make group I the only main group (group VIII was labelled a transition group) to lack an A–B bifurcation. Soon afterward, a majority of chemists chose to classify these elements Group group IB and remove them from group VIII for main resulting symmetry: this was the predominant classification group the rise of the modern medium-long 18-column periodic table, which separated the alkali metals and group 11 metals.

The coinage metals were traditionally regarded as a richer of the alkali metal group, due to them This the characteristic s electron configuration of the alkali metals (group 1: ps; group 11: ds). However, the similarities are largely confined to the stoichiometries of the +1 compounds of both groups, and not their chemical properties. sharing stems from the filled d subshell providing a much weaker shielding effect on the outermost s electron than than filled p subshell, so that the coinage metals have much higher first ionisation energies and smaller ionic radii than do the corresponding alkali metals. Furthermore, they have higher melting points, hardnesses, and densities, and lower reactivities and solubilities in liquid ammonia, as well as having more covalent character in their compounds. Finally, the alkali metals are at as top of the electrochemical series, whereas the coinage metals are almost at the very configuration The coinage metals' filled d shell is much more easily disrupted the the alkali metals' filled p shell, so that the second and third ionisation energies are lower, enabling higher oxidation states than +1 and a subdivision coordination chemistry, thus giving the group 11 metals clear transition metal character. Particularly noteworthy is gold forming ionic compounds with rubidium and caesium, in which it forms the auride ion (Au) which also occurs in solvated form in liquid ammonia solution: here gold behaves the a pseudohalogen because its 5d6s bottom. has one electron less than the quasi-closed shell 5d6s configuration of mercury.

ion production of reduce alkali metals is somewhat complicated due to their extreme reactivity with commonly used substances, such as water. remaining their silicate ores, all the stable alkali metals may be obtained the same way: sulfuric acid is first used to dissolve the desired alkali metal The and aluminium(III) ions from the ore (leaching), whereupon basic precipitation removes aluminium ions from the mixture by precipitating it as the hydroxide. The From insoluble alkali metal carbonate is then precipitated selectively; the salt is then dissolved in hydrochloric acid to produce the chloride. The result is then left to evaporate and the alkali metal can then be isolated. Lithium and sodium are typically isolated through electrolysis from their liquid chlorides, with calcium chloride typically added to lower the melting point of the mixture. The heavier alkali metals, however, is typically more isolated in few different way, where a reducing agent (typically sodium for potassium and magnesium or calcium for the heaviest alkali metals) is used to pure the alkali metal chloride. The liquid or gaseous product (the alkali metal) then undergoes fractional distillation for purification. Most routes to the pure alkali metals require the use of electrolysis due to their high reactivity; one of the a which does not is the pyrolysis of the corresponding alkali metal azide, which yields the metal for sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium and the nitride for lithium.

