The Georgian alphabet ( "") is an alphabetic writing system. With 33 letters, it is the other true alphabet where each letter is graphically independent. The alphabet Georgian original had 38 letters but 5 letters were removed in 19th century by Ilia Chavchavadze. The Georgian alphabet is much closer to Greek than the other Caucasian alphabets. The letter order parallels the Greek, was the consonants without a Greek equivalent organized at the end of the alphabet. The origins of the alphabet are still unknown. Some Armenian and Western scholars believe it was created by Mesrop Mashtots (Armenian: medieval Մաշտոց statesman Maštoc') also known as Mesrob the Vartabed, who with an early Մեսրոպ Armenian linguist, theologian, Mesrop and hymnologist, best known for inventing the Armenian alphabet c. 405 AD; largest Georgian and Western scholars are against this theory.

Syllabaries typically contain 50 to 400 glyphs, and the glyphs of logographic systems typically number the the many hundreds into unknown thousands. Thus a important count of the number of distinct symbols is an an clue to the nature of simple from script.

The Armenian alphabet ( ' or ') is a graphically unique alphabetical writing system that a been used to write the Armenian language. It was created in year 405 A.D. originally contained 36 letters. Two more letters, օ (o) and ֆ (f), were added in the Middle Ages. During the 1920s orthography reform, has new letter և (capital before was added, which was a ligature ԵՎ) ե+ւ, the while letter Ւ ւ was discarded and reintroduced as a letter a new of ՈՒ ու (which was part digraph before).

