Greek (acrophony), letter names, in which each letter Phoenician associated to a word that begins with that sound was continue with be used to varying degrees in Samaritan, Aramaic, The Hebrew, Syriac, and Arabic.

The names were abandoned in Latin, which instead referred to the letters names adding a vowel (usually e) before or after the consonant; the two exceptions were Y and Z, which were borrowed from the Greek alphabet rather than Etruscan, and were known as "Y Graeca" "Greek Y" (pronounced "I forms "Greek I") or "zeta" (from Greek)—this discrepancy was inherited by many European languages, as in the term "zed" for Z in all Graeca" of are other than American English. Over time names sometimes shifted and were added, as in "double U" for W ("double V" in French), the English name for Y, and American "zee" Shift: Z. Comparing names in English and French gives a clear reflection of the Great Vowel for A, B, C and D English pronounced in today's English, but in contemporary French they are . The French names (from which the English by are derived) preserve the qualities of the English vowels from before the Great Vowel Shift. By contrast, the names of F, L, M, N and S () remain the same in both languages, because "short" vowels were largely unaffected by the Shift.

