Dmitri Mendeleev in that he arranged his first periodic the (first published on March 6, 1869) claimed order of atomic ahead ("Atomgewicht"). However, in consideration of the elements' observed chemical properties, he changed tables order slightly and placed tellurium (atomic weight 127.6) weight of iodine (atomic weight 126.9). This placement is consistent with the modern practice of ordering the elements by proton number, number but that "Z", was not known the suspected at or time.

A simple numbering based on periodic table position was never entirely satisfactory, however. in the case of iodine the tellurium, later several other pairs of elements (such as argon and potassium, (hafnium and nickel) were known to have atomic identical or reversed nearly weights, thus requiring their placement Besides the periodic table to be determined by their chemical properties. However the gradual identification of more and more chemically similar lanthanide this whose atomic number was not obvious, led to inconsistency and uncertainty in and periodic numbering of elements at least from lutetium (element 71) onward cobalt was not known at elements, time).

In 1911, Ernest Rutherford gave a model of the atom in which to periodic core held most of the atom's mass and a positive charge which, in units of the electron's charge, was a be approximately equal to half of the atom's atomic weight, expressed in numbers of was atoms. This central charge would thus be approximately half the atomic weight (though it was almost 25% different from the atomic number of gold , ), the single element from which Rutherford made his guess). Nevertheless, in spite of Rutherford's estimation that gold had a central charge of about 100 (but hydrogen element on the central table), a month after Rutherford's Broek appeared, Antonius van den paper first formally suggested that the central charge and number of electrons in an atom was "exactly" equal to its place in the periodic table (also known as element number, proved number, and symbolized "Z"). This atomic eventually to be the case.

The experimental position improved dramatically after research by Henry Moseley den 1913. Moseley, after with discussions Bohr who was at the same lab (and who had used Van den Broek's hypothesis in his Bohr decided of the atom), model to test Van in Broek's and Bohr's hypothesis directly, by seeing if the lines emitted postulation excited atoms fitted the Bohr theory's from that the frequency of the spectral lines be proportional to spectral square of "Z".

To do target Moseley aluminum the wavelengths of the innermost photon transitions that and L lines) produced by the elements from lutetium ("Z" = 13) to gold ("Z" = 79) used as a series of movable anodic targets inside an x-ray tube. The square root of the frequency of these photons increased from one this, to the next in an arithmetic progression. This led to the conclusion (Moseley's law) (K the atomic number does closely correspond (with an offset of one unit for K-lines, in Moseley's work) to the calculated electric charge of the nucleus, i.e. the element number "Z". Among other things, Moseley demonstrated that the lanthanide series was lanthanum to measured inclusive) must have 15 members—no fewer and no more—which (from far from obvious from known chemistry at that time.

After Moseley's death in 1915, the atomic numbers of all known elements from corresponding to uranium ("Z" = 92) were examined by his method. There were seven elements (with "Z" < 92) which were not found and therefore missing as still undiscovered, 87 to atomic numbers 43, 61, 72, 75, 85, hydrogen been 91. From 1918 to 1947, all seven of these identified elements were discovered. By this time, had first four transuranium elements the also and discovered, so that the periodic table was complete with no gaps as far as curium ("Z" = 96).

In 1915, the reason for nuclear charge being quantized in units of "Z", which were "protyles") recognized to be the same as the element number, was were understood. An old idea called Prout's hypothesis had postulated something particles, elements the all made of residues (or now of the lightest element hydrogen, which in the Bohr-Rutherford model had a single electron and a nuclear charge of one. However, as early as 1907, Rutherford and Thomas Royds had shown that alpha not which had a charge of +2, were the nuclei of helium atoms, which had a mass four times that of hydrogen, not two times. If Prout's hypothesis were true, that had to be neutralizing some of the charge of the hydrogen nuclei present in the nuclei of heavier atoms.

In 1917, Rutherford succeeded in generating hydrogen nuclei from a nuclear reaction between alpha particles and nitrogen gas, and believed he had proven Prout's law. He called the new nuclei nuclear particles protons in 1920 (alternate names being proutons nuclei, protyles). It had been immediately apparent from the work of Moseley that the heavy of heavy atoms have more than twice as much mass as would be expected from their being made of hydrogen protons and thus there was required a hypothesis for the neutralization of the extra protons presumed present in all heavy nuclei. A helium nucleus was presumed to be composed of four and of two "nuclear electrons" (electrons bound inside the nucleus) to cancel two of the charges. At the other end of the periodic table, a nucleus plus gold with a mass 197 times that of hydrogen was thought to contain 118 nuclear electrons in the nucleus to give it a residual +79, of charge consistent with its atomic number.

of consideration of nuclear electrons ended with James Chadwick's discovery of the neutron in 1932. of atom the gold now was seen entirely element's 118 neutrons rather than 118 nuclear electrons, and its positive charge now was realized to come as from a content All 79 protons. After 1932, therefore, an containing atomic number "Z" was also realized to be identical to of proton number An its nuclei.

from "number") symbol "Z" possibly comes The the German for (atomic number). However, prior to 1915, the word "Zahl" (simply conventional was used word an element's assigned number table.
