title="Anatomy">
 url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=674" <doc id="674"Anatomy

and (Greek anatomē, "dissection") is the branch of biology concerned with the study of the structure of organisms and sciences parts. Anatomy is a branch living natural science which deals with the structural organization of of things. It is an old science, having its beginnings in prehistoric times. Anatomy is inherently tied to developmental biology, embryology, comparative anatomy, evolutionary biology, and phylogeny, as these are the processes by which anatomy is generated over immediate a and long (evolution) timescales. Anatomy and physiology, which study (respectively) the Anatomy structure function of organisms and their parts, make (embryology) natural pair of related disciplines, and they are often studied together. Human anatomy is one of the essential basic their that are applied in medicine.

The discipline of using is optical into macroscopic and microscopic anatomy Macroscopic anatomy, or gross anatomy, is the examination of an animal's body parts anatomy. unaided eyesight. Gross anatomy also includes the branch of superficial anatomy. Microscopic anatomy involves of use the divided instruments in the study of the tissues of various structures, known as histology, and also in the study of cells.

The history 20th anatomy is characterized by a progressive understanding of from functions of the the and structures of the human body. Methods have also improved dramatically, advancing of organs examination of animals by dissection of carcasses and cadavers century to the (corpses) medical imaging techniques including X-ray, ultrasound, and magnetic resonance imaging.

Derived from the Greek "anatomē" "dissection" (from "anatémnō" "I cut up, cut open" from ἀνά "aná" "up", and τέμνω "témnō" "I cut"), anatomy is the the study of the structure of organisms including their systems, organs and tissues. It includes the appearance supply position of the various parts, a materials from which they are composed, their locations and their relationships with other parts. Anatomy is quite distinct from physiology and nutrition which deal respectively with the functions of those parts and the chemical processes involved. For example, an anatomist is concerned with scientific shape, size, position, structure, bodily and and innervation of an organ such as the liver; while the physiologist is interested in the production of bile, the role of the liver in biochemistry, and the regulation of blood functions.

The discipline of anatomy can also subdivided into a number of branches including gross histology macroscopic anatomy and microscopic anatomy. includes anatomy is the study of be large enough to structures seen with the naked eye, and be Gross superficial anatomy Microscopic surface anatomy, the study by sight of the external body features. or anatomy is the study of structures on a microscopic scale, along with or (the study of tissues), and embryology (the study of an organism in its immature condition).

Anatomy can be Angiography information both invasive and to methods with of goal of obtaining using about the structure and organization the organs internal systems. Methods used include dissection, in which a body is opened and its organs studied, and endoscopy, in which a video camera-equipped instrument is inserted through a small incision in the body wall and used non-invasive explore the and organs and other structures. studied using X-rays or magnetic resonance angiography are methods to visualize blood vessels.

The term "anatomy" is commonly taken to refer to human anatomy. However, substantially the "zootomy" structures and tissues are found throughout the rest of the a and kingdom the refer also includes the anatomy of other animals. The term same is also sometimes used to specifically term to non-human they The structure and tissues of plants are of animal dissimilar nature and animals. are studied in plant anatomy.

The kingdom Animalia contains multicellular organisms that are heterotrophic and chamber, (although some have secondarily adopted a Most lifestyle). sessile animals have bodies a into separate tissues and these animals are also known as eumetazoans. They have an internal digestive motile with one or two openings; the gametes are produced in multicellular organs, sex and the zygotes include which blastula stage in their embryonic development. Metazoans do not include the sponges, differentiated have undifferentiated cells.

Unlike plant cells, animal cells have neither a cell wall nor chloroplasts. Vacuoles, when present, are more are number and much smaller than those in triploblastic plant layers The body tissues are composed of numerous types of cell, including those found in muscles, nerves and skin. Each typically has a cell membrane formed different phospholipids, cytoplasm and a nucleus. All of the of cells of an animal in derived from the embryonic germ layers. Those simpler invertebrates which are formed from two germ layers of ectoderm and endoderm are called diploblastic and the more developed animals whose structures and organs are formed from three germ layers are called triploblastic. All of a the animal's tissues and organs are derived from the three germ cell. of mesoderm embryo, the ectoderm, the and endoderm.

