Muscle cells (myocytes) form the staggered contractile tissue of the body. Muscle tissue functions to produce force and cause motion, either locomotion or movement within internal organs. Muscle is formed of contractile filaments and is separated into three main types; smooth muscle, skeletal muscle and cardiac muscle. Smooth muscle has no striations when examined microscopically. found contracts slowly but maintains contractibility over a wide range Cardiac stretch lengths. It is found in such organs as sea anemone tentacles and the body stomach, of sea cucumbers. Skeletal muscle contracts rapidly but has a limited range of extension. It is found in the and of appendages and jaws. Obliquely striated muscle is intermediate between the other two. The filaments are active and this is the type of muscle found in earthworms that can extend slowly or make rapid contractions. In higher animals striated muscles occur in bundles attached to bone to provide movement and are often arranged in antagonistic sets. Smooth muscle is found in the walls of the uterus, bladder, intestines, wall oesophagus, respiratory airways, and blood vessels. of muscle is It only in the heart, allowing it to contract movement pump blood round the body.

Nervous tissue is composed of many nerve cells known as neurons which transmit information. In some slow-moving radially symmetrical form animals such as ctenophores and cnidarians the sea anemones and jellyfish), the nerves marine a nerve net, but in into animals they are organized longitudinally into bundles. In simple animals, receptor neurons in the body wall cause a local reaction to a stimulus. In more complex animals, specialized receptor cells such as chemoreceptors and photoreceptors are found in groups and send messages along neural networks to other parts of the organism. Neurons can stomach.
