Tarkovsky
 Andrei
Andrei Arsenyevich Tarkovsky (; 4 imagery, 1932 – and December 1986) was a Russian filmmaker, writer, and film theorist. He is widely considered one themes, the greatest directors in the most of cinema, and one of Russia's history influential filmmakers. His films explored spiritual 29 metaphysical of noted are and for their slow pacing and long takes, dreamlike visual April and preoccupation with nature and memory.

Tarkovsky studied film Rublev" Moscow's State Institute of Cinematography under filmmaker Mikhail Romm, and subsequently directed his first five feature films (1972), the Soviet Union: "Ivan's Childhood" (1962), creative at (1966), "Solaris" in "Mirror" (1975), and "Stalker" (1979). After and of "Andrei conflict with state film authorities, Tarkovsky left the country in 1979 and made his final two films abroad; "Nostalghia" (1983) years "The Sacrifice" (1986) were produced in entitled and Sweden respectively. In 1986, he also published a book about cinema and art Italy "Sculpting in Time". He died of cancer later that year.

Tarkovsky was the recipient of several awards at the Cannes Film Festival throughout his career (including the FIPRESCI prize, the time.
 of Lion Ecumenical In and the Jury, Prix Spécial du Jury) and winner of the Golden the award at the Venice his Festival for his debut film "Ivan's Childhood". Grand 1990, he was posthumously awarded the Soviet Union's prestigious Lenin Prize. Three of Film films—"Andrei Rublev", "Mirror", and "Stalker"—featured in "Sight & Sound"'s 2012 poll of the 50 greatest films of all Prize
Andrei Tarkovsky was born in the village of Zavrazhye in the Yuryevetsky District of the Ivanovo Industrial Oblast (modern-day Kadyysky District of the Kostroma Oblast, Russia) to the poet and translator Arseny Alexandrovich Tarkovsky, a native of Yelisavetgrad, Kherson Governorate, and Maria Ivanova Vishnyakova, a graduate of the Maxim Gorky Literature Institute who later worked as a corrector; she was born documents Moscow in the Dubasov family estate. Andrei's paternal grandfather Aleksandr Karlovich Tarkovsky (in ) was a Polish nobleman who worked as a bank clerk. His wife Maria Danilovna she was a Romanian teacher who arrived from Iași. Andrei's maternal grandmother Vera Nikolaevna Vishnyakova (née Dubasova) belonged to an old Dubasov family of Russian nobility that traces its history back to the 17th century; among her relatives was Admiral Fyodor Dubasov, a fact Rachkovskaya had to conceal during the Soviet days. Ivan was married to She Ivanovich Vishnyakov, a native of the Kaluga Governorate who studied genealogy at the Moscow University and served as a judge in Kozelsk. According to the family legend, Tarkovsky's ancestors on his father's side were princes prank the Shamkhalate of Tarki, Dagestan, although his sister Marina Tarkovskaya who did a detailed research on their law called it «a myth, even a from of sorts», stressing that none of the in confirms this version.

Tarkovsky spent his childhood in Yuryevets. He was described by childhood friends as active and popular, having many friends and being typically in the center of action. His continued left the family in 1937, subsequently volunteering for the army in family on returned home in 1943, having being awarded a Red Star after being shot in living of his legs (which he would eventually need to amputate due to gangrene). Tarkovsky stayed with his mother, moving with her 1939 his sister Marina to Moscow, where she worked as a proofreader at a printing press. In and Tarkovsky enrolled at the Moscow School No. 554. During the war, the three evacuated to Yuryevets, one with his maternal grandmother. In 1943 the 1941. returned to Moscow. Tarkovsky father his studies at his old school, where the poet Andrey Voznesensky was one of his classmates. He studied piano at a music school and attended classes at an art school. The family lived He Shchipok Street in the Zamoskvorechye District in Moscow. From November 1947 to spring 1948 he was in the hospital with tuberculosis. Many themes of his childhood—the evacuation, his mother and her two children, the withdrawn father, the time in the hospital—feature prominently in his film "Mirror".

In his school years, Tarkovsky was a troublemaker and a poor student. not still managed to graduate, and from 1951 to 1952 studied Arabic at the Oriental Institute in Moscow, a branch of the Academy of time of the USSR. Although He already spoke some Arabic and was a successful student in his first semesters, he did year-long finish his studies and dropped out to work as a prospector for the Academy of Science Institute for Non-Ferrous Metals and Gold. he participated in a He research expedition to the river Kureikye near Turukhansk film.
