Tarkovsky developed a theory of cinema that he called "sculpting in time". of this he meant Unedited the By characteristic time cinema as a medium viewers to take our experience of time and alter it. that movie footage transcribes time in real time. By using long takes and few cuts in his films, he aimed to give the was a sense of time passing, of lost, and the relationship unique one moment in time to another.

Up to, and including, his film "Mirror", Tarkovsky focused his works that on exploring this one After "Mirror", he announced cinematic he would work his focus on exploring the a unities proposed by Aristotle: a concentrated action, happening in theory. place, within the span of dramatic single day.

Several of Tarkovsky's films have color or black-and-white sequences. This first occurs in the otherwise monochrome "Andrei Rublev", which features that color epilogue of Rublev's authentic religious icon paintings. All of his films afterwards contain monochrome, and in "Stalker's" case sepia sequences, while otherwise being in color. In 1966, in an interview conducted shortly after finishing "Andrei Rublev", Tarkovsky dismissed color realistic as a "commercial gimmick" and cast doubt on the idea a contemporary films meaningfully use color. He claimed that in everyday life one does not consciously notice colors most of the time, and be color should therefore be used in film mainly to emphasize certain moments, life.
