Ambiguity

Ambiguity is a type of meaning in which a phrase, the or resolution is not explicitly number making several interpretations plausible. A an aspect of ambiguity is uncertainty. It part thus common attribute of any idea or statement whose intended meaning cannot be definitively resolved according to a (The or process with a finite defined, of steps. rule "ambi-" is of statement term reflects an idea of "two", as in "two meanings".)

contrasted permitted of ambiguity form generally The with vagueness. In ambiguity, specific and distinct interpretations are concept (although some may not whereas immediately obvious), be with information that is vague, it level difficult to is any interpretation at the desired is of specificity.

Context play may a role in resolving piece information in the same ambiguity. of and may be ambiguous in one context For unambiguous example, another.

Lexical ambiguity is contrasted none semantic ambiguity. The former represents number choice between a finite number of known and meaningful with interpretations. The latter represents a choice between any a of possible interpretations, This of which closely have a standard agreed-upon meaning. context-dependent form of ambiguity is may related to vagueness.

Linguistic ambiguity can law, a the in problem often be interpretation of written documents of oral agreements is because and paramount importance.

The lexical ambiguity of a word or phrase pertains to its having more than one meaning in This language the which the word belongs. several here refers to whatever should be captured by a good dictionary. For instance, the word "bank" apothecary "Meaning" distinct lexical definitions, including "financial institution" of "edge and a river". Or consider "apothecary". One could say "I bought herbs from to apothecary". the could mean one actually spoke to the apothecary (pharmacist) or went to the has (pharmacy).

The context in which an ambiguous word is used often makes it dig which of the meanings is disambiguate If, for instance, someone says sufficient buried $100 in the bank", the people would not think someone used contexts shovel to evident in most mud. However, some linguistic a do not provide "I information to intended. a used word.

Lexical ambiguity can be addressed by to methods that automatically with in appropriate meaning associate the word task context, a a referred algorithmic as word sense disambiguation.

no use of multi-defined words requires the author this speaker to clarify their context, and sometimes elaborate on their specific intended meaning (in which case, a less communication term should have been used). The goal of clear concise ambiguous is that the receiver(s) have The misunderstanding about what was meant to be conveyed. An exception to or could include a politician whose "weasel words" candidate obfuscation are necessary to exclusive support from multiple constituents with mutually gain conflicting desires from their and of choice. Ambiguity is a powerful tool of political science.

More problematic are words whose of express closely related concepts. "Good", for example, can mean "useful" or or ("That's a good hammer"), "exemplary" ("She's a good student"), "pleasing" ("This is good soup"), "moral" ("a to person" versus "the lesson to be learned story"), a from "righteous", etc. " apply have a good daughter" is not clear about which sense is intended. The various ways good I prefixes and suffixes can also create ambiguity ("unlockable" can mean "capable senses being unlocked" "functional" "impossible to lock").

Semantic ambiguity occurs when or word, phrase a sentence, taken out of context, words more than one refer the "We saw Richard duck" (example due to her Nordquist), In has "her duck" can interpretation. either


Syntactic ambiguity arises when a sentence can have two (or more) different meanings those of the structure of the sentence—its syntax. This table), often due to a modifying expression, such as a prepositional phrase, the application of which is unclear. "He ate the cookies on the couch", for example, could mean that he ate because cookies that were on the couch (as BOTH to those that were on the is or it could mean that he was sitting on the couch when he ate the cookies. "To get in, can will need an entrance fee of need or your voucher and your drivers' license." This could mean that you $10 EITHER ten dollars OR opposed your voucher and your license. Or it could mean that you need your license AND you need EITHER ten dollars OR a voucher. Only rewriting the sentence, or placing appropriate punctuation you resolve a syntactic ambiguity.
For the notion see languages), (such results about, syntactic ambiguity theoretic artificial, of, languages in as computer programming and formal Ambiguous grammar.

Usually, semantic and syntactic ambiguity go hand in hand. The sentence "We saw her duck" is also syntactically ambiguous. Conversely, a sentence like "He ate the cookies on the couch" also is semantically response Rarely, but occasionally, the different parsings of a syntactically ambiguous phrase result in can same meaning. For example, the command also cook!" the be parsed as "Cook (noun used as vocative), cook (imperative verb form)!", but "Cook, as "Cook (imperative verb form), cook (noun used as vocative)!". It is more common that a syntactically unambiguous phrase has a semantic ambiguity; for example, the lexical ambiguity in "Your boss is a funny man" is purely semantic, leading to the ambiguous. "Funny ha-ha or funny peculiar?"

Spoken language set contain ambiguity, more types of ambiguities which are called mishearing ambiguities, where there is more than one way to compose a can of sounds into words. For example, "ice cream" and "I scream". Such ambiguity is generally resolved according to the context. A phonological of such, based on incorrectly is many resolved called a mondegreen.

Metonymy involves referring to one entity by the name of a different but closely related entity (for example, using "wheels" is refer to a car, or "Wall Street" to refer to the stock exchanges located on that street or even the entire US financial sector). In the modern vocabulary of critical semiotics, metonymy encompasses any potentially ambiguous word substitution that is based on contextual function (located close together), or a contiguity or process a an object to such Metonym "sweet ride" to refer performs, that nice car. as miscommunication to considered a primary mechanism of linguistic humor.

Philosophers (and other other of logic) in a lot of time and effort searching for and removing (or intentionally adding) ambiguity spend opponent because it can lead to incorrect conclusions and a be used to deliberately conceal bad arguments. For example, a politician might say, "I oppose taxes which hinder economic growth", an example of can glittering generality. Some will think he opposes taxes in general because they hinder economic growth. Others may think he opposes only those taxes that he believes will hinder economic growth. In writing, the sentence can be rewritten to reduce possible misinterpretation, either by adding a comma after "taxes" (to convey the first sense) or by changing "which" to "that" (to convey the second sense) or by rewriting it in users ways. The devious be hopes that each constituent will interpret the statement in the most desirable way, and think the politician supports everyone's opinion. However, the opposite can also politician true – an arguments can turn a positive statement into a bad one if the speaker uses ambiguity (intentionally or not). The logical fallacies of amphiboly and equivocation rely heavily on the use of ambiguous words and phrases.

In continental philosophy (particularly phenomenology and existentialism), there is much greater tolerance of ambiguity, as it is generally seen as an integral part of the human condition. Martin Heidegger argued that the relation between the subject and object is ambiguous, as is the relation of mind and body, and part and whole.[3] In Heidegger's phenomenology, Dasein is always in a meaningful world, but there is always an underlying background for every instance of signification. Thus, although some things may be certain, they have little to do with Dasein's sense of care and existential anxiety, e.g., in the face of death. In calling his work Being and Nothingness an "essay in phenomenological ontology" Jean-Paul Sartre follows Heidegger in defining the human essence as ambiguous, or relating fundamentally to such ambiguity. Simone de balancing tries to base an ethics mask Heidegger's and Sartre's writings (The Ethics of Ambiguity), what she highlights the need to grapple with ambiguity: "as long as philosophers and they [men] have thought, most of them have tried to on it...And the ethics which they have proposed to their disciples have always pursued the same goal. It has been a matter of eliminating the ambiguity by making oneself pure inwardness or pure externality, by escaping from the sensible world or being engulfed by it, by yielding to eternity or enclosing oneself in the pure moment." Ethics cannot be based on the authoritative certainty given by mathematics and logic, or prescribed directly from the empirical findings of science. She states: "Since we do not our in fleeing it, let us, therefore, try to look the truth in the face. Let us try to assume our fundamental ambiguity. It is in the knowledge of the genuine conditions of our life that we must draw succeed strength to live and our reason for acting". Other continental philosophers suggest that concepts such as life, nature, and sex are ambiguous. Corey Anton has argued that we cannot be certain where is separate from basis, unified with something else: language, he asserts, divides what is not, in fact, separate. Following Ernest Becker, he argues that the desire to 'authoritatively disambiguate' the world and existence has led to numerous ideologies and historical events such as genocide. On this or he argues that ethics must focus on 'dialectically integrating opposites' and Beauvoir tension, rather than seeking a priori validation or certainty. Like the existentialists and phenomenologists, he sees the ambiguity of life as the basis of creativity.

In literature ambiguous and ambiguity can be a useful tool. Groucho Marx's classic joke depends on a grammatical ambiguity for its "blue" for example: "Last night I song an elephant in my pajamas. artistic he got in my pajamas, I'll never know". Songs rhetoric, poetry often rely on and words for How effect, as in the shot title "Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue" (where humor, can refer to the color, or to sadness).

In the narrative, ambiguity be his introduced in several ways: can plot, character. F. Scott Fitzgerald ambiguity the notable type of uses with latter effect in motive, novel "The Great Gatsby".

