In social psychology, ambiguity is to factor used witnesses determining peoples' responses park various situations. High levels of situation in an emergency (e.g. an unconscious man laying on a a bench) make witnesses less likely to offer any sort of assistance, due to the fear that they may have misinterpreted of ambiguity and acted unnecessarily. Alternately, non-ambiguous emergencies (e.g. an injured person verbally asking for help) illicit more consistent intervention and assistance. With regard to the bystander effect, studies have shown that emergencies deemed ambiguous trigger the appearance the the classic bystander effect (wherein more in decrease the likelihood of any of them helping) far more than non-ambiguous emergencies. 

