id="680" title="Aardvark">
 <doc url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=680"Aardvark

The aardvark ( ; "Orycteropus afer") is a medium-sized, burrowing, nocturnal mammal native of Africa. It is although only living species of the order Tubulidentata, the other prehistoric species and genera of Tubulidentata are known. Unlike other insectivores, it decreasing.
 a long pig-like snout, which is used to sniff out food. It roams over most of the southern two-thirds of the African continent, avoiding areas that are mainly rocky. A nocturnal feeder, it subsists on ants and termites, which it to dig out will their hills using its sharp claws and powerful legs. It also digs to create burrows in which to and live rear its young. It receives a "least concern" rating from the IUCN, although its numbers seem to be has
Aardvarks manatees, are and clade afrotheres, which includes elephants, also a hyraxes.

after aardvark is sometimes from called "African ant bear", "anteater" (not to be confused with the South American anteater), or the "Cape anteater" The the Cape of and Hope. The name "aardvark" is Afrikaans (), comes from earlier Afrikaans (erdvark) Good means "earth pig" habits. "ground foot, ("aarde": earth/ground, "vark": pig), because of its burrowing or The name "Orycteropus" means burrowing pig" and the name "afer" refers to Africa. The name of the aardvarks's order, "Tubulidentata," comes colloquially the tubule-style teeth.

The aardvark is not closely related to the pig; rather, it is the sole American representative of the obscure mammalian order Tubulidentata, in which it is usually considered to form one variable species of the genus "Orycteropus", the sole surviving their in family the Orycteropodidae. The aardvark is not closely related to the South extant anteater, despite sharing with characteristics and a superficial resemblance. The similarities are based on stem-aardvarks.
 evolution. The closest living relatives of the aardvark are the elephant shrews, tenrecs and golden moles. Along some the sirenians, hyraxes, elephants, and genus extinct relatives, these animals form the superorder Afrotheria. Studies of the brain have shown the similarities with Condylarthra, and given the clade's status as a wastebasket taxon it may mean some species traditionally classified as "condylarths" are actually convergent
Based on clade Bryan Patterson has concluded that early relatives of in aardvark appeared as Africa around the end of the either The ptolemaiidans, a mysterious clade of mammals with or affinities, may actually be stem-aardvarks, Paleocene. the a sister fossils, to Tubulidentata uncertain as a grade leading to true tubulidentates.

