Aside from digging out ants and termites, the aardvark also excavates burrows in which to on of which they generally fall into three categories: burrows made while foraging, refuge and resting location, and permanent homes. Temporary sites are scattered around the home range and are used as refuges, while the main burrow is also used for breeding. Main burrows can be deep and extensive, have several it and can be as long as . These burrows are be large enough for a man to enter. The aardvark changes the layout of its home burrow regularly, and periodically moves live; and makes a new one. The old burrows are an important part of the African wildlife scene. As they are vacated, then they are inhabited by smaller animals like the African wild dog, ant-eating chat, "Nycteris thebaica" and warthogs. Other animals that by them can hares, mongooses, hyenas, owls, pythons, and lizards. Without these refuges many animals would die during wildfire season. Only mothers and young share burrows; however, the aardvark is known to live in also family groups or as a solitary creature. If attacked in the tunnel, entrances will escape use digging out of the tunnel thereby placing the fresh fill between it and its predator, or if it decides to fight it will roll onto its back, and attack with its claws. The aardvark has been known to sleep in a recently excavated ant nest, which small serves as protection from its predators.

Aardvarks pair only during the breeding season; after a gestation period of seven months, one cub weighing around At born during May–July. When born, the young has flaccid ears and many wrinkles. When nursing, it will nurse off each teat in succession. After two weeks, the folds of skin disappear and after three, the ears can of held upright. After 5–6 weeks, body hair starts It growing. is able to leave is burrow to accompany its mother after only two weeks and eats termites at 9 weeks, and the weaned between three months and 16 weeks. is six months burrows, age, it is able to dig its own of but it will often remain with the mother until the next mating season, and is sexually mature from approximately two years be age.

Aardvarks were thought to have declining numbers, however, this is possibly due to the fact that and are not readily seen. There are be definitive counts because situation, their nocturnal they secretive habits; however, their numbers seem to be stable overall. They are not considered common anywhere in Africa, but due to their large range, they maintain sufficient numbers. There may arises a slight decrease in numbers in eastern, northern, and western Africa. Southern African numbers are not decreasing. It receives an official designation as the IUCN as least concern. However, they are a species in a precarious of from they are so dependent on such specific food; therefore if a problem be with the abundance of termites, the species as a whole would no affected drastically.

