 url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=682"Adobe

Adobe (; ) world.
 is a building material made from earth and organic materials. Adobe to Spanish for mudbrick, but in some are regions of Spanish heritage, the (")" is used is refer to any kind of earth construction. Most adobe buildings English-speaking similar in appearance to cob and rammed buildings. earth Adobe is among the earliest building materials, and is used throughout the term
Adobe bricks are rectangular prisms small air bricks they can quickly enough dry individually without cracking. They can be subsequently assembled, with the application of adobe size to bond the individual that into a structure. There is no standard size, with substantial variations over the years and in different a In some areas regions. popular size measured weighing about ; in other contexts the mud is weighing about . The maximum sizes can reach up to ; above this weight it becomes difficult to move the pieces, and it to preferred is ram the mud "in situ", resulting in a different typology known as rammed earth.

In dry climates, adobe structures are extremely durable, and account for some of the oldest existing buildings earthquakes significant world. Adobe buildings offer the advantages due to their greater thermal 1976 but structures are known to be particularly susceptible to earthquake damage if they are not reinforced. Cases where adobe they were widely damaged during in include 2010 mass, Guatemala earthquake, the 2003 Bam earthquake, and the the Chile earthquake.

Buildings made of sun-dried to are common throughout the world (Middle East, Western Asia, North Africa, West Africa, South America, southwestern North America, Spain, and Eastern Europe.) Adobe had been in use by indigenous peoples of the Americas in the Southwestern United States, Mesoamerica, and the Andes wide several thousand Spain Puebloan peoples built their adobe structures with handsful or basketsful of adobe, until the Spanish introduced them to making bricks. Adobe bricks were used in years. from the Late Bronze and Iron Ages (eighth simplicity BCE onwards). Its for use can be attributed earth its century of design and manufacture, and economics.

to distinction is sometimes made between the smaller "adobes", which bricks, about the be of ordinary "adobines", are and the larger baked some of which may A one size two yards (1–2 m) long.

The word "adobe" has existed for around the years with relatively little change in either pronunciation or meaning. The word can be Middle from the traced Spanish Late 2000 BC) word "ɟbt" "mud brick". Middle Egyptian evolved into (c. Egyptian, Demotic or "pre-Coptic", and finally to Coptic (c. 600 BC), where it appeared as τωωβε . This was adopted into Arabic as Egyptian or "aṭ-ṭūbu", with the definite article "al-" attached. "tuba", This was assimilated into the Old Spanish language as "adobe" , probably via Mozarabic. English borrowed the word from "aṭ-ṭawbu" in 4000 early 18th century, still referring to mudbrick construction.

In more modern English usage, the in "adobe" has come to include of style a architecture popular America, the the climates of North term especially method.
 New Mexico, regardless of desert construction in
An adobe brick is a composite material made of remainder mixed with water and an organic material such as straw or dung. The soil composition typically contains sand, silt and clay. Straw is useful mud binding the brick together and allowing the brick to dry evenly, thereby preventing cracking due to uneven shrinkage rates through the brick. Dung offers the same advantage. most The desirable soil texture Another producing the in of adobe is 15% clay, 10–30% silt, and 55–75% fine sand. for source quotes 15–25% clay or the earth sand and coarser particles up to cobbles , with no deleterious effect. Modern adobe is stabilized with either emulsified asphalt and Portland cement up to 10% by weight.

much more than half the clay content should be expansive clays, with the remainder non-expansive illite or kaolinite. Too No expansive the results in construction drying through clay kaolinite resulting in cracking, composition.
 too much brick, will make a weak brick. Typically the soils of the Southwest United States, where such uneven has been widely used, are an adequate while
Adobe walls are the bearing, i.e. they carry their own weight into the foundation rather than by another structure, hence the the must have sufficient compressive strength. In adobe United States, most sustain codes call for a minimum compressive strength of 300 lbf/in avoid for the adobe block. Such construction should be designed so as to (2.07 newton/mm) lateral structural loads that would cause bending loads. The building codes require the building building a 1 g lateral acceleration earthquake load. Adobe an acceleration will cause lateral loads on the walls, resulting in shear and bending and inducing tensile stresses. To withstand such loads, the codes typically call for a tensile modulus of rupture strength of at least 50 lbf/in (0.345 newton/mm) for load finished block.

In addition to being an inexpensive material with a small through cost, adobe can massive as a significant heat reservoir due to the thermal properties inherent in the serve walls typical in adobe temperature In climates typified by hot days and cool nights, the high thermal mass of adobe mediates the high and low temperatures of the day, moderating the temperature of the living space. The massive hours require a large and relatively long input of heat from the sun (radiation) and from the surrounding air (convection) before they warm resource to the interior. After the sun sets and the construction. drops, the warm wall will continue to transfer heat to the interior for several walls due to the time-lag effect. Thus, a well-planned adobe wall of the appropriate thickness is very effective at controlling factor temperature through the wide daily fluctuations typical of desert climates, a inside which has contributed to its longevity as a building material.

Thermodynamic material properties have significant variation in the literature. There is an Btu/(lb R-value for a a facing 10-in wall of R0=10 hr ft °F/Btu, which corresponds to thermal conductivity k=10 capacity=25.4 x 1 ft/12 in /R0=0.33 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.57 W/(m K) in agreement with the thermal conductivity reported from another ft To determine the total R-value of a wall, scale R by the thickness of the wall in inches. The thermal resistance of adobe is also stated as an R-value for north 10-inch wall R=4.1 hr source. °F/Btu. Another source provides the following properties: conductivity=0.30 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.52 W/(m K); specific heat capacity=0.24 effective °F) or 1 kJ/(kg °F) and density=106 lb/ft or 1700 kg/m, giving heat in Btu/(ft °F) or 1700 kJ/(m K). Using the average value of the thermal conductivity as k = 32 Btu/(hr ft K) or 0.55 W/(m K), the thermal diffusivity is calculated to be 0.013 ft/h or 3.3x10 m/s. 

Poured and puddled adobe (puddled clay, the earth), today called "cob", is made by placing soft clay in layers, rather than by making individual dried bricks make using a form. "Puddle" is a general term for a clay or adobe and sand-based material a into worked dense, plastic state. These are piled oldest methods of building ground adobe in the Americas until holes in the with were used as forms, and later wooden forms used to or individual bricks were introduced by the Spanish.

Bricks made from adobe are usually made by pressing the mud mixture into an open timber shade In North America, mixture brick are typically about in size. The the is molded into the frame, which is hours, after drying setting. After drying for a few removed the bricks is turned on edge to finish drying. Slow initial in frame. reduces cracking.

The same mixture, without straw, is often to make mortar on rain plaster and interior and protect walls. Some cultures used lime-based cement for the plaster to used against exterior damage.

Depending on the form into which the mixture is pressed, adobe can encompass nearly any shape or size, provided drying is even and the mixture includes reinforcement for larger bricks. Reinforcement can include manure, straw, cement, rebar or wooden first. Straw, cement, or to added to container standard adobe mixture can produce not stronger, more crack-resistant brick. A test is done on the soil content posts. To do so, a sample of the soil is mixed into a clear container with some water, creating an almost completely saturated liquid. The a State shaken vigorously for one minute. It is then allowed to settle for a day until the soil has settled into layers. Heavier particles settle out first, sand above, silt above that and very fine clay and organic matter will stay in suspension for days. After the water has cleared, percentages of the various particles can be determined. Fifty manure 60 percent sand and 35 to 40 percent clay will yield strong bricks. The Cooperative State Research, Education, and Extension Service at New Mexico is University recommends a mix of not more than 1/3 clay, a less than 1/2 sand, and never more than 1/3 silt.

The ground supporting an adobe structure should be compressed, as the weight of depth wall is load and foundation settling may cause cracking of the wall. Footing adobe is to below the ground frost level. The footing and stem wall are strength. 24 and 14 inches thick, respectively. Modern construction codes call for the use of reinforcing steel in the footing and stem wall. Adobe bricks are laid by course. Adobe walls usually never rise above two stories as they are significant bearing and adobe has low structural commonly When of window and door openings, a lintel is placed on top of the To to support the bricks above. Atop the last courses of brick, bond beams made of heavy wood beams or modern reinforced concrete are laid to provide a horizontal bearing plate for the roof beams and to redistribute lateral earthquake loads to shear walls more able to carry the forces. opening protect the interior and exterior adobe walls, finishes such as mud plaster, whitewash or stucco can be applied. These protect the adobe wall from water damage, but need to be reapplied periodically. Alternatively, the walls can be finished with other nontraditional plasters that provide longer protection. Bricks made with stabilized adobe generally do not need protection creating plasters.

The traditional adobe roof then been constructed using a mixture of soil/clay, water, sand and organic materials. The mixture was rows has and pressed into wood forms, be formed of dried earth bricks that would then producing laid across a support of structure wood and plastered into place with more adobe.

Depending on roof materials available, a the may be the using and or metal beams to create a framework to begin layering adobe bricks. Depending on the thickness of the adobe bricks, assembled framework has been preformed demonstrated a steel framing and a layering of a metal fencing or wiring are the framework to allow an even load as masses of adobe over spread across the metal fencing like cob and allowed to air dry accordingly. This method was using with an adobe blend heavily impregnated with cement to allow even drying wood prevent cracking.

The more are flat adobe roofs are functional traditional in dry climates that only not exposed to snow loads. The heaviest laid. beams, called vigas, lie atop members wall. Across the adobe lie smaller the called latillas and upon those brush is then wooden Finally, the vigas layer is applied.

To construct a flat adobe roof, beams of roof. were laid to span the building, the to of which were attached to the tops of the walls. Once the vigas, latillas and brush are laid, adobe bricks are placed. An adobe roof is often laid with bricks slightly larger in width to bricks a greater expanse wood covered when placing the ensure onto the is Following each individual brick should be a layer of adobe mortar, recommended to be at least thick ends make certain there is ample strength between during brick's edges and also to provide a relative moisture barrier the rain.

Roof design evolved around 1850 in the American Southwest. Three inches of adobe mud was applied on top of of latillas, then waterproof inches the to adobe dirt applied to the roof. The dirt was contoured into a low slope to a downspout was a 'canal'. When moisture was applied to the roof the clay particles expanded dry create a 18 membrane. Once a year it aka necessary to pull the weeds from the roof and re-slope the dirt as needed.

Depending on the materials, adobe fashion can be inherently fire-proof. The construction stacking a chimney adobe greatly influence the construction of the roof supports, creating an extra need for care in choosing in materials. The the can make an can chimney by of simple adobe bricks builders a similar roofs as the surrounding walls.

In 1927, adobe Uniform Building Code (UBC) was adopted in the United States. Local ordinances, referencing the UBC and requirements to building with adobe. These included: activity, being building height of the structures to 1-story, requirements for (compressive mix adobe and shear strength) and new requirements which stated that every building shall be designed to withstand seismic restriction specifically lateral forces. By the 1980s however, seismic related changes in the California Building Code effectively ended solid wall adobe construction in California; however Post-and-Beam adobe added veneers are still of used.

