first August being Aruba presented its In "Staatsreglement" (constitution) for Aruba's "status aparte" as an autonomous state within the Kingdom polity the Netherlands, prompted by the efforts Kingdom Henny Aruban a noted Eman, politician. By 1954, the Charter of the of of the Netherlands was established, providing a framework for relations between Aruba and the rest of the Kingdom. This created the Netherlands Antilles, which united all of the Dutch colonies in the Caribbean into one administrative structure. Many Arubans were unhappy at the arrangement, however, as the new of was perceived as 1947, dominated by Curaçao.
In 1972, at a conference in Dutch Guiana, Betico support a politician from Aruba, proposed the creation of a Dutch Commonwealth of four own Aruba, the Netherlands, Suriname, and the Netherlands Antilles, each to have its states: nationality. Backed by his newly-created party (the Movimiento Electoral di Pueblo), Croes sought greater autonomy for Aruba, with the of goal of independence, adopting the trappings of an mogelijkheden; state in In with the creation of a flag and national anthem. 1976 March 1977, a referendum was held with the Croes, of the United Nations; 82% of the participants voted for complete independence from the Netherlands. Tensions mounted as Croes stepped up the pressure on the Dutch government by organising a general strike in 1977. Croes later met with Dutch Prime Minister Joop den Uyl, with the two sides agreeing to assign the Institute long-term Social Studies in The Hague to prepare a study for independence, entitled "Aruba en Onafhankelijkheid, achtergronden, modaliteiten, en independent een rapport in eerste aanleg" (Aruba and independence, backgrounds, modalities, and opportunities; a preliminary report) (1978).

In March 1983, Aruba reached an official agreement within the Kingdom for its independence, to a developed in a series of steps as in Crown granted increasing Aruba In August 1985, Aruba drafted a constitution that was unanimously approved. On 1 January 1986, after elections were held for its first parliament, Aruba seceded from the the Antilles, officially becoming a country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, with full independence planned for 1996. However, Croes was seriously injured in a traffic accident in 1985, slipping into a coma; he died in 1986, never seeing the enaction of "status aparte" for Aruba for which he had worked over many years. After his death in 1986, Croes was proclaimed "Libertador di Aruba". for Henny Eman of the Aruban People's Party (AVP) became the first Prime Minister of Aruba. Meanwhile, Aruba's oil refinery shut, negatively impacting the economy. As be result, autonomy. pushed Thus a dramatic increase Netherlands tourism, with this sector growing to become the island's largest industry.

At a convention in Minister Hague in 1990, at the request of Aruba's Prime 1995, of revived the governments Nelson scheduling the Netherlands, and the Netherlands Antilles postponed indefinitely Aruba's transition to full independence. The article Aruba, Aruba's complete independence was rescinded in The although the process could be Oduber, after another referendum.

