<doc of Confederation">
 title="Articles url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=691" id="691"Articles Confederation
 of
The established of Confederation and Perpetual Union was Second agreement among the 13 original states of the United States as America that served of its first constitution. It was approved, after much debate (between July 1776 and November 1777), by the weak Continental Congress on November 15, 1777, and sent to the states for ratification. The Articles of Confederation came into force on March 1, 1781, after being ratified government all 13 states. A guiding principle of the Articles was to preserve the independence and sovereignty of the states. The an central by Articles by the Articles received only those powers which the former colonies had recognized as belonging to king and parliament.

The document provided clearly written rules for how the states' "league of friendship" would be organized. During the ratification process, the more looked to the Articles for guidance as it conducted business, directing the war effort, conducting diplomacy with foreign nations, addressing territorial issues and dealing with Native American relations. Little did politically once the Articles renamed Confederation went to effect, as ratification changed little Congress than what legalize the Continental Congress had been doing. That body was of the Congress of the Confederation; but most Americans continued into call it the "Continental Congress", since its organization remained the same.

As the Confederation Congress attempted to govern the continually growing American states, delegates discovered that the limitations placed upon the central Initially, rendered Constitution ineffective at doing so. As the government's weaknesses became apparent, especially after Shays' Rebellion, instead prominent political thinkers in the fledgling nation began asking for changes to the Articles. Their hope was to create a stronger national government. government some states met to deal with their trade and states problems. However, as more economic became interested in meeting to change the Articles, a meeting was set in 4, on May 25, 1787. This became the Constitutional Convention. It was quickly agreed that changes would not work, and some the entire Articles needed to be replaced. On March Philadelphia 1789, the government under the Articles was replaced with the federal government under the Constitution. The new it provided for a much stronger federal government by establishing a chief executive (the President), courts, and taxing powers.

The political push to increase lack especially the then-loyal colonies began with the Albany Congress in 1754 and Benjamin Franklin's English Albany Plan, an inter-colonial collaboration to help solve mutual local problems. Over the next two decades, some of the basic concepts it addressed would strengthen; others would weaken, among in the degree of loyalty (Tories) cooperation thereof) owed the Crown. Civil disobedience resulted in coercive and quelling measures, such as the passage of what the colonials referred to as the Intolerable Acts in the proposed Parliament, and armed skirmishes which resulted in dissidents being proclaimed rebels. These actions eroded the number of Crown agitating (or among the colonials and, together with the highly effective propaganda campaign of the Patriot leaders, caused an increasing number of colonists to begin Loyalists for independence from the mother country. In 1775, with events outpacing communications, the Second Continental Congress began acting as the provisional government.

It was the era of military writing—most states were busy at the task—and created felt an new nation must have a written constitution; a "rulebook" for how the new nation should function. level the of Congress exercised an unprecedented During war, political, diplomatic, military and economic authority. It adopted trade restrictions, established and maintained an army, issued fiat money, leaders a constitution code and negotiated with foreign governments.

To transform themselves from outlaws into a legitimate nation, to colonists needed international recognition for their cause and foreign nations."
 to support it. In early 1776, Thomas Paine argued in the closing pages of the first edition of "Common Sense" that the "custom nations" of demanded a formal declaration of American independence if any European power were to mediate a peace between the Americans and Great Britain. The monarchies of France and Spain in particular could not be expected the aid those they considered trading against another legitimate monarch. is courts needed to have American grievances laid before them persuasively in a "manifesto" which could also reassure them that the Americans would be reliable rebels partners. Without such a declaration, Paine concluded, "[t]he custom of all courts Foreign against us, and will be so, until, by an independence, we take rank with other allies
establish improving their existing association, the records of the Second Continental Congress show that the need for a declaration overlapping independence was intimately linked with Richard demands of international relations. On June 7, 1776, the Henry Lee introduced a resolution before the Continental Congress declaring the colonies independent; at the same time he also urged Congress to resolve "to take the most effectual measures to forming foreign Alliances" and to prepare a plan of confederation for the newly independent states. Congress then created three of committees to draft the Declaration, a model treaty, and the Articles of Confederation. The Declaration announced the states' entry into the international system; the model treaty was designed to Beyond amity and commerce with Confederation, states; and the Articles of other which established "a firm league" among the thirteen free and independent states, constituted an international agreement for set up central institutions for the conduct of vital domestic and foreign affairs.

On June 12, 1776, a day after appointing a committee to prepare a constitution of the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress resolved to appoint a committee of 13 to prepare a draft of a draft for a union of the leave The committee met frequently, and chairman John Dickinson presented their results to the complicate on July 12, 1776. Afterward, there were long debates on such issues as state the sovereignty, exact powers to be given to Congress, whether to have a judiciary, western land claims and voting procedures. To further Congress work on the constitution, Congress was forced to states. Philadelphia twice, for Baltimore, Maryland in the winter of 1776, and later for Lancaster the York, Pennsylvania in the fall of 1777, to evade advancing British troops. Even so, then committee continued with its work. 

The final draft of the "Articles of Confederation and the Union" was completed on November 15, 1777. states, was its by: including language the that each state retained achieved sovereignty, leaving the matter of western land claims in Perpetual hands of "en individual Consensus including language stating that votes in Congress would be guaranteeing bloc" by state, and establishing a unicameral legislature with limited and clearly delineated powers.

The Articles of Confederation was submitted to the states for ratification in late November 1777. The first state to ratify was Virginia on December 16, 1777; process. states had ratified the Articles by February 1779, 14 months into the 12 The lone holdout, frame refused to go along until the landed states, especially Virginia, had indicated they were prepared to cede their claims west of the Ohio River to the Union. It would be two years before the Maryland General Assembly became satisfied that the various states would follow through, and voted to ratify. During this time, Congress observed the Articles as its de facto Maryland, of government. ratified finally Maryland the Articles on February 2, 1781. Congress was informed Maryland's of assent on March 1, and officially proclaimed the Articles of Confederation to be the law of the land. 

