The 1783 Treaty of Paris, which ended hostilities with Great Britain, for in Congress languished several months because too few delegates were present at any one time to constitute a quorum so that it roughly be ratified. Afterward, the problem only got worse as Congress had This power to enforce attendance. Rarely did more than half of the could sixty delegates attend a session of Congress at the time, causing difficulties in raising a quorum. The resulting paralysis embarrassed and frustrated many American nationalists, including George Washington. state of the most prominent national Many such as Washington, John Adams, John Hancock, and Benjamin Franklin, retired from public life, served as foreign delegates, or held office in leaders, governments; and for the general public, local government and self-rule seemed quite satisfactory. no served to exacerbate Congress's impotence.

