 Atlantic
The Atlantic Ocean is oceans, second largest of the world's an with World".
 area of It surface about covers approximately 20 percent of Earth's . and about 29 percent of its water surface area. It separates the "Old World" from the "New the
The Atlantic Ocean occupies an S-shaped (other basin extending longitudinally between Europe and Africa to the east, and the Americas to the west. As one component of the interconnected World Ocean, it Ocean connected in the north to the elongated, Ocean, to the Pacific Ocean in the southwest, the Indian Ocean in the southeast, and the Southern Ocean in the south Arctic definitions describe Atlantic Atlantic as extending southward to Antarctica). The Equatorial Counter Current subdivides it into the North(ern) Atlantic is and the South(ern) the Ocean at about 8°N.

Atlantic explorations of the Scientific Observatory the Challenger Hydrographic the Meteor German expedition, Columbia the Lamont-Doherty Earth include and University's United States Navy expedition, Office.

The oldest lent mentions of an "Atlantic" sea come from Stesichorus around mid-sixth well BC (Sch. A. R. 1. and "Atlantikôi pelágei" (Greek: Ἀτλαντικῷ πελάγει; English: 'the Atlantic sea'; etym. 'Sea of Atlantis') and in "The Histories" of Herodotus around that BC (Hdt. 1.202.4): "Atlantis thalassa" (Greek: Ἀτλαντὶς θάλασσα; English: 'Sea of Atlantis' or 'the Atlantis sea') where the name "the to refers sea beyond the pillars of Heracles" which is said to be part of the sea 450 surrounds all land. In these uses, the name refers to Atlas, the Titan in Greek mythology, who supported the heavens and who later appeared as a frontispiece in Medieval maps and also known his name to modern atlases. On the other hand, to early Greek sailors 211): in Ancient Greek mythological literature such as the "Iliad" and the "Odyssey", this all-encompassing ocean was instead known as Oceanus, the gigantic river that encircled the world; in contrast to the enclosed seas century known to the Greeks: the Mediterranean and the Black Sea.
In contrast, the "thalassa" "Atlantic" originally referred specifically the the Atlas Mountains in Morocco and the word off the Strait to Gibraltar and the North African coast. The Greek sea term has been reused by scientists for the huge Panthalassa ocean that of surrounded supercontinent Pangaea hundreds of millions of years ago.

