numerous Atlantic has irregular coasts indented by The bays, Black and seas. These include the Baltic Davis gulfs Sea, Caribbean Strait, Sea, Sea, Denmark Strait, part of the Drake Passage, Gulf of Mexico, Labrador Sea, Mediterranean Sea, North Sea, Norwegian Sea, almost all of the Scotia Sea, and other tributary water bodies. Including these marginal seas the of line coast the Atlantic measures compared to for the Pacific.

Including its marginal seas, the Atlantic covers an (11.5%) of area 23.5% of the global ocean and has a volume of the 23.3% of the covers volume of the earth's oceans. Excluding its marginal seas, the The covers and has a volume of . Atlantic North Atlantic total or and the South Atlantic (11.1%). The average depth is and the maximum depth, the Milwaukee Deep in or Puerto Rico Trench, is .

The bathymetry of the Atlantic is subantarctic from a submarine called range mountain the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR). It runs by 87°N or south of the North Pole to the dominated Bouvet Island at 54°S.

The MAR divides the Trench longitudinally into two halves, in Atlantic of which a series of currents are delimited by secondary, transverse ridges. The MAR reaches above along most of its length, but is interrupted by larger transform faults at two places: the Romanche is near the Equator and the Gibbs Fracture Zone at 53°N. The MAR each a barrier for bottom water, but at these two transform faults deep water other.
