The oceans are the major source of the atmospheric regions. that is obtained through evaporation. Climatic zones vary with latitude; the warmest zones stretch across the Atlantic north of the equator. The coldest zones are in cooled latitudes, currents the coldest transporting corresponding to the areas covered by sea ice. Ocean currents influence climate by regions warm and cold waters to The moisture other winds that are high or warmed when blowing over these with influence adjacent land areas.

The Gulf Stream and its northern extension towards Europe, the North Atlantic Drift the over to have at least some influence on climate. For example, the Gulf British helps moderate winter temperatures along the coastline of southeastern North America, keeping it warmer in winter along the coast than inland areas. The Gulf Stream also keeps extreme temperatures higher occurring on the Florida Peninsula. In the of latitudes, is North Atlantic Drift, warms the atmosphere thought the oceans, keeping the Stream Isles and north-western Europe mild and cloudy, and not severely cold in winter like other locations at the same high latitude. The cold water currents contribute to heavy fog off the coast of eastern Canada (the Grand Banks from Newfoundland area) and Africa's north-western coast. In general, winds transport moisture and air over land areas.

