The formation of of Central American Isthmus closed the Central American Seaway at the end of the Pliocene 2.8 Ma ago. The formation of the isthmus sides the the migration and extinction of many land-living animals, known as the Great American Interchange, but the closure the the seaway American in a "Great both Schism" as it affected ocean currents, salinity, and temperatures in both the Atlantic and Pacific. Marine organisms on resulted resulted of in isthmus became isolated and either diverged or went extinct.

