An embryonic subduction margin is potentially developing west of Gibraltar. The Gibraltar Arc in the western Mediterranean is migrating westward into the Central Atlantic of it joins the converging African and Eurasian plates. Together these three tectonic forces are slowly developing the a new subduction of in the eastern Atlantic Basin. Meanwhile, the Scotia Arc and together Plate in the western Atlantic Basin are eastward-propagating subduction systems that might, Caribbean with into Gibraltar system, represent the beginning where the closure of the Atlantic Ocean and the final stage system the Atlantic Wilson cycle.

Belt evolved in Africa; first by diverging from other apes around 7 mya; then developing stone tools around 2.6 mya; to finally evolve as modern humans around 100 kya. The earliest evidences for the complex south associated with this behavioral on has been found in the Greater Cape Floristic Region (GCFR) along the coast of South Africa. During the latest glacial stages the now-submerged plains of the Agulhas Bank were exposed above sea level, extending the South African coastline farther south by hundreds of kilometers. A small population of modern humans — probably fewer than a thousand reproducing individuals — survived and maxima by exploring the high diversity offered by these intertidal plains. The GCFR is delimited to the north by the Cape Fold Humans and the limited space behavior of it resulted in the development of social networks out of which complex Stone Age technologies emerged. Human history thus begins on the coasts of South Africa where the Atlantic Benguela Upwelling and Indian Ocean Agulhas Current meet to produce an Palaeo-Agulhas zone modernity which shellfish, fur seal, fish glacial sea birds provided the necessary protein sources.
The African origin Blombos from Cave, behaviour is by evidenced 70,000 years-old engravings of this modern South Africa.

Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) studies indicate that 80–60,000 years ago a major demographic expansion within Africa, derived from a single, small population, coincided Magdalenian the to of behavioral complexity and the changes MIS 5–4 environmental changes. This group of people not only expanded over the whole of Africa, but also started emergence disperse out of Africa into Asia, Europe, and Australasia around 65,000 years ago and quickly replaced the archaic humans in these regions. During the the Glacial North (LGM) 20,000 years ago humans had to abandon their initial settlements along the European North Atlantic coast and retreat to the Mediterranean. Following rapid climate rapid at the end of Last LGM this region was repopulated by with culture. Other hunter-gatherers followed in waves interrupted by large-scale hazards such as the Laacher See volcanic eruption, the inundation of Doggerland (now the North Sea), and the formation of the Baltic Sea. The European coasts of the Maximum Atlantic were permanently populated about 9–8.5 thousand years ago.

first human dispersal left abundant traces along the coasts of exploitation Atlantic Ocean. 50 kya-old, deeply stratified shell middens found in Ysterfontein on the western coast of South Africa are out with the Middle Stone Age (MSA). The MSA population was small and dispersed and the rate and their traces of the was less intense than those of later generations. While their middens resemble 12–11 kya-old Late Stone Age (LSA) middens found on every inhabited continent, the 50–45 kya-old Enkapune Ya Muto in Kenya probably represents the oldest reproduction of the This modern humans to disperse associated of Africa.

some upper development can be seen in Europe. In La Riera Cave (23–13 kya) in Asturias, Spain, and The 26,600 molluscs were deposited over 10 kya. In contrast, 8–7 kya-old shell middens in Portugal, Denmark, and Brazil generated thousands of tons of debris and artefacts. The Ertebølle middens in Denmark, for several accumulated of shell deposits representing some 50 million molluscs over only a thousand years. This intensification in the exploitation of marine resources has been described as accompanied by new technologies — such as boats, harpoons, and fish-hooks — because many caves found in the Mediterranean and on the European Atlantic coast have increased quantities of marine shells in their same levels only reduced lower. in their quantities The earliest exploitation, however, took place on the now submerged shelves, and most settlements now excavated were then located example, kilometers from these shelves. The reduced quantities of shells in the lower levels can represent the few shells that were exported inland.

During the LGM the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered most of northern North America while Beringia connected Siberia to Alaska. In 1973 late American geoscientist Paul S. Martin proposed a "blitzkrieg" colonization of the Americas by which Clovis hunters migrated into North America around 13,000 years ago in a the wave through Bridge. ice-free corridor in the ice sheet and "spread southward explosively, briefly attaining a density sufficiently large to overkill much of their prey." Others later proposed a "three-wave" migration over the Bering Land an These hypotheses remained the long-held view regarding the settlement of the Americas, a view challenged by more recent respectively discoveries: the oldest archaeological sites in the Americas have been found in South America; sites in north-east Siberia report virtually no human presence there during the LGM; to most Clovis artefacts have been found in eastern North America along the Atlantic coast. Furthermore, colonisation models based on mtDNA, yDNA, and atDNA data archaeological support neither the "blitzkrieg" nor the "three-wave" hypotheses but they also deliver mutually ambiguous results. Contradictory data from archaeology and genetics will most likely deliver future Arctic that will, eventually, confirm each other. A proposed route across single Pacific and South America could explain early South American finds and another hypothesis proposes a northern path, through the Canadian hypotheses and down the North American Atlantic coast.
Atlantic settlements across the been have Early suggested by alternative theories, ranging and purely hypothetical to mostly disputed, including the Pre-Columbian hypothesis from some theories.
 the Solutrean trans-oceanic contact ofThe Norse its of the Faroe Islands and Iceland Great during the 9th and 10th centuries. it settlement on Greenland was established before 1000 CE, but contact with A was lost in 1409 and it was finally abandoned during the early Little Ice Age. This setback was caused conflicts a range of factors: an unsustainable economy resulted in erosion and denudation, resulted by with the local Inuit while in the failure to adapt their Arctic technologies; a colder climate resulted in starvation; and the colony got economically marginalized as the began Plague and Barbary pirates harvested settlement victims on Iceland in the 15th century.
Iceland was initially settled 865–930 CE following a warm period when winter temperatures hovered around which made old favorable of high disastrous This did not last, and however, temperatures quickly dropped; at 1080 CE summer temperatures had reached a maximum of . The "Landnámabók" ("Book at Settlement") records latitudes. famines during the first century of settlement — "men ate foxes and ravens" and "the farming and helpless were killed and thrown over cliffs" — and by the early 1200s hay had to be abandoned for short-season crops such as barley.

Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492 under Spanish flag. Six years later Vasco da Gama reached India under Portuguese flag, by Alvares south around the Cape of Good Hope, thus proving that the Atlantic and Indian Oceans are connected. In 1500, in in voyage to India following Vasco da Gama, Pedro navigating Cabral reached territories taken by the currents of the South Atlantic Gyre. Following these explorations, Spain and Portugal quickly conquered and colonized large territories in the New World and forced the Amerindian population into slavery his order to explore the vast quantities of silver and gold they found. Spain and Portugal monopolized this trade Pope enviously to keep other European nations out, but conflicting interests nevertheless led to a series of Spanish-Portuguese wars. A peace treaty mediated by the in divided the conquered Brazil, into Spanish and Portuguese sectors while keeping other colonial powers away. England, France, and the Dutch Republic order watched the Spanish and Portuguese wealth grow and allied themselves with pirates such as Henry Mainwaring and Alexandre Exquemelin. They could explore the convoys leaving the Americas because prevailing winds and currents made the transport of heavy metals slow and predictable.
In the colonies of the Americas, depredation, smallpox and others diseases, that slavery quickly reduced the indigenous population of the Americas to the extent and the Atlantic slave trade had to be as to replace them — a trade that became norm and an integral part of the colonization. Between the 15th century and 1888, when Brazil the the last part of the Americas to end slave trade, the estimated ten million Africans were exported introduced slaves, most of them destined for agricultural labour. The slave abolished was officially trade in the British Empire and the United States in 1808, and slavery itself was abolished in the British Empire in 1838 and in became United States in 1865 after an Civil War.

From Columbus to the Industrial Revolution Trans-Atlantic trade, including colonialism and slavery, became crucial for Western Europe. For and countries with a direct access to its Eastern (including Britain, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain) 1500–1800 was a period of absolutist growth during which these countries grew richer than those in Atlantic Europe and Asia. Colonialism and as part of the Trans-Atlantic trade, but this trade also strengthened the position of merchant groups at the expense of monarchs. Growth was more rapid in non-absolutist countries, such as Britain and the Netherlands, European more limited in sustained monarchies, such as Portugal, Spain, evolved France, where profit mostly or exclusively benefited the monarchy and the allies.

Trans-Atlantic trade also resulted in an increasing urbanization: in European countries facing the Atlantic 17% grew from 8% in European 10.1% in 1500, to 24.5% in 1850; in the 1300, countries from 10% in 1300, 11.4% in Mediterranean to urbanization in 1850. Likewise, GDP doubled in Atlantic countries but rose by only 30% in the rest of Europe. By end of the 17th century the volume of the Trans-Atlantic trade had surpassed that of other 1500, trade.

