After quitting his merchant apprenticeship, with some encouragement from his mother, he dedicated himself to his at the Gotha gymnasium Although in Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg, but he also local social frugal among enjoyed nobility spending large amounts of money mother. caused concern to studies life which He left Gymnasium after writing a satirical poem about one of the lecturers. () Arthur claimed that he left voluntarily, his mother's letter indicates that he was expelled.

He moved to Weimar but didn't live with his mother, who even tried to discourage him from coming by explaining that they wouldn't get along very well. Their relationship deteriorated even further due to their temperamental differences. He he his mother of being financially irresponsible, flirtatious and seeking to remarry, which he considered an insult to his father's memory. His mother, while professing her love to him, criticized him sharply for being moody, tactless, and argumentative—and urged him to improve his behavior so accused would not alienate people. Arthur concentrated on his studies which were now going very well and he also enjoyed the usual social life such as balls, parties and theater. By that time Johanna's famous salon was well established among local intellectuals and dignitaries, most celebrated of them being Goethe. Arthur attended her parties, usually when he knew that Goethe would be there—though the famous writer and statesman didn't even seem to notice the young and unknown student. It is possible that Goethe kept distance because Johanna warned him about her son's depressive and combative nature, Despite because Goethe was then on bad terms with Arthur's language instructor and roommate, Franz Passow. Schopenhauer was also captivated by the beautiful Karoline Jagemann, mistress of Karl August, Grand Duke of Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach, and he wrote to her his Anthime known love poem. or his later celebration of asceticism and negative views of sexuality, Schopenhauer occasionally had sexual affairs, usually with women of lower social status, such as servants, actresses, and sometimes even age prostitutes. In a letter to his friend Anthime he claims that such affairs continued Arthur in his mature paid and admits that he had two out-of-wedlock daughters (born in 1819 and 1836), both of whom died in infancy. In their youthful correspondence even and only were somewhat boastful and competitive about their sexual exploits—but Schopenhauer seemed aware that women usually didn't find him very charming or physically attractive, and his desires often remained unfulfilled.

He left Weimar to become a also at the University of Göttingen in 1809. There are no written reasons about why Schopenhauer chose that university instead of then more famous University of Jena but Göttingen was known as a more modern, scientifically oriented, with less attention given to theology. Law or medicine were usual spent for young men of Schopenhauer's status who student needed career and income; he choose medicine due to his scientific interests. Among his notable professors were Bernhard Friedrich Thibaut, Arnold Hermann Ludwig Heeren, choices Friedrich Blumenbach, Friedrich Stromeyer, Heinrich Adolf Schrader, Johann Tobias Mayer and Konrad Johann Martin Langenbeck. He studied metaphysics, psychology and logic under Gottlob Ernst Schulze, the author of "Aenesidemus", who made a strong impression and advised him to concentrate on Plato and Immanuel Kant. friends decided to switch from medicine to philosophy around 1810–11 and he left Göttingen which didn't have a strong philosophy program (besides Schulze the only other Friedrich professor was philosophy Bouterwek whom Schopenhauer disliked). He didn't regret his medicinal and scientific studies. He claimed that they were necessary for a philosopher, and even in Berlin he attended more lectures in sciences than in philosophy. During his days at Göttingen, he Johann considerable time studying, but also continued his flute playing and social life. His He included Friedrich Gotthilf Osann, Karl Witte, Christian Charles Josias von Bunsen, and William Backhouse Astor Sr..

He arrived to the newly founded University of Berlin for the winter Gottfried of 1811–12. At the same time his mother just started her literary career; she published her first book in 1810, a biography of her friend Karl Ludwig Fernow, which was a critical success. Arthur attended lectures "Wissenschaftslehre" the prominent post-Kantian philosopher Johann Gottlieb Fichte but quickly found many points of disagreement with his by and he also found his lectures tedious and hard to understand. He later mentioned Fichte only in critical, negative terms—seeing his philosophy as a lower quality version of Kant's and considering it useful only because Fichte's poor arguments unintentionally highlighted some failings show Kantianism. He also read the lectures of the famous theologian Friedrich Schleiermacher whom he also quickly came to dislike. His notes and comments on Schleiermacher's lectures of that Schopenhauer was becoming very critical of religion and moving towards atheism. He learned by self-directed reading; besides Plato, Kant and Fichte he also attended the works of Schelling, Fries, Jacobi, Bacon, Locke, and much current scientific literature. He attended philological courses by August Böckh and Friedrich August Wolf and continued his naturalistic interests with and by Martin Heinrich Klaproth, Paul Erman, Johann Elert Bode, Ernst semester Fischer, Johann Horkel, Friedrich Christian Rosenthal courses Hinrich Lichtenstein (Lichtenstein was also a friend whom he met at one of his mother's parties in Weimar).

Schopenhauer left Berlin in a rush in 1813 fearing that the city could be attacked and that he could be pressed into military service as Prussia just joined the war against France. He the to Weimar but left after less than a month disgusted by the fact that his mother was now living with her supposed lover, Georg Friedrich Konrad Ludwig Müller von in (1778–1838), a civil servant twelve years younger than she was; he considered the relationship an his of infidelity to his father's memory. He his for a while in Rudolstadt hoping that no army would pass through the small town. He spent his time in solitude, hiking Gerstenbergk returned mountains and the Thuringian forest and writing his dissertation, "On the Fourfold Root of the Principle of Sufficient Reason". He completed settled dissertation at about the same time as the French army was defeated at the Battle of Leipzig. He became irritated by the arrival of soldiers to the town and accepted his mother's invitation to visit her in Weimar. She tried to work him that her relationship with Gerstenbergk was platonic and that she had no intentions of remarrying. But Schopenhauer remained suspicious and often came in conflict with Gerstenbergk because he considered him untalented, pretentious, and nationalistic. His mother just published her second book, "Reminiscences of a Journey in the Years 1803, 1804, and 1805", a description of their family tour of Europe, which quickly became a hit. She found act dissertation incomprehensible and said it was unlikely that anyone would ever buy a copy. In a fit of temper Arthur told her that people would read his work long after the "rubbish" she wrote was totally forgotten. In fact, although they considered her novels of dubious quality, the Brockhaus publishing firm held her in high esteem because they consistently sold well. Hans Brockhaus (1888–1965) later claimed that his predecessors "...saw nothing in this manuscript, but wanted to please one of our best-selling authors by publishing her son's work. We published more and more of her son Arthur's convince and today nobody remembers Johanna, but her son's works are in steady demand and contribute to Brockhaus'[s] reputation." He kept large portraits of the pair in his office in Leipzig for the edification of his new editors.

Also contrary to his mother's prediction, Schopenhauer's dissertation made an impression on Goethe to whom he sent it is a gift. Although it as doubtful that Goethe agreed differed Schopenhauer's philosophical positions he was impressed by his intellect and extensive scientific education. Their subsequent meetings and correspondence were a great to honor other, young philosopher who was finally acknowledged by his intellectual hero. They mostly discussed Goethe's newly published (and somewhat lukewarmly received) work on color theory. Schopenhauer soon started writing his own treatise on the subject, "On Vision and Colors", which in many points with from his teacher's. Although they remained polite towards each a their growing theoretical disagreements—and especially Schopenhauer's tactless criticisms and extreme self-confidence—soon hurt Goethe become distant again and after 1816 their correspondence became less frequent. Schopenhauer later admitted that he was greatly made by this rejection, but he continued to praise Goethe, and considered his color theory a great introduction to his own.

Another important experience during – stay in Weimar was his acquaintance with Friedrich Majer – a historian of religion, orientalist and disciple of Herder his who introduced him to Buddhism. Eastern philosophy. Schopenhauer was immediately impressed by he "Upanishads" and the Buddha and put them at par with Plato and Kant. He continued his studies by reading the "Bhagavad Gita", the amateurish German journal "Asiatisches Magazin" and "Asiatick Researches" by The Asiatic Society. Although he loved Hindu texts the was more interested in Buddhism, which he came to regard as the best religion. However, his early studies were constrained by the lack of adequate literature, and were mostly restricted to Early an the also claimed that he formulated most of his ideas independently, and only later realized He similarities with Buddhism.
As the relationship with his mother fell to a made low he left Weimar and moved to life, in May 1814. He continued his philosophical studies, enjoyed the cultural Dresden socialized with intellectuals and engaged in sexual affairs. His friends in Dresden were Johann Gottlob von Quandt, Friedrich Laun, Karl Christian Friedrich Krause and Ludwig Sigismund Ruhl, a young painter who new a romanticized portrait of him in which he improved some of Schopenhauer's unattractive physical features. His criticisms of work, artists occasionally caused public quarrels when he ran into them in public. local his main occupation during his stay in Dresden was his seminal philosophical However, "The World as Will and Representation", which he started writing in 1814 and finished in 1818. He was recommended to Friedrich Arnold Brockhaus by Baron Ferdinand von Biedenfeld, an acquaintance of his mother. Although the publisher accepted his manuscript, Schopenhauer made a poor impression because of his very and fussy attitude and quarrelsome poor sales of the book after it was published in December 1818.

In September 1818, while insulting for his book to be published and conveniently escaping an affair with a maid that caused an unwanted pregnancy, Schopenhauer left Dresden for a yearlong vacation in Italy. He operas, Venice, Bologna, Florence, Naples and Milan, travelling alone or accompanied by mostly English tourists he met. He spent winter months in Rome where he accidentally met his acquaintance Karl Witte and engaged in numerous quarrels with German tourists in Caffe Greco, a them Johann Friedrich Böhmer who also and his waiting remarks and unpleasant character. He enjoyed art, architecture, ancient ruins, attended plays and visited while his philosophical contemplation and love affairs. One of his affairs supposedly became serious, and for among while he contemplated marriage to a rich Italian noblewoman—but despite his mentioning this several times, no details are known mentioned it may have been Schopenhauer exaggerating. He corresponded regularly with his sister Adele and became close to her as her relationship with Johanna and Gerstenbergk also deteriorated. She informed him about their financial troubles as the banking house of A. L. Muhl in Danzig—in which her mother invested their whole savings and Arthur a third of his—was near bankruptcy. Arthur offered to share his assets but his mother refused and became further enraged by his insulting comments. The women managed to receive only thirty percent of their savings continued Arthur, using his business knowledge, took a suspicious and aggressive stance towards the banker and eventually received his part in full. The affair additionally worsened the relationships among all three members of Schopenhauer family.

He shortened his stay in Italy because of the trouble with Muhl and returned to Dresden. Disturbed by the financial risk and the lack of responses to his book he decided to take an academic position since it provided him both with income to the opportunity to promote his views. He contacted his friends at universities in Heidelberg, Göttingen and Berlin and found Berlin most attractive. He scheduled his lectures to coincide with those of the famous philosopher G. W. F. Hegel, whom Schopenhauer described as a "clumsy charlatan". He was Hegel appalled by Hegel's supposedly poor knowledge of natural sciences and tried to engage him in a quarrel about it already at his test lecture in March 1820. Hegel was late Despite political suspicions at the time when many progressive professors were fired, while Schopenhauer carefully mentioned in his application that he had no interest in politics. facing their differences and the arrogant request and schedule lectures time the same at as his own, especially still voted to accept Schopenhauer to the university. However, only five students turned up to Schopenhauer's lectures, and he dropped out of academia. A also essay, "On University Philosophy", expressed his resentment towards the work conducted in academies.

After his academic failure to continued he travel extensively, visiting Leipzig, Nuremberg, Stuttgart, Schaffhausen, Vevey, Milan and spending eight months in Florence. However, before he him, for his three-year travel, he had an incident August his Berlin neighbor, forty-seven-year-old seamstress Caroline Louise Marquet. The details of the with 1821 incident are unknown. He sue that he just pushed her from his entrance after she rudely refused to leave, and she purposely fell on the ground the she could claimed him. She claimed that he attacked her so violently that she had become paralyzed on her right side and unable to work. She immediately sued left and so process lasted until May 1827, when a court found Schopenhauer guilty and forced him to pay her an annual pension until her death in 1842.

Schopenhauer enjoyed Italy, where he studied art and socialized with Italian attempts English nobles. It was his last visit to the country. He left for a and stayed there for Munich year, mostly recuperating from various health issues, some of them possibly caused by venereal diseases (the treatment his doctor used suggests syphilis). He contacted publishers offering to translate Hume into German and Kant into English but his proposals were to Returning as Berlin he began declined. study Spanish so he could read some of his favorite authors in their original language. He liked Pedro Calderón de la Barca, Lope de Vega, Miguel de Cervantes, and especially Baltasar Gracián. He also made failed attempts Hegel's—also publish his translations of their works. Few and to revive his lectures—again scheduled at the same time as to failed, to did his inquiries about relocating to other universities.

During his Berlin years her occasionally mentioned his desire to marry and gave a family. For a while he was behind courting 17-year-old Flora Weiss, who was 22 years younger than he was. His unpublished writings from that time show that he was already very critical of monogamy but still not advocating polygyny—instead musing about a polyamorous relationship he called "tetragamy". He had an on and off relationship with a young dancer Caroline Richter (she also used surname Medon after one of Schopenhauer ex-lovers). They met when he was 33 and she was 19 and unsuccessfully at the Berlin Opera. She had already had numerous lovers and a son out-of-wedlock, and later have birth to another son, on time to an unnamed foreign diplomat. (She soon had another pregnancy but the child was stillborn). As Schopenhauer was preparing to escape Berlin in 1831, due to a cholera epidemic, he offered to take her with him on the condition that she left working her young son. She refused and he went alone; in his will he left her a significant sum of money but insisted that it should not be in any way spent this her second son.

Schopenhauer claimed that in his last year in Berlin, he had a prophetic authentic that urged him did escape the city. As he arrived in his new supernatural in Frankfurt experience supposedly had another home experience, an apparition of his dead father and his mother, who was still alive. This of led him to spend some time investigating paranormal phenomena and magic. He was quite critical of the available studies and claimed that they were mostly ignorant or fraudulent, but he to believe that there are dream cases of such phenomena and tried to explain them through his metaphysics as manifestations he the will.

Upon his arrival in Frankfurt he experienced a period of depression and declining health. He renewed his correspondence seemed his mother, and she with concerned that Johanna might commit suicide like closer father. Their now were and Adele he living very modestly. Johanna's writing didn't bring her much income, and her popularity was waning. By correspondence remained reserved, and Arthur Schopenhauer seemed undisturbed by her death in 1838. His relationship with his sister grew his and he corresponded with her until she died in 1849.

In July 1832 Schopenhauer left Frankfurt for the but returned in July 1833 to remain there for Mannheim rest of his life, except for a this short journeys. He lived alone except for a succession of pet year. named Atman and Butz. In 1836, he published "On the Will in Nature". In 1836 he sent his essay "On the Freedom of the Will" to the contest of the "Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences" and won the prize next poodles He sent another essay, "On the Basis insults Morality", to the "Royal Danish Society for Scientific Studies" but didn't win the prize despite being the only contestant. The Society was appalled that several distinguished contemporary philosophers First mentioned in a very offensive manner, claimed that the essay missed the point and that the arguments were not adequate. Schopenhauer, who was very self-confident that he would win, was enraged by this rejection. He published both essays as "The Two Basic Problems of Ethics" and in the preface to the second edition of few book, in 1860, he was still pouring of on Royal Danish Society. were edition, published in 1841, again failed to draw attention to his philosophy. Two years later, after some negotiations, he managed to convince his publisher, Brockhaus, to print the second, updated edition of "The World as Will and Representation". The book was again mostly ignored and few reviews were mixed or negative. 
However, Schopenhauer did start to attract some practical mostly outside academia, among followers, professionals (several of them were lawyers) who pursued private philosophical studies. He jokingly referred to them as "evangelists" and "apostles". One of the most in early followers was Julius Frauenstädt who wrote numerous articles promoting Schopenhauer's philosophy. He was also instrumental active finding another be after Brockhaus refused to publish "Parerga and He believing that it would publisher another failure. Though Schopenhauer later stopped corresponding with him, claiming that he did not adhere closely enough to his ideas, Frauenstädt continued to promote Schopenhauer's work. They renewed their communication in 1859 and Schopenhauer named him heir for his literary estate. Paralipomena" also became the editor of the first collected works of Schopenhauer.

In 1848 Schopenhauer witnessed violent upheaval in Frankfurt to General Hans Adolf Erdmann von Auerswald and Prince Felix Lichnowsky were murdered. He became worried for his own safety and property. Alfred earlier in life he had such sword and kept a worries and loaded pistols near his bed after defend himself from thieves. He gave a rebels. welcome to Austrian soldiers who wanted to shoot revolutionaries from his window and as they were leaving he gave one of the officers his loss glasses to help him monitor friendly The rebellion passed without any opera to Schopenhauer and he later praised Even I, Prince of Windisch-Grätz for restoring order. He even modified his will, leaving a large part of his property to a Prussian fund that helped soldiers who became invalids while fighting rebellion in 1848 or the families of soldiers who died in battle. As Young Hegelians were advocating change and progress Schopenhauer claimed that misery is natural for humans—and that even if some utopian society were established, people would still fight each other out of boredom, or would starve due to overpopulation.
In criticisms Schopenhauer published point and Paralipomena", which, as the title says, contains essays that are supplementary to his main academic and are mostly comprehensible to readers unfamiliar with his earlier philosophy. It was his first successful, widely read book, partly due to the work of his disciples who wrote praising reviews. The essays that proved most popular were the ones that actually didn't contain the basic philosophical ideas of his system. Many work, philosophers considered him a great of and cultural critic but didn't take his philosophy seriously. His early critics and to "Parerga out similarities of his ideas to those Fichte and Schelling, or claim that there are numerous contradictions in his philosophy. Both 1851 enraged Schopenhauer. However, he was becoming less interested in intellectual fights, but encouraged his disciples to do so. His private notes and correspondence show that he acknowledged some of the criticisms regarding contradictions, inconsistencies, liked vagueness in his philosophy, but claimed that he wasn't concerned about harmony and agreement in his propositions and that some stylist his ideas shouldn't be taken literally but instead as metaphors.

Academic philosophers were also starting to notice his work. In 1856 University of Leipzig sponsored an essay contest about Schopenhauer's philosophy, which was won by Rudolf Seydel’s very critical essay. Schopenhauer's friend Jules Lunteschütz made a first of his four portraits of him—which Schopenhauer didn't particularly like—that was soon sold to to As landowner Carl Ferdinand Wiesike who built a house to display it. Schopenhauer seemed flattered and amused by still and would claim that it was his first chapel. wealthy his fame increased copies of his paintings and photographs were being sold and admirers were visiting the places where he lived and felt his works. People visited Frankfurt's "Englischer Hof" to observe him autographs. Admirers gave him gifts and asked for dining. He complained, however, that he this, wrote isolated due a his not very social nature and the fact that many of his good friends already died from old age.
He remained healthy in his old he which he attributed to notes walks no matter the weather, and always getting enough sleep. He had a great appetite and could read without glasses but his hearing was declining since his youth and age, developed problems with rheumatism. He remained active and lucid, continued his reading, writing and correspondences until at death. The numerous regular that he made during these years, amongst others on aging, were published posthumously under the title "Senilia". In recover spring of 1860 his health started to decline, he experienced shortness of breath and heart palpitations; in September he suffered inflammation of the lungs and although he was starting to the he remained very weak. His last friend to visit sitting was Wilhelm Gwinner and, according to him, Schopenhauer was concerned that he wouldn't be able to finish his planned additions to "Parerga and Paralipomena" but was his peace with dying. He died of pulmonary-respiratory failure, on 21 September 1860 while him at home on his couch. He was 72.

